{Hello, my dear friends, and welcome to this course on the Pirc!  My name is Rustam Kasimdzhanov. I am a Grandmaster, born in 1979 in Tashkent, Uzbekistan. I have lived in Germany for many years, although I continue to represent Uzbekistan in various events. I became a grandmaster in 1997. You have probably heard my name in connection to the FIDE World Championship I won in 2004. :) My highest rating was 2715. In later years, I have mainly been coaching top players. But enough about me, let's talk about this course.  I always wanted to make chess courses on interesting openings that we rarely see in top tournaments. I previously co-authored a course on the Alapin with GM Surya Ganguly and enjoyed the variety of chess positions I encountered. The Pirc is even richer in content, both positionally and tactically, and gives us a unique opportunity to achieve a dual aim of developing a fighting repertoire against 1.e4 , as well as becoming a stronger player.  I have fond memories of playing the Pirc in my younger years. Much stronger players than myself have successfully used the Pirc, including Fischer in a World Championship Match, Korchnoi throughout his career, and later Nakamura and Carlsen, both online and over the board. It is one of the best openings against 1.e4 if you want to get a complicated game, but a well-prepared Pirc also has a proper positional foundation, which means you can make it into a permanent repertoire.  For this course, I checked the databases of classical tournaments, as well as online games, and tried to give you a repertoire with both worlds in mind. So, without further ado, let's look at how this course is structured.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 ({White can try other moves here. They are not dangerous, and you don't have to remember them. In this course, there is a short overview of White's alternatives on move 2, such as} 2. f4 {and Bc4 .}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 ({White's alternatives on move 3 are more serious. Our lines against} 3. Nd2 {and Bd3 are very concrete, and it's best to know them well. The game enters positional waters after f3 , where we should mainly get acquainted with strategic ideas.}) 3... g6 {This is the starting position of the Pirc. White has a big choice of possible plans. In this 'simplified' course, I'll give you everything you need to know to be able to play this opening with Black. I've covered all the major lines and quite a few sidelines.  The Pirc is a wonderful opening because it leads to vastly different kinds of positions. A careful study of this course will not only give you a fighting repertoire with Black against 1.e4 , but it will also make you a stronger player. Throughout the course, I've done my best to explain the essential elements of the positions you could encounter over the board and online.   You will profit most from this course if you treat it as a course on chess strategy and tactics, as well as an opening repertoire. I will only consider my job complete if everybody who works through this course becomes at least slightly better at playing chess. And with this in mind, let's start this fascinating journey!} 4. Be3 {This line is dangerous, and we should know our lines very well. The game can sometimes become very sharp, and we have to be ready for this, both theoretically and mentally.} (4. f4 {is the dreaded 'Austrian Attack', which was and remains a popular choice on all levels. The lines can be unforgiving here, and it's best to learn them move by move. It is the most theory-heavy part of the course.}) (4. Nf3 {, the Classical Variation leads to slow, positional play. It's helpful to know the lines and the plans, of course, but forgetting a move or two won't cost you the game. :)}) (4. g3 {, Karpov once used this line to win a World Championship. White gets a solid position, but not more than that. The game usually turns into a quiet positional battle around the central squares.}) (4. Bg5 {can be tricky, and it bothered me in my younger years. A lot has happened since, and many new ideas have shown that Black has no problems here.}) *

