1. e4 d6 {Here, we'll take a very brief look at all sorts of early sidelines. The brevity of our attention is explained by the fact that, technically, all these lines are not part of the Pirc, so it's more of an overview than anything else.} 2. f4 {This is a pretty popular way of playing. It will likely transpose to the Austrian Attack.} Nf6 {Our moves remain the same. White should now stop to cover the e4 -pawn.} 3. Nc3 {White could also play the last two moves in a different order.} g6 {We stick with the Pirc. White can transpose to the Austrian Attack anytime now by playing d4 .} 4. Nf3 {White avoids the Austrian Attack for now. If they were ever willing to play d4 , this would have happened on move 2. :)} Bg7 {Black sticks with the plan. White has the last chance to return to the well-known theory.} 5. Bc4 ({This is the most popular move. White could play} 5. d4 {instead, which transposes , but by now, we know this was never the plan. :)}) 5... Nxe4 {Throughout this course, I have been trying to go for direct continuations. This little combination gives Black a promising position.} 6. Bxf7+ {It is the only way to make sense of White's setup. White gets an unbalanced position, but it's not without risks.} Kxf7 7. Nxe4 {Black has a pair of strong bishops, but our king isn't perfectly safe. The next move takes care of that.} Rf8 {This is a well-known, elegant way to castle. Once Black plays ... Kg8 , the king will be comfy.} 8. O-O {Seeing as there is nothing to do to prevent Black from playing ... Kg8 , White castles and gets their king to safety.} Kg8 {This completes Black's maneuver. The king is safe now, and the black bishops are alive and well. We're looking forward to a fight with mutual chances.} *

