1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 ({This move is an invitation to play a King's Indian Defense after g6} 3. c4 {, etc. Black has many possible setups. I will give you one of the solid ones.}) 3... e5 {Whenever possible, we choose a central strategy. Not just in this opening, of course – it is more of a general principle. The endgames are not dangerous for Black.} 4. Ne2 {White tries to avoid early decision-making. Given enough time, they will proceed with c4 and Nbc3 . Black, however, has a way of causing trouble in the meantime.} exd4 {It's the beginning of a sharp sequence. The white king turns out to be more vulnerable than White would have liked. The f3 -pawn comes with all sorts of problems.} 5. Nxd4 {Taking the pawn with the queen would have been strange, although I can imagine some players attracted to the Qd4 - f2 maneuver.} d5 {It is the continuation of Black's idea. White's moves are surprisingly forced.} 6. e5 {Everything else would have left White with a weakness in the center of the board. The game is becoming sharp.} Nh5 {You are not supposed to place the knight on the edge of the board, but all the rules come with exceptions. This knight helps Black win a vital tempo by creating a deadly threat with ... Qh4 +.} 7. g3 {Black's threat is quite unpleasant, and White is wise to prevent it once and for all with this move.} c5 {Black starts the expansion in the center. With the powerful pawn center and easy development, our position is already easier to play. The h5 -knight doesn't do much at the moment but can be brought back into the game by playing ... g6 and ... Ng7 . It's a pretty unpractical line for White, and they probably should have chosen one of the other lines on move 4.} *

