1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Qd2 {The logical follow-up to 4.Bg5 and a very popular choice. White hasn't committed the f-pawn yet and keeps things flexible. Somewhat surprisingly, it leads to quiet, positional play.} h6 {I like this move best, preventing Bh6 once and for all. Now White has a choice.} 6. Bh4 {To me, this move looks like White's most natural reply. In a way, it's also the most consistent. You play 4.Bg5 if you think that the h4 - d8 -diagonal has some potential, and then you might stick around for a while. :)} g5 {Well, I like following clear plans. Black hunts the white bishop down, hoping that the dark-squared bishop will become a monster (in a good way) in the absence of the main rival.} 7. Bg3 Nh5 {Weakening our position with g5 only makes sense because we catch the bishop. We certainly have some long-term issues on the kingside, but we also have the g7 -bishop reigning supreme on the dark squares.} 8. O-O-O {This is the most popular move. White castles before committing to anything else, especially because Black can't do the same. Black's kingside is no longer a safe place for the king, and, for now, it will have to stay in the center. Fortunately, the position is closed, and Black can afford the luxury of slowly preparing the queenside castling.} Nd7 {Not only a good developing move but also a positional threat. Given time, Black will go ... c5 , opening the long diagonal. This is a threat that White should take seriously.} 9. Be2 {This forces Black to take on g3 and clarify the situation on the kingside. It doesn't prevent Black's play with ... c5 , however.} Nxg3 {Taking on g3 is a forced move, but it is also an achievement. Black waited with the knight on h5 long enough to provoke 9.Be2 , which is not the most dangerous move.} 10. hxg3 {An automatic move, almost invariably chosen, online and over the board. Taking with the other pawn has some positional ground, given that the f7 -pawn is potentially weak, but White doesn't get the time to do anything active after Black plays ... c5 .} c5 {Black gets a dream version of a Sicilian Dragon here. We have a pair of bishops and chances to create an attack against the white king, clearly not an outcome White can be happy with.} *

