1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bc4 {This move has become very popular in recent decades. It always feels nice to develop the bishop to such an active square, but the move also has drawbacks. The bishop can be vulnerable on c4 due to tricks like ... Nxe4 followed by ... d5 .} ({At other times, the bishop is sorely missed along the h5 - d1 diagonal, with the potential ... Bg4 becoming unpleasant. All in all,} 5. Bc4 {is an important move to know, but not a dangerous one.}) 5... O-O {Throughout this course, our strategy remains unchanged. Whenever possible, we bring the king into safety first and then think about what to do later. Now that we have defended the f7 -pawn, ... Nxe4 becomes a serious possibility.} 6. Bg5 {This is one of those active-looking moves that don't really do anything. Most importantly, White does not address the threat of ... Nxe4 .} Nxe4 {Now that we have castled and the f7 -pawn is protected, this trick works very nicely.} 7. Nxe4 ({Since} 7. Bxf7+ {would have left Black with a pair of powerful bishops White has no choice but to recapture the knight.}) 7... d5 {This move, of course, is the point of Black's little combination. White cannot save the extra piece and must choose which one to give back.} 8. Bd3 {There is really no choice but to retreat. Anything else would have left Black with two strong bishops and an advantage.} dxe4 9. Bxe4 {This is the end of the short forced sequence. The white king is still in the center, and this makes it easier for Black to start the play in the center of the board.} c5 {White has numerous weaknesses along the long diagonal, and it's very natural for Black to try to open it up. With the white king still in the center and the pieces in some disarray, White will have to tread carefully in order not to get a bad position from the opening.  Essentially, White should have castled on move 6 to get a better version of this type of position. The g5 -bishop is not great and would have been better deployed elsewhere, defending the b2 or the d4 -pawns.} *

