1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. d5 {This move is played sometimes, and it's probably good to be aware of it. Its problem is that White gets a bad version of the King's Indian Defense. The c2 -pawn should really be on c4 , as it is in the main line of KID. The c4 -pawn in KID is essential for expanding on the queenside with b4 and c5 . As things stand now, it will be difficult for White to find a plan.} Ne8 {As befits a very favorable version of the King's Indian Defense, Black has many promising continuations. I chose this one because it is very straightforward. Black intends to go ... f5 without delay.} 8. Bg5 {There are not many tournament games in this position. Online, most players seem to go for this move to provoke ... f6 . After anything else, Black would react in the same manner, ... f5 , and fight.} f6 {It is the simplest way. This pawn will not stay on f6 for very long. Now, White has a decision to make.} 9. Be3 ({This move essentially admits that Bg5 missed its mark. Playing} 9. Be3 {would have likely led to the same position.}) 9... f5 {We are continuing with the plan indicated by Ne8 . With a short delay, the pawn appeared on f5 and, given the chance, will gladly march further. White is not well-positioned to deal with a pawn storm on the kingside and has to do something about it.} 10. exf5 {White opens the position to stop Black's pawn storm on the kingside, but Black still retains some attacking chances. Two powerful pawns in the center of the board will be an asset.} ({Playing} 10. Bg5 {instead would likely end up in the same position as White cannot avoid taking on f5 sooner or later.}) 10... gxf5 {Taking on f5 with a bishop would certainly be a grave positional mistake, as it would abandon the e4 -square forever and lose all the attacking chances. Both sides should now be aware that the g-file has been opened, and Black is the only side likely to be able to use it to their advantage.} 11. Bg5 ({This bishop move is a natural way to deal with the threat of ... f4 . It's good to know that} 11. Ng5 {would have lost a piece to} f4 {. We all want to play a long, complex game of chess, but there's something nice about winning a piece in the opening. :)}) 11... Bf6 {This is the most typical way to parry White's threat, although both other reasonable moves, ... Nf6 and ... Qd7 are fully playable as well. Now the exchange of dark-squared bishops would be very profitable for Black. Our plan is simple, ... Kh8 , ... Rg8 , and get an attack on the kingside.  It's unclear where White would get any play since Black is stronger in the center and has no targets on the queenside. Realistically, White should probably look for the repetition of moves with Bh6 and Bg5 .} *

