1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. h4 ({A very popular resource these days in all sorts of positions,} 5. h4 {started giving Black some headaches in recent years. White threatens h5 , followed by a nice positional exchange sacrifice. Luckily, we have a very simple antidote.}) 5... h5 {Chess is a very simple game at times. Black prevents 6.h5 and asks White to show their plan. Interestingly, with h4 and ... h5 included, White's possible advances on the kingside are extremely limited.} 6. f3 {Sooner or later, White will need to prevent ... Ng4 . Also, it is by far the most popular move in practice.} c6 {A very flexible approach. Black keeps their king in the center for now and gets ready to roll the queenside pawns with the usual ... b5 and ... b4 . Having played h4 , White has limited options, and can only castle long, where the white king usually finds very little to be happy about. This also makes it more difficult for White to play a4 at any moment since that would leave White with no safe spot for their king whatsoever.} 7. Nh3 {Trying to take advantage of the newly weakened g5 -square. The white knight would be quite annoying on g5 , so it's best for Black to take some drastic measures.} Bxh3 {Once again, the simplest. No knight, no problem. And taking on h3 is a very fast way to finish development, too.} 8. Rxh3 {Not a happy place for a rook. One of these days, White will lose more time by having to move it back to find some use for this piece.} Nbd7 {Black finished developing their minor pieces and has a clear plan of pushing the b-pawn. White won't find this easy to handle, having a rook on h3 and hardly any useful pawn breaks. The white king will likely end up on c1 and, as often in this line, it's not a great place to be.} *

