1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. e6 {This is one of the three important tries that White has in this position. Since this is such a central position, we will cover each of them separately.} fxe6 ({I think this is by far the cleaner solution. We do need to know a few lines, but they all end very well for Black. The alternative,} 8... Bxb5 {, is much more messy.}) 9. Ng5 {This is the point of White's setup. The e6 -pawn and the g4 -knight are both hanging, and Black needs something truly spectacular to get out of this predicament alive. What happens now is one of the most famous opening discoveries in the history of chess.} Bxb5 {The beginning of a most majestic trick. Even now it's not easy to see that Black's counterplay is directed against the white king.} 10. Nxe6 {Do you know any opening positions where Black made nine moves and has three minor pieces and the queen hanging? I don't, and I wouldn't be surprised if this position is one-of-a-kind. Black's situation looks desperate, but it only takes one move to make everything right.} Bxd4 {Now this is most definitely a bolt from the blue. There is something undeniably beautiful in Black's minor pieces finding sudden harmony. With this move, we remind our opponent that there are things more valuable in chess than the queen. The only thing White can do now is choose between various ways to make a draw.} 11. Nxd8 {By taking the queen, White agrees to an immediate draw. There are some alternatives to this, but they're hardly more promising.} Bf2+ {The game ends in perpetual check here, and this happens as early as move 11. Undoubtedly, this cannot be considered an opening success for White. After this perpetual check was discovered, White was forced to look for options elsewhere. Should Black find themselves in a must-win situation, this line can still be employed, but with the alternative on move 8.} *

