1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. Bxd7+ ({The second most popular move, with} 8. e6 {being the critical continuation. White prefers not to engage in a complicated opening preparation and instead chooses a line that often leads to a more positional game. A slight drawback of this approach is that it doesn't cause many problems.}) 8... Qxd7 {As often before, we should take with the queen to cover the tactically vulnerable squares, e6 and g4 . Now, White has a choice between two very different systems.} 9. d5 {This is the main line. White changes the nature of the position by moving the pawn away from d4 and controlling the c6 -square. We will talk more about the nuances of the position once the situation is clarified somewhat.} dxe5 {Our play here and over the next couple of moves is quite forced. We cannot let White have such a powerful pawn center and should address this immediately.} 10. h3 {This move is the point behind the pawn sacrifice. By attacking the g4 -knight, White tries to restore two pawns on the 5th rank, and it would be a most unwelcome outcome for Black. Fortunately, we have a nice strategic resource.} e4 {An elegant positional solution to our problems. Now, instead of two powerful pawns on the 5th rank, White will get long-term weaknesses in the center.} 11. Nxe4 {This simple capture is probably White's best bet. The alternative is sometimes played but leads to too many weaknesses for my taste.} Nf6 {The knight proudly returns to f6 , having caused some havoc in White's position. The double attack on e4 and d5 forces White to react.} 12. Nxf6+ ({The simplest, and also the best. White is not sufficiently developed to go for any pawn-grabbing expeditions.} 12. Ne5 Qd8 13. Nxf6+ exf6 $1 {This line shows that placing the knight on e5 can have its drawbacks.}) 12... Bxf6 {This bishop is very well-placed on the open diagonal, and there is no reason for us to consider the alternative capture.} 13. O-O {With nothing left to clarify in the center of the board, White finds the time to castle. Despite the broken-looking structure on the kingside, the white king is actually quite safe.} O-O {The black king also finds a haven on the kingside. With play having calmed down a lot, maybe we could talk a bit about the strategic aspects of this position. Both sides have a solid position without major weaknesses and will have no problems finishing the development.  White has a bit more space, but the space also comes with the responsibility to defend it, especially the d5 -pawn that requires constant attention. We are already used to the f4 -pawn blocking the white bishop. White has tried many directions here in tournament practice, and I will mention a few.} 14. Be3 {This move is White's favorite choice, although it comes with certain risks. Allowing Black to take the b2 -pawn leaves White's structure potentially vulnerable.} Bxb2 {Why shouldn't we take this pawn? This capture ensures that Black will have the counterplay on the queenside and in the center since the white pawns will always be slightly vulnerable. Furthermore, White will never be able to block the long diagonal for our bishop by playing c3 at the right moment.} 15. Rb1 ({This is certainly the most natural and probable move. White has an alternative in} 15. Ne5 {, but it doesn't look too dangerous either. For example, after Ne5} Qc7 16. Rb1 {, Black has two options, one of them involving an exchange sac.} Bd4 (16... Bxe5 17. fxe5 Nd7 18. Bh6 Nxe5 {is fine for Black, but perhaps not to everyone's taste, given the material imbalance.}) 17. Bxd4 cxd4 18. Qxd4 Nd7 19. Ng4 h5 20. Ne3 Nf6 {is completely fine for Black since} 21. f5 {is well met by} g5 {, when White has to start defending the central pawns soon.}) 15... Bg7 {This is the best square for the bishop, and the black king feels so much better with this defender in the vicinity. White will likely capture the c5 -pawn, restoring the material balance, which we'll answer with ... Rd8 , immediately starting the play against the d5 -pawn. Once Black completes development, White's numerous pawn weaknesses will begin to tell.} *

