1. e4 d6 {Here, we'll take a very brief look at all sorts of early sidelines. The brevity of our attention is explained by the fact that, technically, all these lines are not part of the Pirc, so it's more of an overview than anything else.} 2. Bc4 {Many amateur players enjoy placing the light-squared bishop on c4 . However, it's a bit early here since Black can still opt for ... e6 and ... d5 , closing the white bishop in.} Nf6 {Black attacks the central pawn and postpones the decision about the pawn structure for one more move.} 3. d3 {White could naturally defend the e4 -pawn in various ways, but it wouldn't change much. Black's setup remains the same.} e6 {Black begins the process of walling in the white bishop. Cask of Amontillado, anyone? :)} 4. Nf3 {White develops in a natural manner. There is not much to do against the plan of ... d5 .} d5 {Black forces White to trade the pawns in the center. After that, the white bishop must assume a modest position on b3 . Black then proceeds with ... Bd6 and ... O-O , getting good play.} *

