1. e4 d6 {Here, we'll take a very brief look at all sorts of early sidelines. The brevity of our attention is explained by the fact that, technically, all these lines are not part of the Pirc, so it's more of an overview than anything else.} 2. f4 {This is a pretty popular way of playing. It will likely transpose to the Austrian Attack.} Nf6 {Our moves remain the same. White should now stop to cover the e4 -pawn.} 3. Nc3 {White could also play the last two moves in a different order.} g6 {We stick with the Pirc. White can transpose to the Austrian Attack anytime now by playing d4 .} 4. Nf3 {White avoids the Austrian Attack for now. If they were ever willing to play d4 , this would have happened on move 2. :)} Bg7 {Black sticks with the plan. White has the last chance to return to the well-known theory.} 5. Bc4 ({This is the most popular move. White could play} 5. d4 {instead, which transposes , but by now, we know this was never the plan. :)}) 5... Nxe4 {Throughout this course, I have been trying to go for direct continuations. This little combination gives Black a promising position.} 6. Nxe4 {This move is too timid and hands over the initiative without a fight.} d5 {Black wins back the sacrificed piece and gets a wonderful position. Like in many lines in the Pirc, the f4 -pawn is misplaced, limiting the c1 -bishop and weakening a bunch of squares.} *

