1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 ({This move is an invitation to play a King's Indian Defense after g6} 3. c4 {, etc. Black has many possible setups. I will give you one of the solid ones.}) 3... e5 {Whenever possible, we choose a central strategy. Not just in this opening, of course – it is more of a general principle. The endgames are not dangerous for Black.} 4. dxe5 {This move leads to quiet endgames.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {The black king won't castle today, but it doesn't matter much with the queens no longer on the board. The f3 -pawn prevents White from playing Nf3 , attacking the central pawn. Black has nothing to fear here. In the spirit of full disclosure, yours truly recently lost a game from this position. :( The opening had nothing to do with that result.} 6. Bc4 {White targets the f7 -pawn. Other moves lead to a similar kind of play.} Ke8 {It's the easiest way to defend the pawn. I was never a big fan of playing ... Be6 and getting the doubled pawns in the center.} 7. Be3 {It's a natural square for the dark-squared bishop. The bishop covers the potentially weak squares in the center, and this gives us an idea. Let's try to exchange that piece so that one day, we can claim those central squares.} Nbd7 {Black is ready to play ... Bc5 . Once the bishops are exchanged, Black can start feeling optimistic.} 8. Nc3 {This move threatens some unpleasantness with Nb5 . Throughout this course, the c3 -knight has a complicated destiny because Black has a good way of controlling all the vital squares.} c6 {It's a good motive to remember, here and in many other positions. The c6 -pawn ensures that the c3 -knight can't do anything active for a long time.} 9. Nge2 {White would like a better square for this knight, but the f3 -pawn has this unfortunate effect in many openings. Other moves would lead to the same reaction by Black.} Bc5 {Black will likely trade the bishops now. The ending remains approximately equal, but there is still a lot of life left. Black will find a cozy spot for the king on e7 and will try to expand on the queenside. White's pieces are not ideally played either, dominated by the black pawns on c6 and e5 .} *

