1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 ({This move is an invitation to play a King's Indian Defense after g6} 3. c4 {, etc. Black has many possible setups. I will give you one of the solid ones.}) 3... e5 {Whenever possible, we choose a central strategy. Not just in this opening, of course – it is more of a general principle. The endgames are not dangerous for Black.} 4. d5 {White closes the center and opts for a position more common for the King's Indian Defense. There are some differences, however, and I think they mainly favor Black.} Be7 {This move is the main difference with the King's Indian. There, Black plays the bishop fianchetto with ... g6 and ... Bg7 . Black saves a move by playing ... Be7 , and our kingside remains intact. Once the real fight starts, the black kings will be safe.} 5. c4 {White builds an impressive pawn chain in the center. The drawback of this approach, as with any big build, is that it takes time. Black will use this time to get their pieces onto great squares.} a5 {The position is closed, and we can keep our king in the center for a while. Black can castle at any moment, anyway. By playing ... a5 , we ensure the c5 -square for our knights.} 6. Nc3 {It's the natural square for the white knight. Traditionally, White castles queenside in these structures, and the moves Nc3 , Be3 , and Qd2 can be played in any order. The purpose of getting the white king to c1 remains the same.} Na6 {This move is a logical follow-up of our last move. The knight is well-placed here.} 7. Be3 {White develops in accordance with well-established patterns. Somewhat surprisingly, their plans will run into huge obstacles very soon.} Nd7 {Things are getting concrete. Black reminds White about the possibility of ... Bg5 since the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is favorable for Black.} 8. Qd2 {White still seems to have everything under control. This move prevents ... Bg5 and prepares to castle queenside. I think most players would be surprised to find out that White is already in some trouble, as will become apparent after Black's next move.} Ndc5 {You don't see this setup every day! Black usually plays ... a5 and ... Na6 in these structures to access the c5 -square, but it turns out that this outpost is for the other knight. Black now threatens ... f5 , and there is nothing White can do to stop it.  This break is usually prevented by White playing g4 , but in this position, it runs into ... Bh4 +, with the most unpleasant consequences. White is just one move away from playing both O-O-O and g4 , which explains why Black hasn't castled yet. After the inevitable ... f5 , White will face a long and difficult defense.} *

