1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 ({This move is an invitation to play a King's Indian Defense after g6} 3. c4 {, etc. Black has many possible setups. I will give you one of the solid ones.}) 3... e5 {Whenever possible, we choose a central strategy. Not just in this opening, of course – it is more of a general principle. The endgames are not dangerous for Black.} 4. d5 {White closes the center and opts for a position more common for the King's Indian Defense. There are some differences, however, and I think they mainly favor Black.} Be7 {This move is the main difference with the King's Indian. There, Black plays the bishop fianchetto with ... g6 and ... Bg7 . Black saves a move by playing ... Be7 , and our kingside remains intact. Once the real fight starts, the black kings will be safe.} 5. Be3 {The most popular way to play. By keeping the pawn on c2 , White maintains a certain level of flexibility. Depending on what Black does, they could still go for c4 or Nc3 .} O-O {Black manages to castle early in this line. White still needs a few moves before they can castle either side.} 6. Qd2 {White follows the plan and continues to keep the options open. Black's next move will force White to make a decision.} c6 {Black begins the fight in the center. It's not an easy fight for White to face with their king still in the middle of the board. Black is now threatening to weaken the white center by taking on d5 , a threat White should take seriously.} 7. c4 {Any other move would have left White with a long-term weakness in the center. White's space advantage will become an asset soon, which is why Black needs to adopt strong measures.} b5 {A powerful blow against White's pawn structure, especially since White is still far from finishing the piece development. Sure, it is a pawn sacrifice, but White will pay dearly for this pawn.} 8. cxb5 {White takes the pawn. It's a principled decision, but not without risks.} ({The sober} 8. Nc3 {would keep more control, although Black would still be doing well after grabbing the space on the queenside with} b4 {and ... c5 .}) 8... cxd5 {This is the point of Black's idea. Taking the other pawn would have left the white center intact.} 9. exd5 {Black's compensation is based on the weakness of the d5 -pawn. Should it ever fall, Black will simply overrun White in the center.} Bb7 {Black develops the bishop and attacks the d5 -pawn. Other pieces will soon follow suit.} 10. Nc3 ({White protects the pawn.} 10. Bc4 {would lead to the same position a few moves later.}) 10... Nbd7 ({Black's attack is taking shape. The immediate threat is ... Nb6 . White's task is difficult both after Bc4 Nb6 , and a4} 10... Qa5 {. In both lines, the d5 -pawn is in danger, and Black can increase the pressure with ... a6 , amongst other things.}) *

