{Black wins back the piece. White would be hard-pressed to find promising continuations here in a real-life situation. There are some sharp computer-generated tries, which means you probably can move away from this ... Qe7 idea after playing it a few times. But let's be realistic – you could spend a lifetime in chess without anyone trying Nd2 against you.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nd2 {White sometimes plays this move with a similar idea, trying to get Bd3 , c3 , Nf3 , etc. There is no need to commit the knight so early, though, and Black gets some new options in this line.} e5 ({We go for this central setup, like in the lines with f3 and Bd3 . We could also build a repertoire with} 3... g6 {after anything, but I guess you'll appreciate seeing other structures for a change.}) 4. c3 {White protects the d4 -pawn and tries to build a safe, central position. There are some problems with this approach, though. The d2 -knight isn't great, blocking the dark-squared bishop. And the white pawn center is far from stable, as we'll discover soon.} exd4 {I like experimenting with new ideas. We could certainly build a repertoire along the common lines, but where's the fun in that. :) Taking on d4 has a very concrete idea.} 5. cxd4 Qe7 {When you can shock your opponent as early as move 5, you should. White cannot keep the proud pawn center without serious positional concessions.} 6. Bd3 ({The natural way to protect the pawn. Playing} 6. f3 {would have kept the center intact but at a high price, as the white knights would have been denied their best squares.}) 6... Nxe4 {This little combination is the point behind our opening idea. Black destroys the pawn center once and for all.} 7. Nxe4 {Taking with the bishop would have given Black a bishop pair for no good reason.} d5 *

