1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {This line enjoys some popularity, and I used to employ it myself. I think it's been some 30+ years since I last tried this system. I freshened up my knowledge for this course, so don't worry about a thing. :)} e5 {We use the same solid approach as in the other sidelines on move 3. Black's central strategy usually leads to more dynamic play than the typical Pirc setups.} 4. dxe5 {This move is completely harmless. Its only advantage is that it leads to boring play – if that's something White likes. There are all sorts of players out there. :)} dxe5 {Black will finish the development by playing ... Bd6 , ... O-O , and bringing the knight to c5 . The position is equal, but there is still potential for both players to go wrong.} *

