1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {This line enjoys some popularity, and I used to employ it myself. I think it's been some 30+ years since I last tried this system. I freshened up my knowledge for this course, so don't worry about a thing. :)} e5 {We use the same solid approach as in the other sidelines on move 3. Black's central strategy usually leads to more dynamic play than the typical Pirc setups.} 4. d5 {There is always an option of closing the center. The resulting King's Indian structures are rarely advantageous for White, especially if Black knows a move or two.} Nbd7 {Black goes for the d3 -bishop. The e4 -pawn is vulnerable, and White cannot comfortably prevent the plan with ... Nc5 and ... Nd3 . True, the bishop pair will not be immediately devastating in this fairly closed position, but they will be an asset nonetheless.} 5. c4 {White builds the pawn center. The structure is very much King's Indian Defense but with a twist. The g7 -pawn hasn't moved, and this little fact makes the line much safer for Black than you'd expect.} Nc5 {Black is going for the bishop. If White had one more move, our plan would no longer succeed.} 6. Nc3 {White develops the knight and protects the central pawn. Given the chance, White will play Bc2 next. We should not let that happen.} Nxd3+ {This move completes the plan Black started on move 4. The three moves Black took to eliminate the white bishop might seem an overly generous expenditure, but I assure you, it's worth it. The black bishops have great potential.} 7. Qxd3 Be7 {The time has come to develop our pieces. Once again, the black bishop is happy to go to e7 . It's both faster and safer than playing ... g6 and ... Bg7 .} 8. Nge2 {The white king will be safer on the kingside. White develops the knight to e2 in anticipation of the possible ... f5 . The white knight can be potentially useful on g3 .} O-O {Black castles, and maybe we can take stock of the position. Black has two bishops, a safe king, and a potential break with ... f5 . In the immediate future, Black will play ... a5 , followed by ... Nd7 - c5 and maybe ... Bg5 . Black has nothing to fear in the battle to come.} *

