1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {This line enjoys some popularity, and I used to employ it myself. I think it's been some 30+ years since I last tried this system. I freshened up my knowledge for this course, so don't worry about a thing. :)} e5 {We use the same solid approach as in the other sidelines on move 3. Black's central strategy usually leads to more dynamic play than the typical Pirc setups.} 4. Nf3 {It's not a very popular move, and yet, it's never a mistake to develop a piece. White abandons the plans to fortify the pawn center with c3 , and this allows us to try our luck with a different structure.} exd4 {We don't often go for this structure throughout this course. There are details here, however, that are favorable for Black. The d3 -bishop is somewhat in the way, and the white knight will feel uncomfortable on d4 .} 5. Nxd4 g6 {The white knight on d4 makes the fianchetto especially attractive. The g7 -bishop will exert pressure on White's position, and the g6 -pawn controls the f5 -square. What more could you possibly ask from any move?} 6. O-O {Both sides castle short in this line. The king's safety will not be a concern for a long time, and we can concentrate on the positional factors.} Bg7 {The black bishop is very happy here.} 7. Nc3 {White, too, has the luxury of developing their pieces in a natural way.} O-O {The 'castle first, ask questions later' rule has served me well for the last 40 years or so. :)} 8. Bg5 {It's the most active way to develop the dark-squared bishop, especially since the e3 -square is vulnerable to ... Ng4 . Black should bear in mind the possible Nd5 now.} c6 {Black takes firm measures against any Nd5 -related nonsense. In general, the c6 -pawn is something of a magic worker in this opening, controlling most of the nice squares that the white knights could go to. Black's plans in the near future will include ... Qb6 , ... Nbd7 , and ... Re8 , with a complicated game and mutual chances.} *

