1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 {This line enjoys some popularity, and I used to employ it myself. I think it's been some 30+ years since I last tried this system. I freshened up my knowledge for this course, so don't worry about a thing. :)} e5 {We use the same solid approach as in the other sidelines on move 3. Black's central strategy usually leads to more dynamic play than the typical Pirc setups.} 4. c3 {White tries to keep the pawn center intact. The alternatives to this move are numerous and lead to vastly different structures.} d5 {Black goes for the early break in the center. It leads to a lively game with many active possibilities for both sides.} 5. dxe5 {It is the only challenging move. Any other reaction would leave White struggling in the center of the board.} Nxe4 ({Black should be careful here, as the tempting} 5... dxe4 {runs into some unpleasantness after} 6. Bb5+ {. Taking on e4 with the knight leads to a nice, open game where all the pieces have wonderful prospects. My kind of game. :)}) 6. Nf3 {As always, it's a good developing move. White defends the e5 -pawn, always a vulnerable spot in these structures, and prepares to castle short. Taking the e4 -knight and going for the ending would have been a serious mistake since the pair of bishops would far outweigh the uncastled black king.} Nc5 {Black has many possible ways to develop. I like this one because it is very forcing in character. Black threatens to take the bishop, something White should prevent.} 7. Bc2 {It's only natural for White to make use of the c3 -pawn. The c2 -square is now available for the light-squared bishop, a somewhat unexpected benefit of White's fourth move.} Bg4 {It's always pleasant to make such an active move. The pin along the g4 - d1 -diagonal allows Black to choose a very ambitious plan with ... Nc6 and ... d4 .} 8. O-O {The white king is safe on the kingside. I don't think White can profit from delaying this move.} Nc6 {Black continues to develop their pieces very actively. The c6 -knight potentially threatens the e5 -pawn, but even more importantly, it supports the central break with ... d4 . In some lines, Black can also choose a harmonious setup with ... Ne6 and ... Bc5 .} 9. Re1 {This move is the most popular by a margin. Maybe the pawn wasn't hanging for tactical reasons, but these days, nobody likes risking any material deficit. :)} d4 {When looking at this position, I get the feeling that Black is the one exerting pressure. White will get into trouble if they decide to take the d4 -pawn, which means they have to learn to live with the unpleasant threat of ... d3 .} 10. h3 {White makes a useful move, postponing making tough decisions by a bit. Black needs to keep the pin, so the next move is pretty forced.} Bh5 {Black keeps the pin, and White needs to make a decision on how to proceed with this game. Black is ready to counter White's active attempts, such as b4 or g4 , by playing ... d3 . Taking the d4 -pawn still runs into trouble after ... Bxf3 . I'm not saying Black is better, but rather that in a real game, White will not find this position easy to play.} *

