1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f3 ({This move is usually followed by Be3 . It will transpose to the lines with} 4. Be3 {, and the combination of Be3 and f3 isn't that great anyway. Both of the lines mentioned here, f3 and Bf4 , transpose to the Be3 lines at best. I could also ignore these lines, and they are only for completeness' sake.}) 4... Bg7 {Black goes for the main setup. I will not go into depth here since we're just fast-forwarding to where this line transposes to another one.} 5. Be3 {The f3 -pawn always requires the dark-squared bishop around. Someone has to cover all those weak spots. :)} c6 {Black follows the same setup as after Be3 . We don't need to overcomplicate our repertoire.} 6. Qd2 {A natural move, bringing us to a position covered in the 4.Be3 lines .} b5 {Check the aforementioned 4.Be3 move order for more details.} *

