1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bf4 ({This line is quite popular. I must say I don't quite understand the attraction. It looks like a worse version of the} 4. Be3 {line to me. The f4 -bishop doesn't protect the d4 -pawn, and it is vulnerable to ... Nh5 and ... e5 . Sure, White can play Qd2 and Bh6 , but they could also do this in a Be3 line.}) 4... Bg7 {What we need to know about this variation is that it will probably transpose to one of the 4.Be3 lines. Our reaction is the same as in the other line. It's up to White to show why the bishop is better on f4 , which I think is an impossible task.} 5. Qd2 {It's the natural follow-up to Bf4 . White is now ready to castle long and to play Bh6 .} c6 {Our standard reaction. Black is ready to play ... b5 next and can add ... Qa5 into the mix. What White does next will determine the kind of battle we'll get.} 6. Bh6 ({This move is White's best try. It transposes directly to the main lines of the} 6. Be3 {variation.}) 6... Bxh6 {So please check the 4.Be3 move order .} *

