1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bf4 ({This line is quite popular. I must say I don't quite understand the attraction. It looks like a worse version of the} 4. Be3 {line to me. The f4 -bishop doesn't protect the d4 -pawn, and it is vulnerable to ... Nh5 and ... e5 . Sure, White can play Qd2 and Bh6 , but they could also do this in a Be3 line.}) 4... Bg7 {What we need to know about this variation is that it will probably transpose to one of the 4.Be3 lines. Our reaction is the same as in the other line. It's up to White to show why the bishop is better on f4 , which I think is an impossible task.} 5. Qd2 {It's the natural follow-up to Bf4 . White is now ready to castle long and to play Bh6 .} c6 {Our standard reaction. Black is ready to play ... b5 next and can add ... Qa5 into the mix. What White does next will determine the kind of battle we'll get.} 6. Nf3 {It's always reasonable to develop your pieces. White will certainly keep a decent position with this approach. The only drawback of White's setup is that it's not very threatening, and Black can simply proceed with their plans.} Bg4 {Black is happy to develop the bishop into such an active position. The immediate threat is to ruin the white pawns with ... Bf3 , and as we'll see throughout this course, this weakening can have long-lasting consequences. White is not helped by the fact that the f4 -bishop is vulnerable to both ... Nh5 and ... e5 in various lines.} 7. Be2 {White prevents structural damage with this move. It's interesting to observe that White developed the queenside with Bf4 and Qd2 and then moved to the kingside with Nf3 and Be2 . There is nothing wrong with this pattern, but it can sometimes be symptomatic of a certain lack of harmony in the position.} Nbd7 {With simple means, Black reached a very harmonious setup. Over the following few moves, Black will have the luxury of choosing between many plans, such as playing for ... b5 or preparing ... e5 . It seems likely that White will lose a tempo in the near future to move the f4 -bishop back, a clear sign of something going wrong with the opening plan.} *

