1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bf4 ({This line is quite popular. I must say I don't quite understand the attraction. It looks like a worse version of the} 4. Be3 {line to me. The f4 -bishop doesn't protect the d4 -pawn, and it is vulnerable to ... Nh5 and ... e5 . Sure, White can play Qd2 and Bh6 , but they could also do this in a Be3 line.}) 4... Bg7 {What we need to know about this variation is that it will probably transpose to one of the 4.Be3 lines. Our reaction is the same as in the other line. It's up to White to show why the bishop is better on f4 , which I think is an impossible task.} 5. Qd2 {It's the natural follow-up to Bf4 . White is now ready to castle long and to play Bh6 .} c6 {Our standard reaction. Black is ready to play ... b5 next and can add ... Qa5 into the mix. What White does next will determine the kind of battle we'll get.} 6. O-O-O {It should come as no surprise to us that this move is the most popular one. After all, the queenside castling seems to be a logical follow-up to White's previous moves. The truth is, as often in the Pirc, the queenside is not a very safe place for the white king.} b5 {Black starts the fight for the initiative. Black threatens to win the e4 -pawn with ... b4 , but this is just the beginning of White's troubles. That White should think of defensive measures so early in the game is a bad sign.} 7. Bd3 {White defends the e4 -pawn, developing a piece at the same time.} ({White could also play} 7. f3 {, which wouldn't change our plans. Black would still react in the same vein, with ... b4 and ... Qa5 , getting a promising attacking position.}) 7... b4 {Chess is an enjoyable game, especially when you go for clear, direct plans. Black forces the white knight to choose a square to retreat to, and White doesn't have many good squares here. I've always had the same feeling about many Sicilian positions. Once the white knight is attacked by ... b4 , all the available options start looking pretty grim.} 8. Na4 {It looks like a more active of the possible squares for the white knight, but it has a big problem. The a4 -knight turns out to be a target, and Black will be able to force a considerable weakening of the white king's position by attacking it.} Qa5 {Black attacks the white knight, and White only has one way of protecting it.} 9. b3 {It's not what White wanted to do with their pawn structure, but there was no choice. The dark squares around the white king are weakened beyond repair now. This might not immediately feel like a big deal, but these things tend to get worse. :)} Nbd7 {Black creates a deadly threat of ... Nb6 . White can find ways not to lose at once, but Black is dominant in the long run as well. A simple plan of castling short and playing ... c5 will be a nightmare for White. It's a lesson I learned from the Sicilian – if you put a knight on a4 , it tends to end badly.} *

