1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bf4 ({This line is quite popular. I must say I don't quite understand the attraction. It looks like a worse version of the} 4. Be3 {line to me. The f4 -bishop doesn't protect the d4 -pawn, and it is vulnerable to ... Nh5 and ... e5 . Sure, White can play Qd2 and Bh6 , but they could also do this in a Be3 line.}) 4... Bg7 {What we need to know about this variation is that it will probably transpose to one of the 4.Be3 lines. Our reaction is the same as in the other line. It's up to White to show why the bishop is better on f4 , which I think is an impossible task.} 5. Qd2 {It's the natural follow-up to Bf4 . White is now ready to castle long and to play Bh6 .} c6 {Our standard reaction. Black is ready to play ... b5 next and can add ... Qa5 into the mix. What White does next will determine the kind of battle we'll get.} 6. O-O-O {It should come as no surprise to us that this move is the most popular one. After all, the queenside castling seems to be a logical follow-up to White's previous moves. The truth is, as often in the Pirc, the queenside is not a very safe place for the white king.} b5 {Black starts the fight for the initiative. Black threatens to win the e4 -pawn with ... b4 , but this is just the beginning of White's troubles. That White should think of defensive measures so early in the game is a bad sign.} 7. Bd3 {White defends the e4 -pawn, developing a piece at the same time.} ({White could also play} 7. f3 {, which wouldn't change our plans. Black would still react in the same vein, with ... b4 and ... Qa5 , getting a promising attacking position.}) 7... b4 {Chess is an enjoyable game, especially when you go for clear, direct plans. Black forces the white knight to choose a square to retreat to, and White doesn't have many good squares here. I've always had the same feeling about many Sicilian positions. Once the white knight is attacked by ... b4 , all the available options start looking pretty grim.} 8. Nce2 {This square, though very modest, is still better than the alternatives. Going to b1 is just sad, and the a4 -square has problems, too.} Qa5 {Black attacks the a2 -pawn and protects the b4 -pawn at the same time. What happens now is a textbook example of how to develop the initiative.} {Starting with b5 , every move by Black has a direct threat. Black threatened the e-pawn first, the white knight was attacked later, and the a2 -pawn after that. That's the power of initiative in chess, depriving the opponent of peace of mind.} 9. Kb1 {The a2 -pawn needs White's attention. White shouldn't be tempted by the possibility of playing a3 now since it would only create a target for the attack. The pawns don't move back, do they? :)} Be6 {Every move is a threat, remember? We threaten mate in 2 now – they rarely get bigger than this. As a bonus, Black develops the bishop for free.} 10. Nc1 {White defends against the deadly threat without creating weaknesses in their camp. Both alternatives, a3 and b3 , would strengthen Black's attacking potential.} Qb6 {The queen steps back, getting out of the way of potential Nb3 . We'll see why this is relevant here very soon. Also, Black threatens to take on d4 . Not a single move without a threat, remember?} 11. Nge2 ({White protects the d4 -pawn and develops the knight at the same time. Playing} 11. Nf3 {is very similar.}) 11... c5 {It's a timely break, adding to White's problems on the queenside before they could fully consolidate. Black is threatening ... c4 , winning a piece, which makes it a sixth move in a row with a direct threat. White can parry the threat in various ways, but not without some concessions. The long diagonal is likely to open up for the g7 -bishop. Black has excellent chances in this sharp position.} *

