1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bc4 {There are always chess players out there who experiment with relatively new ideas. Bc4 , in combination with Nc3 , was basically unknown in my time, and yes, I'm old enough to say something like this. :) In recent years, White discovered interesting ways of playing this variation, and we should acquaint ourselves with some lines.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to postpone this natural move. The f7 -pawn can be a bit soft with the light-squared bishop on c4 , and we would like to castle quickly to give it an extra bit of protection.} 5. Qe2 {This move is the main reason why this line needs our attention. White creates the idea of e5 and e6 , and this is a threat that needs to be dealt with. Black has a few ways of doing that and, as always, I pick the one that keeps things interesting.} Nc6 {I like this fast approach. The knight doesn't usually make it to c6 when our pawn is still on c7 . White's last move left the d4 -pawn without protection, however, and we see it as an invitation to be annoying. :) If White were to protect the pawn by normal moves, Black would get a nice position by playing ... Bg4 or ... e5 . Things will take a surprising turn now.} 6. e5 {It's a principled approach, and it has found hundreds of ardent followers. What makes it highly unusual is that it's a queen sacrifice. White is planning to answer Nd4 with exf6 , getting three minor pieces for the queen in a highly irregular position.  I didn't check, but it must be one of the earliest queen sacrifices in all opening theory – after all, it's only move 6! I analyzed this position for a while and decided we'd be better off refusing the gift.} Ng4 {Black is fighting for the initiative. Both white pawns in the center are hanging and protecting them doesn't look easy. White is somewhat lucky to have a move that keeps control.} 7. e6 {This dangerous-looking move doesn't work at all. It is useful for us to know it, though.} Nxd4 {Black has many playable moves, but this one is just winning. I have been discovering recently, although much too late for my own career, that sometimes you should grab as much material as you can.} 8. Qxg4 {White tries to insist that everything was planned and burns all the bridges. Many players tried this, but none knew what they were doing. :)} Nxc2+ {Black will take the a1 -rook next. White's attack is an illusion since the black king will be rock-solid on f8 .} ({In fact, after Ke2 , for example, Black can even refrain from grabbing the rook and opt for} 8... fxe6 {since} 9. Rb1 d5 10. Bb3 e5 {is almost winning for Black. Three pawns and a powerful initiative against White's 'centralized' king is more than enough for the piece investment.}) *

