1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bc4 {There are always chess players out there who experiment with relatively new ideas. Bc4 , in combination with Nc3 , was basically unknown in my time, and yes, I'm old enough to say something like this. :) In recent years, White discovered interesting ways of playing this variation, and we should acquaint ourselves with some lines.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to postpone this natural move. The f7 -pawn can be a bit soft with the light-squared bishop on c4 , and we would like to castle quickly to give it an extra bit of protection.} 5. Qe2 {This move is the main reason why this line needs our attention. White creates the idea of e5 and e6 , and this is a threat that needs to be dealt with. Black has a few ways of doing that and, as always, I pick the one that keeps things interesting.} Nc6 {I like this fast approach. The knight doesn't usually make it to c6 when our pawn is still on c7 . White's last move left the d4 -pawn without protection, however, and we see it as an invitation to be annoying. :) If White were to protect the pawn by normal moves, Black would get a nice position by playing ... Bg4 or ... e5 . Things will take a surprising turn now.} 6. e5 {It's a principled approach, and it has found hundreds of ardent followers. What makes it highly unusual is that it's a queen sacrifice. White is planning to answer Nd4 with exf6 , getting three minor pieces for the queen in a highly irregular position.  I didn't check, but it must be one of the earliest queen sacrifices in all opening theory – after all, it's only move 6! I analyzed this position for a while and decided we'd be better off refusing the gift.} Ng4 {Black is fighting for the initiative. Both white pawns in the center are hanging and protecting them doesn't look easy. White is somewhat lucky to have a move that keeps control.} 7. Bb5 {This pin comes to White's rescue. Black can't take anything now since they have a threat of d5 to deal with. The time has come to evacuate our king.} O-O {Black castles and renews all the threats. White's next move is forced.} 8. Bxc6 {This move finally eliminates the threat to the central pawns, though at a serious cost. White made three moves with the light-squared bishop, only to have it exchanged.} bxc6 {Black has a pair of bishops and a very compact position. There are still some positional nuances, though, and we should stay with this line a bit longer.} 9. h3 {It is White's main positional trump. The black knight is being kicked to h6 , which is not a great square. The game will now revolve around this theme. White will try to ensure that the knight remains sidelined, and Black will try to get it into play.} Nh6 {I always felt joy when making the only moves. Chess can be tough, and it is lovely to make some of the decisions without effort. As mentioned before, this knight has no intention of staying here forever.} 10. Nf3 {It's the natural way to develop. White protects the central pawns and gets ready to castle. Now that the white knight is on f3 , Black should not play ... Nf5 . Black would have to return the knight to h6 after White plays g4 , a most unfortunate outcome.} Qd7 {I like this unusual-looking move. Black's position will be great once we manage to get the knight into play. By controlling the e6 -square, we prepare the plan of ... f6 and ... Nf7 . The black queen is in the way of the light-squared bishop, but it has other, better diagonals in mind.} 11. O-O {Nothing could be more natural than this, yet White loses one of their main strategic resources with this move. White is unlikely to play g4 with the white king on g1 , and this means that the black knight can go to the most active square.} Nf5 {We no longer need to hide our intentions. The black knight assumes its dominant position in the center of the board. The only way to disturb would be by playing g4 , a weakening White cannot afford.} 12. Re1 {This move shows a high level of awareness. Black was intending, among other things, the break with ... f6 . Now it would run into e6 , something Black should never allow. The pair of bishops need their diagonals, though, and the next move takes care of this most decisively.} c5 {The time has come to make an ambitious claim in this game. The black bishops can become very strong, especially the light-squared one. Black opens the long diagonal and doesn't hesitate to sacrifice a pawn if necessary. Once the position opens up, the extra pawn will be nothing more than a silent witness of White's demise.} 13. dxc5 {White has no choice. They have to keep the position as closed as possible, which means the e5 -pawn should stay where it is. This will also be relevant over the next couple of moves.} Bb7 {We could simply take the pawn back, but there is no rush. The black bishop assumes its dominant position, and White has to make some difficult decisions. Taking on d6 will open the e-file after ... exd6 , and this White might not survive. Black is also threatening the e5 -pawn, and at least this is a threat White can do something about.} 14. Bf4 {White defends the e5 -pawn and finishes the development, more or less. After the eventual Rad1 , the a1 -rook is ready to join the action in the center. Black still has a few tricks, however.} Qc6 {It is a nice little move, reminding White of the possible dangers along the long diagonal. Black threatens ... Nd4 and ... Qxc5 , both potentially devastating. It is still dangerous for White to open the e-file, so taking the d6 -pawn is not advisable. Black has the bishop pair and good chances in this complex middlegame.} *

