1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {Here, we'll consider some rare setups. I won't dive too deeply into lines you're unlikely to face, so this serves as general guidance.} 4. Bd3 {This move is fine but doesn't have much independent meaning. It usually transposes to some other line or becomes quite toothless.} Bg7 ({There is nothing wrong with our normal developing move. If you feel like trying something else, Black also has} 4... e5 {or Nc6 , amongst other moves.}) 5. Nge2 ({This move looks consistent with 4.Bd3 , but the knight isn't great here. Other, perhaps better, moves transpose to different systems. You'll find the positions after} 5. Nf3 {or f4 elsewhere in this course.}) 5... e5 {The ease with which we get this advance is symptomatic of something wrong in White's setup. The e5 -pawn restricts the e2 -knight, and this is likely to be an issue for a long time.} 6. O-O {There is nothing better.} O-O {After both kings have castled, it's obvious that Black is comfortable. We already know that the e2 -knight isn't great, and Black has many interesting ways to continue. We can either play ... Nc6 in the manner of the King's Indian Defense or ... Nbd7 and ... c6 , with good prospects.} *

