1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {Here, we'll consider some rare setups. I won't dive too deeply into lines you're unlikely to face, so this serves as general guidance.} 4. Be2 {This move appears to support a pawn advance on the kingside. The bishop enables ideas like g4 or h4 - h5 , but both achieve little beyond weakening White's pawn structure.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to do something else. White's 4.Be2 doesn't threaten much, so we can develop and see what comes next.} 5. g4 {White isn't ready for such an early expansion on the kingside. After all, it's only move 5! Whatever happened to the rules of opening play? :)} d5 {This is the classical response: when your opponent does something questionable on the side of the board, you strike in the center. Once the knight leaves the f6 -square, White's pawn will start questioning its purpose in life.} 6. e5 {There is nothing else. The pawns are far too vulnerable to risk opening the center. By keeping things closed, White can hope to buy some time.} Ne4 {The knight is perfectly placed here, in the center of the board. Black will soon break White's pawn structure with ... c5 . The g4 -pawn severely weakens White's position, and with that, we conclude our analysis of this line. :)} *

