1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {Here, we'll consider some rare setups. I won't dive too deeply into lines you're unlikely to face, so this serves as general guidance.} 4. Be2 {This move appears to support a pawn advance on the kingside. The bishop enables ideas like g4 or h4 - h5 , but both achieve little beyond weakening White's pawn structure.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to do something else. White's 4.Be2 doesn't threaten much, so we can develop and see what comes next.} 5. h4 {Of the two possible ways to begin moving pawns on the kingside, this one is far more reasonable. It does not bring White any immediate attacking chances, but at least it maintains a solid position.} ({Bent Larsen famously declared that moving the h-pawn is often better than it appears because it does not create structural weaknesses. Comparing the lines with} 5. g4 {and h4 clearly illustrates his point.}) 5... h5 {It is best to stop the white pawn at once. If it reaches h5 , Black will face only bad options. The pawn structure on the kingside closes now, and the game character slows down. The white pawns are firmly blocked, and White should return to developing pieces.} 6. Nf3 {White develops the classical way, but the inclusion of h4 and ... h5 changes a lot. It results in both sides getting strong outposts in the enemy camp. White will use the g5 -square, while Black will establish a piece on g4 .} O-O {Since White has no realistic kingside attack, we can castle without concern. We sometimes have to appreciate the little gifts of life. Being able to castle without getting checkmated is one of them. :)} 7. Ng5 {This move is very popular, as White establishes the knight on an active outpost and prepares the plan involving f3 , Be3 , and Qd2 . Should White succeed in making all these moves, Black's position could become dangerous. Once again, we should engage our opponent in the center of the board.} Nc6 {It is an excellent move, using long-term and minute positional factors. One of them is that the black knight would be happy on e5 , after d5 , for instance. The inclusion of moves h4 and ... h5 impacts the structure by making e5 a fortress since White can never play f4 . Additionally, it is vital to threaten ... e5 before White completes the plan with Be3 and f3 .} 8. Be3 {You cannot have everything. White would like to play this move without allowing ... Ng4 , but Black was already threatening ... e5 .} Ng4 {Just in time, Black secures the pair of bishops. White certainly keeps a solid central position, but I would rather play with the black pieces.} *

