1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {Here, we'll consider some rare setups. I won't dive too deeply into lines you're unlikely to face, so this serves as general guidance.} 4. Be2 {This move appears to support a pawn advance on the kingside. The bishop enables ideas like g4 or h4 - h5 , but both achieve little beyond weakening White's pawn structure.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to do something else. White's 4.Be2 doesn't threaten much, so we can develop and see what comes next.} 5. Be3 {This move is popular enough to be mentioned here. The combination of Be3 and Be2 might look aesthetically pleasing, but in fact, White gets a worse version of the lines with Be3 , as they work better without Be2 .} O-O {Black castles and keeps all the options of changing the pawn structure on the next move. Depending on White's reaction, we could still choose between ... c6 , ... c5 , or ... e5 . This flexibility of the pawn structure is one of the strategic appeals of this opening.} 6. Qd2 {It's a natural move and, as these things go, also the most popular one. People have all sorts of illusions when it comes to chess players. We are supposed to be deep thinkers, hard workers, and much more. But the truth is, more often than not, we make a move that looks good. :)} ({Aggressive tries on the kingside, such as} 6. h4 {and g4 , will be similar to the lines on move 5. They are not dangerous.}) 6... e5 {We like this central approach whenever possible. The e5 -pawn ensures equality in the center of the board and gives us play against the d4 -pawn and, indirectly, the e4 -pawn by threatening to open the e-file. Allowing the early ... e5 is the main drawback of this line for White. The endings are good for Black, so White will mainly normally choose between closing the center and allowing ... exd4 .} 7. Nf3 {If White avoids changing the pawn structure in the center, this move is only natural. Black was threatening ... exd4 and ... Nc6 , and White got ready to take back on d4 in a better way.} exd4 ({It's certainly not the only way to play, but it is simple and direct. Black gets the necessary play against the e4 -pawn and equalizes with ease. We could keep things closed by playing} 7... Nc6 {or Ng4 if that's stylistically preferable to you.}) 8. Nxd4 {This is the only move that makes sense. Taking on d4 with the bishop looks very awkward after ... Nc6 .} Re8 {We activate the rook with the gain of time. White can't ignore the threat to the central pawn and needs to react.} 9. f3 {It's the only way to protect the pawn firmly and is the favorite choice of most players who wander into this position. Should White get enough time to castle long and start some action on the kingside, their chances will be higher. Black should act quickly.} d5 {A logical follow-up of Black's plan. The e8 -rook will become quite strong if we manage to open the e-file. Black is also threatening ... c5 , with potentially unpleasant consequences for White. We're looking at a sharp battle with mutual chances.} *

