{We prepared this move some time back by playing c6 . The black queen is active, prevents White from taking on d6 , and largely dissuades White from castling queenside. Black will proceed with ... Be6 and ... Rad8 . A timely ... d5 should give us excellent chances in the upcoming middlegame.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {Here, we'll consider some rare setups. I won't dive too deeply into lines you're unlikely to face, so this serves as general guidance.} 4. Be2 {This move appears to support a pawn advance on the kingside. The bishop enables ideas like g4 or h4 - h5 , but both achieve little beyond weakening White's pawn structure.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to do something else. White's 4.Be2 doesn't threaten much, so we can develop and see what comes next.} 5. Be3 {This move is popular enough to be mentioned here. The combination of Be3 and Be2 might look aesthetically pleasing, but in fact, White gets a worse version of the lines with Be3 , as they work better without Be2 .} O-O {Black castles and keeps all the options of changing the pawn structure on the next move. Depending on White's reaction, we could still choose between ... c6 , ... c5 , or ... e5 . This flexibility of the pawn structure is one of the strategic appeals of this opening.} 6. Qd2 {It's a natural move and, as these things go, also the most popular one. People have all sorts of illusions when it comes to chess players. We are supposed to be deep thinkers, hard workers, and much more. But the truth is, more often than not, we make a move that looks good. :)} ({Aggressive tries on the kingside, such as} 6. h4 {and g4 , will be similar to the lines on move 5. They are not dangerous.}) 6... e5 {We like this central approach whenever possible. The e5 -pawn ensures equality in the center of the board and gives us play against the d4 -pawn and, indirectly, the e4 -pawn by threatening to open the e-file. Allowing the early ... e5 is the main drawback of this line for White. The endings are good for Black, so White will mainly normally choose between closing the center and allowing ... exd4 .} 7. d5 {The option of closing the center with d5 is never the easy one for White. Natural e4 -players have always struggled with closed King's Indian structures. We should also mention that it's not a good version of the King's Indian structure either because the c2 -pawn would be better off on c4 .} c6 {It's a good way of creating counterplay in this position. Black challenges White's center and threatens ... cxd5 , forcing a favorable transformation in the center. White has to react.} 8. dxc6 {A sensible way to play, trying to take advantage of the d6 -pawn being vulnerable. On the other hand, White helps Black to activate the b8 -knight. Suddenly, White is the one lagging in development.} Nxc6 ({It's always pleasant to develop a piece. The alternative,} 8... bxc6 {, is equally playable and leads to a complex position. Black is ahead in development and has all the chances to deal with the slight weakness of the d6 -pawn.}) 9. Nf3 {This move controls the vulnerable d4 -square and is perhaps the more prudent way of playing. White delays attacking the d6 -pawn until better times, and tries to finish the piece development first.} Qa5 *

