1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 {Here, we'll consider some rare setups. I won't dive too deeply into lines you're unlikely to face, so this serves as general guidance.} 4. Be2 {This move appears to support a pawn advance on the kingside. The bishop enables ideas like g4 or h4 - h5 , but both achieve little beyond weakening White's pawn structure.} Bg7 {There is no reason for Black to do something else. White's 4.Be2 doesn't threaten much, so we can develop and see what comes next.} 5. Be3 {This move is popular enough to be mentioned here. The combination of Be3 and Be2 might look aesthetically pleasing, but in fact, White gets a worse version of the lines with Be3 , as they work better without Be2 .} O-O {Black castles and keeps all the options of changing the pawn structure on the next move. Depending on White's reaction, we could still choose between ... c6 , ... c5 , or ... e5 . This flexibility of the pawn structure is one of the strategic appeals of this opening.} 6. Qd2 {It's a natural move and, as these things go, also the most popular one. People have all sorts of illusions when it comes to chess players. We are supposed to be deep thinkers, hard workers, and much more. But the truth is, more often than not, we make a move that looks good. :)} ({Aggressive tries on the kingside, such as} 6. h4 {and g4 , will be similar to the lines on move 5. They are not dangerous.}) 6... e5 {We like this central approach whenever possible. The e5 -pawn ensures equality in the center of the board and gives us play against the d4 -pawn and, indirectly, the e4 -pawn by threatening to open the e-file. Allowing the early ... e5 is the main drawback of this line for White. The endings are good for Black, so White will mainly normally choose between closing the center and allowing ... exd4 .} 7. d5 {The option of closing the center with d5 is never the easy one for White. Natural e4 -players have always struggled with closed King's Indian structures. We should also mention that it's not a good version of the King's Indian structure either because the c2 -pawn would be better off on c4 .} c6 {It's a good way of creating counterplay in this position. Black challenges White's center and threatens ... cxd5 , forcing a favorable transformation in the center. White has to react.} 8. dxc6 {A sensible way to play, trying to take advantage of the d6 -pawn being vulnerable. On the other hand, White helps Black to activate the b8 -knight. Suddenly, White is the one lagging in development.} Nxc6 ({It's always pleasant to develop a piece. The alternative,} 8... bxc6 {, is equally playable and leads to a complex position. Black is ahead in development and has all the chances to deal with the slight weakness of the d6 -pawn.}) 9. O-O-O {At any rate, it's a consistent approach. White attacks the d6 -pawn, but the weakness of the d4 -square means that White will get more trouble than anything else.} d5 {It is truly a bolt from the blue. Black turns the weakness into strength and goes for the direct fight in the center, the fight White is not ready for. White has only one playable move now.} 10. exd5 {White has no choice but to take the pawn. Now, the d-file is closed, much to the dismay of White's heavy artillery.} Nd4 {This move is the reason behind Black's pawn sacrifice. The knight assumes a dominant position in the center, exerting a huge pressure in all directions. For tactical reasons, White can't take on d4 yet and has to find other ways of playing.  Black has an array of threats, such as the simple ... Nd5 , but also ... Bf5 and ... Rc8 , developing the attack. White has long-term concerns about the safety of their king and faces an uphill battle with little upside.} *

