1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 {The kingside fianchetto is a favorite tool of players who like to keep it quiet and positional. White intends to continue with Bg2 , Nge2 , and O-O , getting a healthy central setup. The one major drawback of this variation is that it provides the opponent with complete freedom of action.} Bg7 {This move, and the next, are automatic. Since White opts for such a quiet setup, we can take all the time we want. This means we castle first and then decide what to do next.} 5. Bg2 {The g2 -bishop is quite helpful here, as it gives the e4 -pawn an additional layer of protection. The drawback of this approach is that the bishop is limited by a pawn for a very long time. Everything in life comes at a cost.} O-O {The speed with which Black is usually able to castle is one of the best features of the Pirc. Too many games are lost because the king is stuck in the center of the board.} 6. Nf3 {If playing Nf3 after Bg2 looks strange to you, you're not alone. I wasn't even aware it was a thing myself. This move prevents ... e5 , however, so we need some adjustments.} c5 {Now that ... e5 has been made more difficult to achieve, we revisit the other way of challenging the white center. Somewhat surprisingly, we'll soon find ourselves in one of the rare variations of the Sicilian Dragon.} 7. O-O {Going for the endgame with dxc5 promises very little, so White decides to castle short. Now we're entering Sicilian waters.} cxd4 {Black should clarify the structure at once before White has a chance to change their mind.} 8. Nxd4 {Taking with a queen would look strange, no?} Nc6 {Now we're officially playing a rare line of the Dragon. White usually proceeds with Nde2 , and Black then goes for the plan of preparing ... b5 . It includes ... Rb8 and ... a6 , in case it's necessary. Black will have nothing to worry about in these structures.} *

