1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 {The kingside fianchetto is a favorite tool of players who like to keep it quiet and positional. White intends to continue with Bg2 , Nge2 , and O-O , getting a healthy central setup. The one major drawback of this variation is that it provides the opponent with complete freedom of action.} Bg7 {This move, and the next, are automatic. Since White opts for such a quiet setup, we can take all the time we want. This means we castle first and then decide what to do next.} 5. Bg2 {The g2 -bishop is quite helpful here, as it gives the e4 -pawn an additional layer of protection. The drawback of this approach is that the bishop is limited by a pawn for a very long time. Everything in life comes at a cost.} O-O {The speed with which Black is usually able to castle is one of the best features of the Pirc. Too many games are lost because the king is stuck in the center of the board.} 6. Nge2 {This move is the more natural development for the white knight, given that the light-squared bishop is on g2 . It's good to bear in mind the dual nature of this piece. The knight doesn't block the long diagonal, and the f2 -pawn is free to move, but e2 isn't always such a wonderful square. You could say the knight is sacrificing something for the greater good. :)} e5 {This central approach is almost always a good way to proceed. The e5 -pawn gives Black ample space in the center and restricts the e2 -knight, an additional bonus in this line.} 7. O-O {Nothing can be more natural than castling, but White won't be able to get the ideal setup in the center now. The weakness of the d4 -pawn is very fleeting, so Black has to act at once.} Nc6 {Black attacks the white center before White can play Be3 and protect their center properly. The d4 -pawn should make a decision now. It has two moves, and they lead to vastly different positions.} 8. d5 {White can always close the center with this move and get something close to the King's Indian Defense. The problem is that White usually ends up in a bad King's Indian, with the c2 -pawn blocked by a knight and no clear prospects. It's not any different here.} Ne7 {Black will play ... c6 next, undermining the d5 -pawn. White will face an unpleasant choice. They could either allow ... cxd5 or take on c6 . Either way, Black gets an extra pawn in the center and very good chances. That's the price of not having the pawn on c4 .} *

