1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 {The kingside fianchetto is a favorite tool of players who like to keep it quiet and positional. White intends to continue with Bg2 , Nge2 , and O-O , getting a healthy central setup. The one major drawback of this variation is that it provides the opponent with complete freedom of action.} Bg7 {This move, and the next, are automatic. Since White opts for such a quiet setup, we can take all the time we want. This means we castle first and then decide what to do next.} 5. Bg2 {The g2 -bishop is quite helpful here, as it gives the e4 -pawn an additional layer of protection. The drawback of this approach is that the bishop is limited by a pawn for a very long time. Everything in life comes at a cost.} O-O {The speed with which Black is usually able to castle is one of the best features of the Pirc. Too many games are lost because the king is stuck in the center of the board.} 6. Nge2 {This move is the more natural development for the white knight, given that the light-squared bishop is on g2 . It's good to bear in mind the dual nature of this piece. The knight doesn't block the long diagonal, and the f2 -pawn is free to move, but e2 isn't always such a wonderful square. You could say the knight is sacrificing something for the greater good. :)} e5 {This central approach is almost always a good way to proceed. The e5 -pawn gives Black ample space in the center and restricts the e2 -knight, an additional bonus in this line.} 7. O-O {Nothing can be more natural than castling, but White won't be able to get the ideal setup in the center now. The weakness of the d4 -pawn is very fleeting, so Black has to act at once.} Nc6 {Black attacks the white center before White can play Be3 and protect their center properly. The d4 -pawn should make a decision now. It has two moves, and they lead to vastly different positions.} 8. dxe5 {This move leads to an ending, and I was surprised to see many hundreds of games from this position. The truth is, White doesn't have any advantage to speak of. On the other hand, White probably would have chosen a different system on move 4 if they had been trying to get an advantage.} dxe5 {Black has no reason to fear the ending. By taking with a pawn, we ensure equal chances in the fight to come. When writing these words, I suddenly realized that this position offers a unique sight for this opening – a symmetrical structure!} 9. Bg5 {This move is White's best bet. White finds a weak spot in Black's structure, the c7 -pawn. In chess, it's essential to realize what exactly your opponent is threatening. Once we know this, the defense is usually much easier to conduct.} Qxd1 {Black certainly has some alternatives to this move. I chose it mainly because it's simple, and the ensuing idea is instructive.} 10. Rfxd1 {This way of taking back the queen is more popular. It's always difficult to understand which rook you should play. My experience is that no matter which rook you choose, you end up regretting it. :)} Ne8 {That's the instructive maneuver I mentioned earlier. It might look passive to play ... Ne8 , but in fact, Black's position is rock-solid now. Black protects the c7 -pawn and controls all the entry squares on the d-file. White can't create any threats here because there's absolutely nothing they could attack. Black proceeds by playing ... f6 , ... Rf7 , ... Be6 , and ... Bf8 , getting all their pieces onto lovely squares.} *

