ld follow the plans you made. It was Chigorin, I think, who said: “It's better to follow a bad plan than no plan at all“ or something to this effect. Following a good plan is a better option yet. :)} exd4 {Black clarifies the situation in the center of the board. White had firmly protected their pawns, and there was nothing more Black could do to add to the pressure. Taking on d4 opens the long diagonal for the g7 -bishop and the e-file for the rook. With the d4 -pawn gone, Black will focus on the e4 -pawn.} 9. Nxd4 {Needless to say, the dark-squared bishops are worth their weight in gold in these positions. That's just a fancy way of saying, 'Only move'. :)} Bd7 {This development is part of Black's plan anyway, and it's nice not to think about Nxc6 ruining our pawn structure on the queenside. From now on, this can always be answered by ... Bxc6 , adding to White's problems in the center.} 10. O-O {It's time to get the king out of the center. Both sides have completed the piece development and need to think about their longer-term plans. Over the next few moves, Black should act with some sense of urgency. This type of position tends to favor White in the long run, which means Black should have a clear idea of how to play it. Fortunately, we do. :)} Re8 {Well, that's why Black opened the e-file. The rook is excellently placed here, exerting the never-ending pressure on the e4 -pawn. White should now choose from many possible plans, and I'll cover their critical tries.} 11. Qd2 ({A very natural move, similar to our main line with} 11. Re1 {. Black's reaction is the same, and this simplifies the process of memorizing stuff. :)}) 11... Nxd4 {It's the beginning of a common theme for this line. Black liberates the c6 -square and starts a direct assault against the e4 -pawn. There are definitely plausible alternatives to the text, but I decided to keep it direct and simple. Life is complicated enough as it is.} 12. Bxd4 c5 ({This move is nice and forcing. Black gains space before playing ... Bc6 . If you are curious about possible alternatives, you could investigate} 12... b5 {instead, which leads to a complicated fight.}) 13. Bxf6 ({White probably isn't happy about abandoning the bishop pair, but the task of defending the e4 -pawn after} 13. Be3 Bc6 {isn't too tempting either. With hindsight, Qd2 looked natural but did very little to support the vital central pawn.}) 13... Qxf6 {This move keeps the d6 -pawn alive. Black has a pair of bishops now and excellent chances in the long term.} 14. Nd5 {Since White can't profit from attacking the d6 -pawn, it's natural to position the knight in the center.} Qd8 {Black keeps everything under control. I like unclear exchange sacrifices more than anyone, but it's just too early for tough decisions. Black has a great position as it is.} 15. c3 {White closes the long diagonal, hoping to limit Black's dark-squared bishop. Surprisingly, the c3 -pawn can become a target.} b5 {Balck starts the queenside offensive. The plan includes ... a5 , ... Rb8 , and ... b4 . In the long run, the pair of bishops and a mass of dangerous pawns on the queenside will be tricky for White to handle. White will need to start looking for counterplay soon.} *

