1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 {The kingside fianchetto is a favorite tool of players who like to keep it quiet and positional. White intends to continue with Bg2 , Nge2 , and O-O , getting a healthy central setup. The one major drawback of this variation is that it provides the opponent with complete freedom of action.} Bg7 {This move, and the next, are automatic. Since White opts for such a quiet setup, we can take all the time we want. This means we castle first and then decide what to do next.} 5. Bg2 {The g2 -bishop is quite helpful here, as it gives the e4 -pawn an additional layer of protection. The drawback of this approach is that the bishop is limited by a pawn for a very long time. Everything in life comes at a cost.} O-O {The speed with which Black is usually able to castle is one of the best features of the Pirc. Too many games are lost because the king is stuck in the center of the board.} 6. Nge2 {This move is the more natural development for the white knight, given that the light-squared bishop is on g2 . It's good to bear in mind the dual nature of this piece. The knight doesn't block the long diagonal, and the f2 -pawn is free to move, but e2 isn't always such a wonderful square. You could say the knight is sacrificing something for the greater good. :)} e5 {This central approach is almost always a good way to proceed. The e5 -pawn gives Black ample space in the center and restricts the e2 -knight, an additional bonus in this line.} 7. h3 {This little move is an integral part of White's plan. In this system, a lot depends on the safety of white pawns in the center. White's setup thus includes Be3 so that the d4 -pawn is covered twice and h3 so the bishop can go to e3 without being disturbed. Simple chess. :)} Nc6 {Black is piling up the pressure on the d4 -pawn. White is prepared for this and will play the next move without hesitation.} 8. Be3 {White is still following their plan. They only played h3 to make Be3 possible, and in chess, you should follow the plans you made. It was Chigorin, I think, who said: “It's better to follow a bad plan than no plan at all“ or something to this effect. Following a good plan is a better option yet. :)} exd4 {Black clarifies the situation in the center of the board. White had firmly protected their pawns, and there was nothing more Black could do to add to the pressure. Taking on d4 opens the long diagonal for the g7 -bishop and the e-file for the rook. With the d4 -pawn gone, Black will focus on the e4 -pawn.} 9. Nxd4 {Needless to say, the dark-squared bishops are worth their weight in gold in these positions. That's just a fancy way of saying, 'Only move'. :)} Bd7 {This development is part of Black's plan anyway, and it's nice not to think about Nxc6 ruining our pawn structure on the queenside. From now on, this can always be answered by ... Bxc6 , adding to White's problems in the center.} 10. O-O {It's time to get the king out of the center. Both sides have completed the piece development and need to think about their longer-term plans. Over the next few moves, Black should act with some sense of urgency. This type of position tends to favor White in the long run, which means Black should have a clear idea of how to play it. Fortunately, we do. :)} Re8 {Well, that's why Black opened the e-file. The rook is excellently placed here, exerting the never-ending pressure on the e4 -pawn. White should now choose from many possible plans, and I'll cover their critical tries.} 11. f4 {This move needs to treated with caution at best of times. White gains space but leaves a bunch weknesses behind. That's a useful general rule, in this position this move simply doesn't work.} Nxe4 {This simple trick leads to an advantage for Black. White can take back on e4 in two ways, both losing a piece after ... d5 . White has too many loose pawns in their structure to hope for a good outcome in any tactical skirmish.} *

