1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 {The kingside fianchetto is a favorite tool of players who like to keep it quiet and positional. White intends to continue with Bg2 , Nge2 , and O-O , getting a healthy central setup. The one major drawback of this variation is that it provides the opponent with complete freedom of action.} Bg7 {This move, and the next, are automatic. Since White opts for such a quiet setup, we can take all the time we want. This means we castle first and then decide what to do next.} 5. Bg2 {The g2 -bishop is quite helpful here, as it gives the e4 -pawn an additional layer of protection. The drawback of this approach is that the bishop is limited by a pawn for a very long time. Everything in life comes at a cost.} O-O {The speed with which Black is usually able to castle is one of the best features of the Pirc. Too many games are lost because the king is stuck in the center of the board.} 6. Nge2 {This move is the more natural development for the white knight, given that the light-squared bishop is on g2 . It's good to bear in mind the dual nature of this piece. The knight doesn't block the long diagonal, and the f2 -pawn is free to move, but e2 isn't always such a wonderful square. You could say the knight is sacrificing something for the greater good. :)} e5 {This central approach is almost always a good way to proceed. The e5 -pawn gives Black ample space in the center and restricts the e2 -knight, an additional bonus in this line.} 7. h3 {This little move is an integral part of White's plan. In this system, a lot depends on the safety of white pawns in the center. White's setup thus includes Be3 so that the d4 -pawn is covered twice and h3 so the bishop can go to e3 without being disturbed. Simple chess. :)} Nc6 {Black is piling up the pressure on the d4 -pawn. White is prepared for this and will play the next move without hesitation.} 8. Be3 {White is still following their plan. They only played h3 to make Be3 possible, and in chess, you should follow the plans you made. It was Chigorin, I think, who said: “It's better to follow a bad plan than no plan at all“ or something to this effect. Following a good plan is a better option yet. :)} exd4 {Black clarifies the situation in the center of the board. White had firmly protected their pawns, and there was nothing more Black could do to add to the pressure. Taking on d4 opens the long diagonal for the g7 -bishop and the e-file for the rook. With the d4 -pawn gone, Black will focus on the e4 -pawn.} 9. Nxd4 {Needless to say, the dark-squared bishops are worth their weight in gold in these positions. That's just a fancy way of saying, 'Only move'. :)} Bd7 {This development is part of Black's plan anyway, and it's nice not to think about Nxc6 ruining our pawn structure on the queenside. From now on, this can always be answered by ... Bxc6 , adding to White's problems in the center.} 10. O-O {It's time to get the king out of the center. Both sides have completed the piece development and need to think about their longer-term plans. Over the next few moves, Black should act with some sense of urgency. This type of position tends to favor White in the long run, which means Black should have a clear idea of how to play it. Fortunately, we do. :)} Re8 {Well, that's why Black opened the e-file. The rook is excellently placed here, exerting the never-ending pressure on the e4 -pawn. White should now choose from many possible plans, and I'll cover their critical tries.} 11. Re1 {A good move, showing that White knows what's essential in this position. Black is about to launch their counterplay against the e4 -pawn, and White is increasing their presence in the area.} Nxd4 {Black launches the central offensive. Our target is the e4 -pawn.} 12. Bxd4 c5 {Black expands in the center and on the queenside. In theory, this comes at the cost of weakening the d6 -pawn and the d5 -square. In this particular position, the black pieces are well-placed to deal with these potential problems.} 13. Be3 {Thanks to their 11th move, White can keep the pair of bishops without worrying about the safety of the e4 -pawn.} Bc6 {A natural continuation of the plan Black started with Nxd4 . The bishop is doing an excellent job here, attacking the e4 -pawn and covering the d5 -square.} 14. Qd3 {Both sides are trying to combine attack and defense. White develops the queen, defends the e4 -pawn, and prepares to play Rad1 . Fortunately, Black has enough resources to protect the d6 -pawn without sacrificing activity.} Re6 {Just like White did with the previous move, Black combines the best of two worlds with this rook lift. The d6 -pawn is firmly protected, and Black is ready to strengthen the pressure on White's center even further.} 15. Nd5 {Seeing that the pressure along the d-file doesn't bring much, White decides to establish the knight in the center of the board. The central knight is always a pretty sight to behold. In this position, though, Black can always take on d5 with the bishop should the white knight become annoying.} Qd7 {We already know that Black could take on d5 , but there is no rush. This knight isn't going anywhere. Black connects the rooks and threatens to increase the pressure on the white center with ... Rae8 .  Other promising plans include the queenside expansion with a well-known ... b5 . Even after the eventual ... Bd5 , the white bishops will find it tricky to find any targets in this position. The black bishop, on the other hand, will reign on the long diagonal after ... b5 and ... b4 .} *

