1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. e5 {The most direct approach and a very popular one. White's strategy, ideally, involves a pawn triangle d4 - e5 - f4 , limiting the g7 -bishop. Going for it so early in the game creates many unbalanced positions, and we don't mind that. :)} Nfd7 ({This modest retreat is both safer and more promising than} 5... dxe5 {, its equally popular alternative. The opening of the d-file has its dangers. Play will now revolve around the e5 -pawn. White should try to keep it there to block the g7 -bishop, and Black should try to undermine it.}) 6. exd6 {It's a possible move, although I find it somewhat inconsistent. White abandons the idea of blocking the g7 -bishop and goes for an unclear fight with Sicilian undertones.} cxd6 {After this forced recapture, we get a rare pawn structure, where Black seems to have played the Sicilian Dragon, and White chose one of these new-age openings that I never got to learn. :)} 7. Qd2 {That's the idea. White castles queenside and is clearly looking for a fight. The c-file is open, however, and it's not clear why c1 should be such a great location for the white king.} Nf6 {On d7 , this knight is in the way of the c8 -bishop, and Black decides to return it to the original square. Black's structure is safe enough to afford this time expenditure. We aren't castling yet in order not to invite an early attack with Bh6 , h4 , etc.} 8. O-O-O {It's a natural move, although White probably should think twice before playing it. The white king might not have a rosy future on c1 .} h6 {The easiest way to prevent White from playing Bh6 . Now White needs to decide where to place the g5 -bishop. In most lines, Black gets a harmonious setup by playing ... Nbd7 , ... a6 , ... b5 and ... Bb7 . As we know from many different lines of the Pirc, the c3 -knight is again badly placed. White has no easy plans here and faces an uphill battle.} *

