1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. e5 {The most direct approach and a very popular one. White's strategy, ideally, involves a pawn triangle d4 - e5 - f4 , limiting the g7 -bishop. Going for it so early in the game creates many unbalanced positions, and we don't mind that. :)} Nfd7 ({This modest retreat is both safer and more promising than} 5... dxe5 {, its equally popular alternative. The opening of the d-file has its dangers. Play will now revolve around the e5 -pawn. White should try to keep it there to block the g7 -bishop, and Black should try to undermine it.}) 6. Nd5 {It's tempting to attack the e7 -pawn, creating winning threats. Since Black is unlikely to leave the pawn unprotected, it doesn't achieve anything.} Nc6 {Black defends the e7 -pawn and is ready to push the white pieces back by playing ... Nb6 and ... h6 . White will find it difficult to defend their central positions, with the kingside still being fully undeveloped.} *

