1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. e5 {The most direct approach and a very popular one. White's strategy, ideally, involves a pawn triangle d4 - e5 - f4 , limiting the g7 -bishop. Going for it so early in the game creates many unbalanced positions, and we don't mind that. :)} Nfd7 ({This modest retreat is both safer and more promising than} 5... dxe5 {, its equally popular alternative. The opening of the d-file has its dangers. Play will now revolve around the e5 -pawn. White should try to keep it there to block the g7 -bishop, and Black should try to undermine it.}) 6. f4 {It is White's most principled reply. The pawn triangle, d4 - e5 - f4 , deserves some attention. If White keeps it intact for a long time, the g7 -bishop will have all the potential to become a passive onlooker, a most unfortunate outcome for this opening. Black isn't helpless, however, and can undermine the white central pawns by playing ... c5 , ... f6 , or, sometimes, ... h6 and ... g5 .} O-O {Castling kingside is safe in this position. White isn't developed enough to start an immediate attack.} 7. Nf3 {A good developing move that supports the vital central pawns, and plans to finish the development and castle short. White only needs two more moves to do this, but two moves in chess can be an eternity.} Nb6 {This move might feel like we're moving in the wrong direction, but in fact, we are creating ideal conditions for playing ... f6 .} ({It was maybe possible to play} 7... f6 {at once, but I don't really want to find out if the attack after} 8. Bc4+ {and h4 would lead to checkmate. Once the c4 -square is controlled, we can play ... f6 without fear.}) 8. Bd3 {The c4 -square being sadly unavailable, White goes for the other, seemingly active, development. Black's reaction against any other move will be the same, ... f6 and fight.} f6 {We knew this move was coming for a while now, yet let us savor this moment. White's center starts crumbling now, and Black takes over the initiative.} 9. Bh4 {White retreats since opening the e-file with the king still on e1 is decidedly unattractive.} fxe5 {It's a good moment to take, with the f4 -pawn hanging and the white king in the center of the board. The b6 -knight is doing a great job of controlling c4 and d5 .} 10. fxe5 {My computer claims White could sac the f4 -pawn, but let's keep it real. Nobody sacrifices pawns anymore.} Bg4 {Black increases the pressure on the white center and can cause even more trouble by playing ... Nc6 next. White will probably end up losing a central pawn for dubious compensation.} *

