1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Nf3 ({It is a popular move, leading to a position played thousands of times. The reason behind this number is that White has two ways of reaching this position, the other being playing} 5. Nf3 {first and 5.Bg5 later. White goes for the quick development but blocks the f2 -pawn, meaning the plan of playing f4 and e5 no longer exists.}) 5... O-O ({This is the most natural and popular move, although other moves exist, like} 5... d5 $5 {, for instance. Throughout this course, it has been our strategy to castle whenever possible, so let's stick to it. :)}) 6. e5 {This move is how the engine wants to play in this position. It hasn't been very successful so far, but some players have started looking in this direction recently.} Nfd7 {An ambitious way of playing, going for a complex position. We could also take on e5 and look for exchanges.} 7. Qe2 {This unusual development is the point behind e5 . White defends the e5 -pawn and prepares to castle long. The light-squared bishop is unlikely to be happy on f1 , but on the other hand, you can't please them all.} dxe5 {The timing is a very delicate issue in this line. It's important to take on e5 before White had a chance to castle.} 8. dxe5 {This move does not pose any problems for Black because White will find it surprisingly difficult to castle long now. This makes the entire plan with Qe2 look rather pointless.} Nb6 {This is an excellent move that accomplishes many goals. Most importantly, Black opens the d-file, preventing White from castling long. The b6 -knight controls the d5 -square and the c8 - h3 diagonal is now open, allowing Black to continue developing naturally. White must begin searching for alternative plans.} *

