1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Nf3 ({It is a popular move, leading to a position played thousands of times. The reason behind this number is that White has two ways of reaching this position, the other being playing} 5. Nf3 {first and 5.Bg5 later. White goes for the quick development but blocks the f2 -pawn, meaning the plan of playing f4 and e5 no longer exists.}) 5... O-O ({This is the most natural and popular move, although other moves exist, like} 5... d5 $5 {, for instance. Throughout this course, it has been our strategy to castle whenever possible, so let's stick to it. :)}) 6. e5 {This move is how the engine wants to play in this position. It hasn't been very successful so far, but some players have started looking in this direction recently.} Nfd7 {An ambitious way of playing, going for a complex position. We could also take on e5 and look for exchanges.} 7. Qe2 {This unusual development is the point behind e5 . White defends the e5 -pawn and prepares to castle long. The light-squared bishop is unlikely to be happy on f1 , but on the other hand, you can't please them all.} dxe5 {The timing is a very delicate issue in this line. It's important to take on e5 before White had a chance to castle.} 8. O-O-O {It is by far the most challenging continuation. White castles long, using the fact that the e7 -pawn is vulnerable. White's threats could become unbearable soon, which is why we need to be extremely precise.} h6 {This little move is the first step in fortifying our defenses on the kingside. It's not immediately obvious, but the h4 -square is very important. We will see exactly why in a bit.} 9. Bh4 {The white bishop has to keep attacking the e7 -pawn while other bishop moves would have allowed Black to take on d4 .} e4 ({An important defensive resource. The pawn could not be saved anyway, but by playing this way, Black ensures that the d-file remains closed. Now we see why including h6 was important. If Black had played} 9... e4 {immediately, White would have been able to play Qxe4 and h4 , resulting in a strong attack.}) 10. Nxe4 {In this position, this is a more natural capture. Taking with the queen on e4 would run into the same ... Nf6 , forcing the queen to retreat.} Nf6 {This move completes Black's plan. As in many other lines, the d7 -knight was in the way of other minor pieces. The knight returns to its most natural square, using the fact that the pawn on f6 would fortify Black's kingside. It's not easy to develop White's kingside now, and White would likely lose some time moving the queen. We are likely to get an interesting game with mutual chances.} *

