1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Nf3 ({It is a popular move, leading to a position played thousands of times. The reason behind this number is that White has two ways of reaching this position, the other being playing} 5. Nf3 {first and 5.Bg5 later. White goes for the quick development but blocks the f2 -pawn, meaning the plan of playing f4 and e5 no longer exists.}) 5... O-O ({This is the most natural and popular move, although other moves exist, like} 5... d5 $5 {, for instance. Throughout this course, it has been our strategy to castle whenever possible, so let's stick to it. :)}) 6. Qd2 {With this move, White prepares to castle long. Given enough time, White's next few moves would include h4 , Bh6 , h5 , and checkmate. Fortunately, we have many resources to prevent this from happening.} d5 {We usually create counterplay in the center by playing ... c5 or ... e5 , but we are flexible. :) White can't avoid opening the center now, and this largely prevents any attacking ideas White might have had.} 7. e5 {This would normally be White's reaction to ... d5 , consolidating the pawn center and blocking the g7 -bishop. The position of the bishop on g5 changes everything, as you will see very soon.} Ne4 {This move, in a way, is a simple fork. Black attacks the white queen and the g5 -bishop. Surprisingly, White is already in some trouble.} 8. Qe3 {A sad necessity. White would have liked to take the e4 -knight but has no reasonable squares to move the f3 -knight to after Black takes back. It's one of the unfortunate side-effects of the g5 -square being unavailable.} Nxg5 {Black gets a pair of bishops. The position might look fairly closed, but it's an illusion. White's center is already crumbling.} 9. Qxg5 {This strange recapture is still the lesser evil. The f3 -knight needs to stay put to defend the central pawns.} c5 {Black is opening up the position, and White is soon to be left with a weakness on e5 and a tough defense ahead. It's interesting to see just how little potential White has without their dark-squared bishop.} *

