1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Nf3 ({It is a popular move, leading to a position played thousands of times. The reason behind this number is that White has two ways of reaching this position, the other being playing} 5. Nf3 {first and 5.Bg5 later. White goes for the quick development but blocks the f2 -pawn, meaning the plan of playing f4 and e5 no longer exists.}) 5... O-O ({This is the most natural and popular move, although other moves exist, like} 5... d5 $5 {, for instance. Throughout this course, it has been our strategy to castle whenever possible, so let's stick to it. :)}) 6. Qd2 {With this move, White prepares to castle long. Given enough time, White's next few moves would include h4 , Bh6 , h5 , and checkmate. Fortunately, we have many resources to prevent this from happening.} d5 {We usually create counterplay in the center by playing ... c5 or ... e5 , but we are flexible. :) White can't avoid opening the center now, and this largely prevents any attacking ideas White might have had.} 7. Bxf6 {Many players seem attracted to this move – after all, White wins a central pawn. It turns out to be a positional mistake.} exf6 {This recapture is the reason why 7.Bxf6 is not a great move. By moving the pawn to f6 , Black opens the e-file and creates the breakthrough possibilities with ... f5 . Suddenly, White has no good options.} 8. exd5 {It's not how White would like to capture the d5 -pawn, but taking the pawn with a knight in this position would leave White crumbling after ... f5 .} Nd7 {By moving the knight to b6 , Black will easily win back the d5 -pawn. After that, Black will have two bishops and a very pleasant position.} *

