1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Nf3 ({It is a popular move, leading to a position played thousands of times. The reason behind this number is that White has two ways of reaching this position, the other being playing} 5. Nf3 {first and 5.Bg5 later. White goes for the quick development but blocks the f2 -pawn, meaning the plan of playing f4 and e5 no longer exists.}) 5... O-O ({This is the most natural and popular move, although other moves exist, like} 5... d5 $5 {, for instance. Throughout this course, it has been our strategy to castle whenever possible, so let's stick to it. :)}) 6. Qd2 {With this move, White prepares to castle long. Given enough time, White's next few moves would include h4 , Bh6 , h5 , and checkmate. Fortunately, we have many resources to prevent this from happening.} d5 {We usually create counterplay in the center by playing ... c5 or ... e5 , but we are flexible. :) White can't avoid opening the center now, and this largely prevents any attacking ideas White might have had.} 7. exd5 {This move is White's most prudent reaction. They don't get much of an advantage, but at least get a nice, playable position.} Nxd5 {We take back the pawn at once, of course. The structure now is more reminiscent of some other openings, like the Scandinavian, for instance.} 8. Bh6 {This is the most challenging continuation. The g7 -bishop could become very strong, so White trades it when it's still possible.} Nxc3 {White is slightly ahead in development and has some attacking chances. That's why it's useful for us to exchange some pieces.} 9. Bxg7 {White includes this move to take back on c3 with the queen. There's no reason to spoil the pawn structure by playing bxc3 .} Kxg7 10. Qxc3 {The white queen occupies a lovely position on c3 , but we shouldn't overestimate White's threats. The discovered check won't kill us. :)} Nd7 {This knight is going to f6 . It's a great spot, and the black king will feel much better once it has some defenders.} 11. O-O-O {The white king is perfectly safe on c1 . The h1 -rook will later join the game via e1 .} Nf6 {With this move, the black knight reaches its destination, and the position calms down a lot. Both kings are safe, and the time has come for us to draw some conclusions. White has a slight space advantage, and Black has some lovely squares for the pieces. The knight is perfect on f6 , the queen will go to d6 , and the bishop will join the fray at g4 or e6 . We have an interesting fight ahead of us.} *

