{Black ignores the hanging knight on f6 and goes for the counterattack. White's position is already beyond repair. After exf6 exf6 , Black will get back the piece with interest.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. Nf3 {It's a decent move that enjoys some popularity, online and over the board. However, its slight problem is that it does nothing to stop Black's traditional play in the center.} c5 {This typical shot works well in this position. Black opens the long diagonal, and, more often than not, the g5 -bishop turns out to be misplaced.} 7. e5 {This move has been played in a million online games. Playing e5 is often premature, and in this position, it simply loses.} cxd4 *

