1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. Nf3 {It's a decent move that enjoys some popularity, online and over the board. However, its slight problem is that it does nothing to stop Black's traditional play in the center.} c5 {This typical shot works well in this position. Black opens the long diagonal, and, more often than not, the g5 -bishop turns out to be misplaced.} 7. dxc5 {It's the most natural reaction. White hopes for a queen trade, but that's wishful thinking, plain and simple.} Qa5 {This is the usual way of dealing with dc5 in various lines of the Pirc. Black threatens ... Nxe4 , a threat White has to take seriously. This allows us to take on c5 with the queen, keeping our pawn structure intact.} 8. Bd3 {This is a possible move. White protects the e4 -pawn, and yet this approach has a slight problem. After Black's next move, White will have to start preparing to castle queenside anyway, and 8.Bd3 can be seen as a loss of time.} Qxc5 {Black regains the pawn and prevents White from castling kingside. You can see how misplaced the g5 -bishop can be in these structures. The natural plan with Qe2 and Be3 is no longer possible. Once the fight heats up, the white bishop could be missing from the action on the queenside.} *

