1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. Nf3 {It's a decent move that enjoys some popularity, online and over the board. However, its slight problem is that it does nothing to stop Black's traditional play in the center.} c5 {This typical shot works well in this position. Black opens the long diagonal, and, more often than not, the g5 -bishop turns out to be misplaced.} 7. dxc5 {It's the most natural reaction. White hopes for a queen trade, but that's wishful thinking, plain and simple.} Qa5 {This is the usual way of dealing with dc5 in various lines of the Pirc. Black threatens ... Nxe4 , a threat White has to take seriously. This allows us to take on c5 with the queen, keeping our pawn structure intact.} 8. Qd2 {Covering the e4 -pawn and preparing to castle long. You will often see this dance, ... Qa5 , Qd2 , ... Qc5 , throughout this course.} Qxc5 {Black takes back the pawn and retains the pawn structure intact. The black queen controls the c5 - g1 diagonal, forcing White to castle long. In these positions, you see why having the bishop on g5 changes the course of play so drastically – White can never play Be3 and disturb the queen on c5 .} 9. O-O-O {White has no choice but to castle queenside. The long-term king safety will be a permanent concern for White. If you compare this to the main lines of the Sicilian Dragon, you can tell just how much more vulnerable White's position is. The f-pawn would be happier on f3 , and the bishop should be on e3 , etc.} Be6 {This is a good, solid approach. Black prevents a possible plan with Bxf6 and Nd5 .} 10. Nd4 {It's difficult to think of a different plan. In this way, White at least gets a pair of bishops, for what it's worth.} Nc6 {Forcing White's hand. The knight is well-placed on c6 , controlling a number of vital squares.} 11. Nxe6 {White probably won't resist the temptation to take the bishop. Black is doing well after other moves, too.} fxe6 {Black doesn't mind this change in pawn structure. The d5 -square is now firmly under control, and the f8 -rook suddenly got new opportunities along the f-file. Black threatens ... Ng4 with a devastating effect. White will have to play very well over the next few moves to come out of this unscathed.} *

