1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. e5 {This move comes way too early. White is not ready for an altercation in the center yet, not with the king on e1 and the kingside undeveloped.} Ng4 {Creating all sorts of unpleasant threats, such as ... f6 , ... c5 , and ... Ne3 .} *

