1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. Qd2 {This is a major way to continue. White plans to castle long and slowly build up a kingside attack. Surprisingly, the white queen turns out to be a tactical vulnerability, as we will see shortly.} h6 {This marks the beginning of a short tactical sequence. It's vital to force the white bishop onto an unprotected square.} 7. Bxf6 {A possible move, and it is better than it looks. White saves some time by refusing to move back, but this bishop will be missed.} exf6 {I like this way of taking on f6 , whenever possible. The appearance of the pawn on f6 makes our king even safer, and the opening of the e-file gives us additional possibilities. We'll continue with ... f5 or ... d5 , blasting files and diagonals open.} *

