1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. Qd2 {This is a major way to continue. White plans to castle long and slowly build up a kingside attack. Surprisingly, the white queen turns out to be a tactical vulnerability, as we will see shortly.} h6 {This marks the beginning of a short tactical sequence. It's vital to force the white bishop onto an unprotected square.} 7. Bh4 {It's definitely more natural for White to keep the bishop. Unless you have seen it before, Black's next move will likely come as a surprise to you.} e5 {This beautiful trick was first played by GM Tkachiev in 2000. At the time, information didn't travel quite as fast as it does today, and I still remember Vlad telling me about this move a few weeks later in a restaurant in Istanbul. Black exploits the white queen's vulnerability to achieve the central breakthrough White did so much to prevent.} 8. dxe5 {This is certainly not the best way to react to Black's idea. Despite all appearances, White will end up with a worse ending.} Nxe4 {This is the point, of course. White will have to exchange queens and defend for a while, not a dream outcome from an opening.} ({After Bxd8 Nxd2 Bxc7 Nxf1 Kxf1} 8... dxe5 {Bxe5 Bxe5} 9. fxe5 Nc6 10. Nf3 Bf5 {, Black will win the pawn back, while White struggles to coordinate in a slightly worse endgame.}) *

