1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. f4 {Playing f4 is a central part of White's plan, and many players choose to play it immediately. It is a principled approach, though committing to f4 so early comes with certain drawbacks as well.} O-O {As is often the case, ensuring the king's safety first is the simplest and safest approach. Depending on White's reaction, we might decide on different ways to continue.} 6. Qd2 {This is a major way to continue. White plans to castle long and slowly build up a kingside attack. Surprisingly, the white queen turns out to be a tactical vulnerability, as we will see shortly.} h6 {This marks the beginning of a short tactical sequence. It's vital to force the white bishop onto an unprotected square.} 7. Bh4 {It's definitely more natural for White to keep the bishop. Unless you have seen it before, Black's next move will likely come as a surprise to you.} e5 {This beautiful trick was first played by GM Tkachiev in 2000. At the time, information didn't travel quite as fast as it does today, and I still remember Vlad telling me about this move a few weeks later in a restaurant in Istanbul. Black exploits the white queen's vulnerability to achieve the central breakthrough White did so much to prevent.} 8. fxe5 {Of two ways to take the pawn, this is the better option. White frees the f4 -square for the queen, which becomes relevant in some variations.} Nxe4 ({This continuation leads to a highly complex position. If you prefer simplicity, you might want to consider the alternative,} 8... dxe5 9. dxe5 Qxd2+ 10. Kxd2 Ng4 11. Nd5 Nc6 {with a very promising ending.}) 9. Qf4 {This demonstrates why freeing the f4 -square was important. White defends the bishop while keeping the queens on the board. Black's response is now forced.} Ng5 {The most unusual square for the knight. In this or any other opening.} 10. O-O-O {White should use the opportunity to get the king out of the center. White intends to continue with Nf3 and create a range of unpleasant threats. Black's reaction is forced.} dxe5 {By taking on e5 , we ensure that White will be left with a weakness in the center of the board. This gives us much-needed counterplay.} 11. dxe5 {This recapture is, of course, forced. Now, Black must choose the next move carefully.} Qe8 {This is the only move that works for Black. We need to get out of the d-file while avoiding the e7 -square. Now, the weakness of the e5 -pawn will give us enough play, and we can always attack it further with ... Nc6 . The only thing we have to watch out for is the possibility of the white knight making it to  f6 .} *

