1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Qd2 {The logical follow-up to 4.Bg5 and a very popular choice. White hasn't committed the f-pawn yet and keeps things flexible. Somewhat surprisingly, it leads to quiet, positional play.} h6 {I like this move best, preventing Bh6 once and for all. Now White has a choice.} 6. Bf4 {This move looks strange to me, but the huge online community seems to disagree. The f4 -bishop can sometimes support the break with e5 , but will also be vulnerable to ... Nh5 , ... g5 , and ... e5 in various places.} a6 {This move is a rare guest in our repertoire, as we usually go for faster development. Here, however, White spent a considerable time playing Bg5 and later Bf4 , so we can afford the luxury of spending two moves to expand on the queenside with ... a6 and ... b5 .} 7. O-O-O {This is the most natural approach. The position is pretty closed, and the king is safe on c1 , at least for now.} b5 {As the saying goes, if you played ... a6 , you should follow it up with ... b5 . :) Now White has to reckon with the possibility of ... b4 .} 8. f3 {It makes sense to defend the e4 -pawn, but this approach is slow and doesn't pose any problems.} Nbd7 {Black has an easy game here. The plan is to go ... Nb6 , ... b4 , ... a5 , and attack. White will find it tough to generate enough counterplay here as Black's position is rock-solid.} *

