1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Qd2 {The logical follow-up to 4.Bg5 and a very popular choice. White hasn't committed the f-pawn yet and keeps things flexible. Somewhat surprisingly, it leads to quiet, positional play.} h6 {I like this move best, preventing Bh6 once and for all. Now White has a choice.} 6. Be3 ({It's not a bad square for the bishop, but then again, maybe White should have played the system with} 6. Be3 {. Getting ... h6 for free turns out to be useful, as Black continues to harass the white bishop.}) 6... Ng4 {Giving White no time to consolidate. If White were able to play f3 or h3 , the e3 -bishop would start enjoying the undisturbed existence.} 7. Bf4 {White has no other options if they want to keep this bishop. Sadly, the f4 -square will not prove safe either.} Nc6 {That's a lovely moment. Black attacks the d4 -pawn, and White has many ways of dealing with this threat. What makes this case peculiar is that after any plausible move, Black can play ... e5 ! and get a good position.} *

