1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Qd2 {The logical follow-up to 4.Bg5 and a very popular choice. White hasn't committed the f-pawn yet and keeps things flexible. Somewhat surprisingly, it leads to quiet, positional play.} h6 {I like this move best, preventing Bh6 once and for all. Now White has a choice.} 6. Bh4 {To me, this move looks like White's most natural reply. In a way, it's also the most consistent. You play 4.Bg5 if you think that the h4 - d8 -diagonal has some potential, and then you might stick around for a while. :)} g5 {Well, I like following clear plans. Black hunts the white bishop down, hoping that the dark-squared bishop will become a monster (in a good way) in the absence of the main rival.} 7. Bg3 Nh5 {Weakening our position with g5 only makes sense because we catch the bishop. We certainly have some long-term issues on the kingside, but we also have the g7 -bishop reigning supreme on the dark squares.} 8. Nge2 {This move looks clever and sophisticated, but it only makes sense if Black takes on g3 at once. In all other scenarios, the knight is a badly placed piece and prevents White's kingside from developing.} c5 {Black postpones taking the bishop for now. It's not like it could run away, right? The e2 -knight is in the way of other pieces, and exchanging the queens won't change that. Black opens the long diagonal and gets a great position.} *

