1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Qd2 {The logical follow-up to 4.Bg5 and a very popular choice. White hasn't committed the f-pawn yet and keeps things flexible. Somewhat surprisingly, it leads to quiet, positional play.} h6 {I like this move best, preventing Bh6 once and for all. Now White has a choice.} 6. Bh4 {To me, this move looks like White's most natural reply. In a way, it's also the most consistent. You play 4.Bg5 if you think that the h4 - d8 -diagonal has some potential, and then you might stick around for a while. :)} g5 {Well, I like following clear plans. Black hunts the white bishop down, hoping that the dark-squared bishop will become a monster (in a good way) in the absence of the main rival.} 7. Bg3 Nh5 {Weakening our position with g5 only makes sense because we catch the bishop. We certainly have some long-term issues on the kingside, but we also have the g7 -bishop reigning supreme on the dark squares.} 8. O-O-O {This is the most popular move. White castles before committing to anything else, especially because Black can't do the same. Black's kingside is no longer a safe place for the king, and, for now, it will have to stay in the center. Fortunately, the position is closed, and Black can afford the luxury of slowly preparing the queenside castling.} Nd7 {Not only a good developing move but also a positional threat. Given time, Black will go ... c5 , opening the long diagonal. This is a threat that White should take seriously.} 9. e5 {This central advance is the most frequent way to fight for the initiative. White creates some unpleasant threats and forces Black to abandon aggressive plans for now.} Nb6 {We have encountered this move before. The b6 -square isn't the most frequent spot for the black knight, but it can be useful to cover some vulnerable squares. With the white pawn on e5 , we should also watch the e6 -square, the task for our light-squared bishop.} 10. Bd3 {It's a logical developing move that prevents ... Bf5 . For all its qualities, it's not very popular yet, perhaps out of concern for the well-being of the e5 -pawn. The correspondence players have discovered it, although without much success.} Be6 {We are not sufficiently developed to start pawn-grabbing (just trust me on this). As is the case in the main line after Qe3 , our task is to get the bishop out, play ... Qd7 , and castle. The f5 -square is unavailable, but e6 will do just as well.} 11. Nge2 {Once the bishop is out, e2 is a better square for the white knight. Playing Nf3 might look natural but would leave White wondering what to do next. From e2 , the knight can go to g3 or support the break with f4 .} Qd7 {With this move, Black prepares to castle queenside. Once the king is safe, we can confidently claim to have adequate chances in the fight to come. The position has been tested in a few correspondence games, and Black held their own without much headache.} *

