1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {This is a very central line that we need to cover in detail. The main positional idea behind it is that the bishop gets out before White plays f4 so that White doesn't have a problem with the bishop being limited by the pawn chain. In life, everything comes at a cost, and this line is no exception. The g5 -bishop often becomes vulnerable, and this gives us new opportunities.} Bg7 {A popular move and our standard reaction in most lines. Black could choose a strategy that keeps the bishop on f8 , but I believe in development and castling my king. :)} 5. Qd2 {The logical follow-up to 4.Bg5 and a very popular choice. White hasn't committed the f-pawn yet and keeps things flexible. Somewhat surprisingly, it leads to quiet, positional play.} h6 {I like this move best, preventing Bh6 once and for all. Now White has a choice.} 6. Bh4 {To me, this move looks like White's most natural reply. In a way, it's also the most consistent. You play 4.Bg5 if you think that the h4 - d8 -diagonal has some potential, and then you might stick around for a while. :)} g5 {Well, I like following clear plans. Black hunts the white bishop down, hoping that the dark-squared bishop will become a monster (in a good way) in the absence of the main rival.} 7. Bg3 Nh5 {Weakening our position with g5 only makes sense because we catch the bishop. We certainly have some long-term issues on the kingside, but we also have the g7 -bishop reigning supreme on the dark squares.} 8. O-O-O {This is the most popular move. White castles before committing to anything else, especially because Black can't do the same. Black's kingside is no longer a safe place for the king, and, for now, it will have to stay in the center. Fortunately, the position is closed, and Black can afford the luxury of slowly preparing the queenside castling.} Nd7 {Not only a good developing move but also a positional threat. Given time, Black will go ... c5 , opening the long diagonal. This is a threat that White should take seriously.} 9. e5 {This central advance is the most frequent way to fight for the initiative. White creates some unpleasant threats and forces Black to abandon aggressive plans for now.} Nb6 {We have encountered this move before. The b6 -square isn't the most frequent spot for the black knight, but it can be useful to cover some vulnerable squares. With the white pawn on e5 , we should also watch the e6 -square, the task for our light-squared bishop.} 10. Qe3 {Now that the central pawn is in danger, White defends it with this elegant move. We know that Black's plan involves castling queenside, and thus the next move shouldn't come as a surprise.} Bf5 {Chess can be a simple game, especially when following a clear plan. Since we don't want to castle short, it is a bit draughty, after all, we should try to castle long. Ergo, we should move the bishop to be able to play ... Qd7 and castle. You could also consider ... Bg4 or ... Be6 . In a few moves, we'll have a safe king and a complicated position with mutual chances, which is exactly why we play this opening.} *

