1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bd3 {Grandmasters don't play this very often, but online, it's everybody's favorite. The bishop is well placed on d3 , giving an extra bit of protection to the e4 -pawn. On the flip side, the d4 -pawn, and the dark squares in general, can become vulnerable.} O-O {Black quietly brings the king into safety before deciding on what to do next. You can already tell how different this line is compared to, say, the Austrian Attack. The two sides haven't really had contact yet, and will be able to complete their piece development and castle before anything difficult happens.} 6. h3 {White controls the g4 -square, preventing some of Black's counterplay. Needless to say, it's a slow approach that fails to pose many problems. As in many other lines, the h3 -pawn stops ... Bg4 but doesn't do anything else.} Nc6 {One of the many possible ways to play. Black develops the knight to an active square and plans to proceed with ... e5 to get a stronghold in the center.} 7. O-O {White decides to castle, and it's probably for the best. Any idea that involves castling queenside would take forever to implement. White is quite happy to have prevented ... Bg4 and has a reasonably safe, although not very threatening, position.} e5 {Black gets to put a pawn in the center without any concessions and has, in my opinion, a more harmonious setup. The arising structures are very similar to the King's Indian Defense, and the h3 -pawn can become a target in the long run.} *

