1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bd3 {Grandmasters don't play this very often, but online, it's everybody's favorite. The bishop is well placed on d3 , giving an extra bit of protection to the e4 -pawn. On the flip side, the d4 -pawn, and the dark squares in general, can become vulnerable.} O-O {Black quietly brings the king into safety before deciding on what to do next. You can already tell how different this line is compared to, say, the Austrian Attack. The two sides haven't really had contact yet, and will be able to complete their piece development and castle before anything difficult happens.} 6. Be3 {This is a solid developing move, giving the extra cover to the potentially vulnerable d4 -pawn. Having said that, I suspect the actual reason for playing Be3 is the desire for perfect symmetry. The problem with symmetry, however, is that you'll have to break it on the next move.} Nbd7 {Since the d4 -pawn is well-protected now, our default plans with ... Bg4 and ... Nc6 are less effective. The knight is equally well placed on d7 , supporting the central push with ... e5 , and the c8 -bishop has a bright future. But more on this later. :)} 7. O-O {Having run out of natural developing moves, White finally decides to castle short. The more ambitious plans of playing Qd2 and castling queenside do not go together well with 5.Bd3 .} e5 {With this move, Black establishes a firm central presence. Over the next couple of moves, we can either decide to keep the pawn on e5 or take on d4 , followed by ... b6 and ... Bb7 . Either way, Black has easy play. And it's much more difficult for White's somewhat awkwardly developed pieces to generate any activity.} *

