{Black exerts massive pressure on White's center. White has problems of both structural and tactical nature here. Their central positions are unsustainable, especially since Be3 loses to 11...Ne5 , with either knight. :)} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bd3 {Grandmasters don't play this very often, but online, it's everybody's favorite. The bishop is well placed on d3 , giving an extra bit of protection to the e4 -pawn. On the flip side, the d4 -pawn, and the dark squares in general, can become vulnerable.} O-O {Black quietly brings the king into safety before deciding on what to do next. You can already tell how different this line is compared to, say, the Austrian Attack. The two sides haven't really had contact yet, and will be able to complete their piece development and castle before anything difficult happens.} 6. O-O {Nothing can be more natural than castling in this position and, duly, it's the most popular move. Its only drawback is that it does very little to stop the plan with ... Bg4 and ... Nc6 .} Bg4 {A nice developing move that begins the play against White's weakness on d4 . We'll probably have to abandon this bishop, but as often in this opening, the pair of bishops are not very powerful.} 7. h3 ({This pin is difficult to live with, and White immediately clarifies the situation. White has some alternatives, of course, but in tournament practice,} 7. h3 {is almost invariably played.}) 7... Bxf3 {By now there is really no choice. Clearly, we're not going back. :)} 8. Qxf3 {White has obtained a pair of bishops, but it came at a cost. The d4 -pawn is vulnerable and the white pieces are not well-placed to deal with it.} Nfd7 {It is perhaps the most flexible way of beginning our play. By keeping the knight on b8 for the time being, we keep the option of playing ... c5 . White will find it difficult to defend the d4 -pawn without some minor concessions.} 9. Ne2 {This move, defending the d4 -pawn and preparing to consolidate with c3 , looks very logical but has a surprising tactical problem.} c5 {Now we see why Black refrained from playing ... Nc6 earlier. Our attack in the center will be much more efficient when more of our forces join in.} 10. c3 {With this move, White tries to keep the pawn center, which begins to look more like a liability than an asset. More broadly, this type of battle is very typical for this entire opening. White is allowed to occupy the center early in the game, but very often this center becomes a bit shaky. :)} Nc6 *

