1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bd3 {Grandmasters don't play this very often, but online, it's everybody's favorite. The bishop is well placed on d3 , giving an extra bit of protection to the e4 -pawn. On the flip side, the d4 -pawn, and the dark squares in general, can become vulnerable.} O-O {Black quietly brings the king into safety before deciding on what to do next. You can already tell how different this line is compared to, say, the Austrian Attack. The two sides haven't really had contact yet, and will be able to complete their piece development and castle before anything difficult happens.} 6. O-O {Nothing can be more natural than castling in this position and, duly, it's the most popular move. Its only drawback is that it does very little to stop the plan with ... Bg4 and ... Nc6 .} Bg4 {A nice developing move that begins the play against White's weakness on d4 . We'll probably have to abandon this bishop, but as often in this opening, the pair of bishops are not very powerful.} 7. h3 ({This pin is difficult to live with, and White immediately clarifies the situation. White has some alternatives, of course, but in tournament practice,} 7. h3 {is almost invariably played.}) 7... Bxf3 {By now there is really no choice. Clearly, we're not going back. :)} 8. Qxf3 {White has obtained a pair of bishops, but it came at a cost. The d4 -pawn is vulnerable and the white pieces are not well-placed to deal with it.} Nfd7 {It is perhaps the most flexible way of beginning our play. By keeping the knight on b8 for the time being, we keep the option of playing ... c5 . White will find it difficult to defend the d4 -pawn without some minor concessions.} 9. Be3 {It is a good way to defend the central pawn, but the fix will prove temporary since Black has many ways to increase the pressure. White having to defend so early in the game is proof of something being slightly wrong about this whole setup with Bd3 .} Nc6 {Black attacks the d4 -pawn once more, and it becomes clear that White will not be able to keep the bishop pair forever. It's also worth noting that Black has no weaknesses in their position, which means that even after the opening phase is over, White will find it difficult to play.} 10. Ne2 ({One of the two ways White has to save the pawn. The alternative,} 10. d5 {, has the drawback of opening the long diagonal for the g7 -bishop. Black has a large choice of possible plans now.}) 10... Nb4 {It's probably the simplest approach. With this move, Black makes sure that White will not be able to keep the pair of bishops. It also serves to free the path for the c-pawn to begin the play with ... c7 - c5 .} ({There is also nothing wrong with} 10... e5 {, aiming for a more complex battle.}) 11. Bg5 {It's an understandable attempt to keep a healthy pawn structure since White can take back on d3 with a queen now. On the flip side, the d4 -pawn is vulnerable again.} c5 {Black continues attacking the d4 -pawn, trying to make it move. The g7 -bishop and the d7 -knight will get a lot of interesting new prospects once this pawn is gone.} 12. c3 {White clearly has to keep on defending the central pawn. Now, for a moment, it might look like White succeeds in stabilizing the situation and keeping the pawn center, but it turns out to be an illusion.} Nc6 {I quite like this surprising retreat. There was nothing wrong with just taking the d3 -bishop, but finally forcing the d4 -pawn to move seems to me to be the logical conclusion of Black's opening plan.} ({The game is now likely to proceed} 12... d5 {Nce5} 13. Qe3 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 b5 $1 {with a sharp, double-edged middlegame. The pair of bishops is gone now, and Black has a straightforward plan of playing ... Rb8 , ... b4 , getting a lot of targets on the queenside. I'm not saying Black is better, but we do get the kind of a battle we want in this opening.}) *

