1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bc4 {This move has become very popular in recent decades. It always feels nice to develop the bishop to such an active square, but the move also has drawbacks. The bishop can be vulnerable on c4 due to tricks like ... Nxe4 followed by ... d5 .} ({At other times, the bishop is sorely missed along the h5 - d1 diagonal, with the potential ... Bg4 becoming unpleasant. All in all,} 5. Bc4 {is an important move to know, but not a dangerous one.}) 5... O-O {Throughout this course, our strategy remains unchanged. Whenever possible, we bring the king into safety first and then think about what to do later. Now that we have defended the f7 -pawn, ... Nxe4 becomes a serious possibility.} 6. Bb3 {It is an understandable attempt to step out of all the tricks with ... Nxe4 and ... d5 , but this move does waste a precious tempo. The white bishop is not even that well-placed on b3 and remains a target, as we will see shortly.} Nc6 {Black has many different plans at their disposal, but I quite like this move that creates a highly unpleasant threat of ... Bg4 and forces White to react. It also has a slightly more hidden idea of ... Na5 , getting the pair of bishops.} 7. h3 {This natural move is also the most frequent one in tournament practice. White prevents ... Bg4 for good, but the necessity to stop some threats so early in the opening is already a bad sign. Spending three moves to play Bc4 , Bb3 , and h3 is a very slow approach and cannot possibly pose any problems for Black.} Na5 {It will be very difficult to justify the two moves spent to bring the bishop to b3 once the bishop is gone. From now on, the bishop pair will be the most important positional factor.} 8. O-O {White castles and both kings are very safe for the time being. This usually implies that the game will have a slow, strategic character.} Nxb3 {Black immediately clarifies the situation. This bishop had nowhere to run, but sometimes miracles do happen. :)} 9. axb3 {An automatic recapture, opening the a-file for the rook. When I was a kid, the approach taught in chess books was to always capture towards the center. And whilst exceptions exist, as a general rule, I always found it pretty useful.} b6 {Black has a lot of positional trumps besides having a pair of bishops, like potentially a healthier pawn structure. The e4 -pawn is a bit soft, and the same is true for many light squares in White's structure, like c2 and b3 , although we are talking very, very long-term.  Last but not least, Black will play ... a5 later in the game, making the a1 -rook pretty useless. White does have a possibility now to search for complications with e5 and e6 , but their pieces are not ready to join in the attack.} *

