1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bc4 {This move has become very popular in recent decades. It always feels nice to develop the bishop to such an active square, but the move also has drawbacks. The bishop can be vulnerable on c4 due to tricks like ... Nxe4 followed by ... d5 .} ({At other times, the bishop is sorely missed along the h5 - d1 diagonal, with the potential ... Bg4 becoming unpleasant. All in all,} 5. Bc4 {is an important move to know, but not a dangerous one.}) 5... O-O {Throughout this course, our strategy remains unchanged. Whenever possible, we bring the king into safety first and then think about what to do later. Now that we have defended the f7 -pawn, ... Nxe4 becomes a serious possibility.} 6. Qe2 {Many players have tried this move, and it makes a certain amount of sense. White prevents all the tricks with ... Nxe4 because they could capture the knight with the queen. Furthermore, White prepares to develop the dark-squared bishop and castle long. The truth is that White will never get enough time for all of this.} c6 {I really like this flexible approach, keeping a lot of possibilities alive. Depending on White's reaction, Black can continue with ... b5 , ... d5 , ... Qa5 , or ... Bg4 . Amongst those, ... b5 is a particularly unpleasant threat to face, which is why players with the white pieces often feel provoked to start immediate action in the center.} 7. e5 {It is a tempting continuation, but as it turns out, White is not ready for the action in the center. The e5 -pawn will become a weakness, and White will not have anything in return. Hundreds of players have chosen this move, which shows that the resulting positions are not easy to evaluate over the board.} dxe5 {It's good to clarify the situation immediately, especially since White's reaction is essentially forced.} 8. dxe5 {In an ideal world, White probably would have preferred to recapture with the knight, but the d4 -pawn is a big pawn to lose. From now on, the weakness of the e5 -pawn will be a constant source of worry.} Nd5 {Naturally, we occupy the central square, especially since the alternatives are pretty gloomy. The d5 -knight is well-placed and also serves the purpose of blocking the a2 - g8 diagonal for the light-squared bishop, making all the ideas with e6 unplayable.} 9. Bd2 {This is by far the most natural continuation, and it has been played in hundreds of games. It looks very logical to defend the c3 -knight and prepare to castle long. However, it turns out to be one of those positions where making natural and logical moves gets you in trouble.} ({Maybe preventing ... Bg4 with} 9. h3 {would have been more prudent, although I understand why nobody is too happy about allowing ... Nxc3 , ruining White's structure.}) 9... Bg4 {This move is a big part of Black's plan. By pinning the f3 -knight, Black makes sure that the e5 -pawn will be a chronic weakness. From now on, there is no way for White to avoid some serious damage to the pawn structure.} 10. O-O-O {On the surface, it looks as if White got everything they intended. White finished development and castled long. Usually, this should mean some initiative and some advantage. In this particular case, everything is different, as will become apparent after Black's next move.} e6 {This is a great positional move, consolidating Black's advantage. The e6 -pawn fulfills a double purpose of defending the d5 -knight forever and fixing the e5 -pawn. Black will simply attack the pawn a few times until White cannot defend it anymore.   White's lead in development will not result in anything tangible since Black has no weaknesses. And with nothing to attack, there is nothing to be achieved. White has to get ready for a long and gruesome defense.} ({h3} 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 {, hoping for a quick attack with h4 - h5 , fails to concrete reasons:} Nd7 {followed by ... Qh4 , or Qh4 directly points at White's weakened structure. Black is better, and White is often best advised to give up the bishop pair as well.}) *

