1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bc4 {This move has become very popular in recent decades. It always feels nice to develop the bishop to such an active square, but the move also has drawbacks. The bishop can be vulnerable on c4 due to tricks like ... Nxe4 followed by ... d5 .} ({At other times, the bishop is sorely missed along the h5 - d1 diagonal, with the potential ... Bg4 becoming unpleasant. All in all,} 5. Bc4 {is an important move to know, but not a dangerous one.}) 5... O-O {Throughout this course, our strategy remains unchanged. Whenever possible, we bring the king into safety first and then think about what to do later. Now that we have defended the f7 -pawn, ... Nxe4 becomes a serious possibility.} 6. O-O {Nothing can be more natural than castling short in this position, and most people have indeed chosen this continuation. Its only drawback is that it allows the execution of Black's tactical idea.} Nxe4 {We could certainly choose some other continuation, but this approach is very straightforward and simple. Not only do we exchange some pieces, which is useful for the side with less space, but we also destroy White's pawn center in the process.} 7. Bxf7+ {A possible approach if White is trying to keep things complicated. White abandons the bishop pair and, in return, Black has to live with a slightly weakened kingside. It's not a very popular variation though, and knowing the first few moves will be sufficient.} Rxf7 8. Nxe4 {We can already see the outlines of a battle to come. Black has a bishop pair, White has a safer king and potentially a better pawn structure. This imbalance gives opportunities to both sides and is exactly the kind of fight we are looking for.} h6 {We control the g5 -square, preventing all the unpleasant knight jumps. Furthermore, the black king gets a cozy square on h7 . It is a good habit to think about the long-term safety of your king, one that took me too long to develop.} 9. h3 {The threat of ... Bg4 becoming unpleasant, White also needs to take some defensive measures.} Qf8 {A nice and very unusual way to develop the queen. It is well placed on f8 , defending the h6 -pawn and adding pressure along the f-file. There is also an immediate threat of ... Rxf3 with great compensation for the exchange.} 10. Nh2 {The threat of ... Rxf3 is unpleasant, and White prudently removes the knight to the square made available by their last move. The sheer fact that White has to address some threats created by Black over the last few moves suggests that something went slightly wrong with White's opening strategy.} b6 {I like this ambitious approach, trying to make the most out of the bishop pair. Black has a simple plan of developing the pieces with ... Bb7 and ... Nd7 , followed by a central breakthrough with ... e5 . Once the position opens up, Black's advantage will be beyond doubt. White will have to do something very smart over the next few moves to prevent that if this is even possible.} *

