1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Bc4 {This move has become very popular in recent decades. It always feels nice to develop the bishop to such an active square, but the move also has drawbacks. The bishop can be vulnerable on c4 due to tricks like ... Nxe4 followed by ... d5 .} ({At other times, the bishop is sorely missed along the h5 - d1 diagonal, with the potential ... Bg4 becoming unpleasant. All in all,} 5. Bc4 {is an important move to know, but not a dangerous one.}) 5... O-O {Throughout this course, our strategy remains unchanged. Whenever possible, we bring the king into safety first and then think about what to do later. Now that we have defended the f7 -pawn, ... Nxe4 becomes a serious possibility.} 6. O-O {Nothing can be more natural than castling short in this position, and most people have indeed chosen this continuation. Its only drawback is that it allows the execution of Black's tactical idea.} Nxe4 {We could certainly choose some other continuation, but this approach is very straightforward and simple. Not only do we exchange some pieces, which is useful for the side with less space, but we also destroy White's pawn center in the process.} 7. Nxe4 {White usually goes for this safe approach. This move allows White to retain the pair of bishops but doesn't pose many problems for Black. The next few moves are quite forced.} d5 {This is the point, of course. White has to give back the piece now.} 8. Bd3 {The only move that makes sense. The position is rapidly opening up, and this makes the bishops much more valuable.} dxe4 9. Bxe4 Nd7 {The position has clarified a lot and the time has come to think of a plan. The d7 -knight occupies a very flexible square, preparing the breakthrough with ... c5 . Depending on White's reaction, this knight has a bright future on c5 or f6 .} 10. c3 {There is nothing very active that White can do, and this move will be necessary anyway once Black plays ... c5 . Playing c3 early also allows the white bishop to retreat to c2 in some lines.} c5 ({We follow the plan outlined by our previous move. Playing} 10... e5 {would have been a plausible approach, but our move is more ambitious. It creates structural imbalances, which is very useful if you want to get winning chances.}) 11. Be3 {By far the most natural approach and also the most popular move. White could try different things, but they all lead to very similar positions.} Qc7 {This is a very cozy spot for the black queen. Black defends the c5 -pawn, keeps the queens on the board, and frees the d8 -square for the rook. The best moves in chess have more than one purpose. :)} 12. Re1 {One of many plausible moves. The white rook occupies an open file, eyeing the vulnerable e7 -pawn in the distance. Black's reaction against other moves would have been similar.} cxd4 ({We clarify the structure early since White is surprisingly limited in ways to recapture the pawn. Other moves, for instance,} 12... Nf6 {, are equally possible.}) 13. Nxd4 ({Of the three ways to recapture the black pawn, this is still the best. Nobody likes to play with an isolated pawn, and} 13. Bxd4 {would have run into} e5 {, forcing the bishop to retreat.}) 13... a6 {This little move is extremely valuable in this structure. By controlling the b5 -square, Black safeguards the position of the queen on c7 and renews the threat of ... e5 , pushing White's pieces back.  Other plans we can try include ... Rd8 and ... Nf6 , postponing the pawn advance in the center. Black's central superiority – we are the only side with central points left – gives Black an easier play and a brighter future.} *

