1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. Bg5 ({Here is a brief overview of White's sidelines after 6...e5 . The main move,} 7. dxe5 {, is covered elsewhere.}) ({People like playing} 7. Bg5 {in all sorts of positions, probably because it looks like such an active developing move. The truth is, the white bishop has no future on this diagonal.}) 7... h6 {It's useful to clarify the situation right away. Had we waited with ... h6 , White could play Qd2 , followed by Bh6 sometime in the future.} 8. Bh4 {There's hardly any choice. Taking on f6 leaves Black with two strong bishops, and going back to e3 is just sad.} Nbd7 {This is a good, ambitious, developing move. From d7 , the knight defends e5 and f6 and also prevents White from simplifying the position by trading queens.} 9. dxe5 ({White usually takes on e5 , mainly because they have run out of good ideas. As usual, there is no shortage of bad ideas.} 9. Qd2 {, for instance, runs into trouble.} exd4 $1 10. Nxd4 Nxe4 {is a nice trick to remember, winning material.}) 9... dxe5 {Black already has slightly better prospects in this position, mainly because the white pieces are misplaced. We know from various lines of this opening that the c3 -knight can become passive after ... c6 . And the h4 -bishop doesn't make it better. Black's plan could include ... c6 , ... Qc7 , ... Nc5 , depending on what White does, of course.} *

