1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. dxe5 {Taking the pawn is White's most popular choice and, in a way, the critical continuation. Other variations are covered separately.} dxe5 {After we recapture the pawn, White can choose between various setups, most involving some endings. We'll look at the most critical variations, including those that some great theoreticians, such as Anish Giri and Jan Gustafson, suggested for White in various opening courses.} 8. Bg5 {A good developing move and one of the most popular moves in the position. Its only drawback is that it allows Black to keep the queens on the board.} Nbd7 {We don't mind playing with queens on the board. Black has a solid position and a clear plan to follow. This plan includes proving that the c3 -knight is placed badly in the long term. The best way to see this is to observe how the position changes over the next few moves. They serve as an illustration of how things can go wrong for White here.} 9. Bc4 {White, being a better-developed side, goes for maximum activity. The problem here is that there are no objects for attack. This usually makes the edge in development pretty meaningless.} c6 {This modest pawn move is an integral part of Black's strategy. The pawn controls the d5 -square, which severely limits the potential activity of the c3 -knight. It looks as if Black weakens the d6 -square instead, but Black is extremely well-placed to deal with that, as we will see soon enough.} 10. Qd6 {The white queen immediately occupies the weakened d6 -square, preventing the natural development with ... Qe7 or ... Qc7 . By the look of it, White should be doing well here, but this is one of those cases where the appearances are deceptive.} Qb6 {This move marks the beginning of Black's counterplay. Since the natural squares, c7 and e7 , are not available to the black queen, we use the fact that the b2 -pawn is hanging to develop.} 11. Bb3 {This is a natural move, preventing ... Qxb2 and placing the bishop on a defended square. This whole line is a good example of how White can get into trouble by making very natural moves.} Qc5 {The fight for the d6 -square heats up! Black uses the vulnerability of the e4 -pawn to be able to play this without having to worry about the fate of the e5 -pawn.} 12. Rad1 {Still making very natural moves, White assumes that the rook on d6 will be unpleasant to deal with. It is useful to note that despite all the seeming activity, White can't actually attack anything in this position.} h6 {The time has come to push the white pieces back. The h6 -pawn is very useful as it controls the g5 -square, making the f7 -pawn much less vulnerable.} 13. Be3 {This bishop doesn't have any prospects on h4 , so it makes sense to play this and force Black to take on d6 and clarify the situation.} Qxd6 14. Rxd6 {The queens have finally been exchanged, and White looks to have an active and promising position. Nothing could be further from the truth. :)} Re8 {It doesn't look like a big move, but it marks a big moment. The rook frees the f8 -square to prepare ... Bf8 to kick the d6 -rook out. After this, Black will have perfect control over the central squares and an easy plan to follow, with ... Nc5 , attacking the e4 -pawn.  Very importantly, White's minor pieces are badly placed, especially the c3 -knight, bereft of all the active squares and forced to defend the e4 -pawn. White will have to defend this position carefully for a long time, and the imperceptible way they ended up in a worse ending is typical for the entire opening.} *

