1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. dxe5 {Taking the pawn is White's most popular choice and, in a way, the critical continuation. Other variations are covered separately.} dxe5 {After we recapture the pawn, White can choose between various setups, most involving some endings. We'll look at the most critical variations, including those that some great theoreticians, such as Anish Giri and Jan Gustafson, suggested for White in various opening courses.} 8. Qxd8 {Exchanging the queens right away is one of White's main tries. White goes for immediate clarity, making sure that Black doesn't reconsider. There is also a vague hope that the d8 -rook might become tactically vulnerable in some lines.} Rxd8 {With queens off the board, White still has the same choice, to take on e5 or play Bg5 .} 9. Nxe5 {Taking the pawn leads to an approximately equal ending. There are only a few details to learn, which are not very difficult.} Nxe4 {This was always the plan, of course. There is no other way to get the pawn back. It's important to note that all the tricks with Nxf7 do not work now.} 10. Nxe4 ({Since} 10. Nxf7 {doesn't work in view of} Nxc3 11. Nxd8 Nxe2+ {, White has no choice but to recapture.}) 10... Bxe5 {Things have clarified a lot. The queens are off. The pawn centers have disappeared. Since White has some slight lead in the development, we still have to show some elementary precision.} 11. Bg5 {Attacking the rook looks very tempting but fails to achieve anything real.} Re8 {Suddenly, it turns out that White has a lot of tactical weaknesses. The e2 -bishop and the e4 -knight are loose, and the b2 , c2 , and h2 -pawns need attention.} *

