1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. dxe5 {Taking the pawn is White's most popular choice and, in a way, the critical continuation. Other variations are covered separately.} dxe5 {After we recapture the pawn, White can choose between various setups, most involving some endings. We'll look at the most critical variations, including those that some great theoreticians, such as Anish Giri and Jan Gustafson, suggested for White in various opening courses.} 8. Qxd8 {Exchanging the queens right away is one of White's main tries. White goes for immediate clarity, making sure that Black doesn't reconsider. There is also a vague hope that the d8 -rook might become tactically vulnerable in some lines.} Rxd8 {With queens off the board, White still has the same choice, to take on e5 or play Bg5 .} 9. Bg5 {This popular developing move attempts to keep the position more complex. As we have seen in other lines with the same pawn structure, the complexity can entail some risks for White.} Bg4 ({I must say I quite like this move and prefer it to its alternative, the more standard} 9... Re8 {. We invite White to get a pair of bishops, and in this particular type of position, the bishops can be pretty useless. The positional risks White runs here will be more apparent a few moves later.}) 10. h3 {Since taking on e5 is not an attractive option, White is likely to try to clarify the situation immediately by attacking the g4 -bishop. As mentioned earlier, we don't really mind.} Bxf3 {The c8 -bishop has a difficult fate in a lot of openings. There are many positions in which we struggle to find good squares for this piece. In many ways, exchanging this bishop is the best way of developing it. :)} 11. Bxf3 {An automatic recapture, of course. There are some positions where taking back with the pawn makes sense. This is not one of them.} c6 {This is a vital move that we have encountered in many other lines. The pawn controls the d5 -square, preventing Nd5 with simplifications. The endgame is about equal, but Black has an easier task.  Our plan includes the maneuver ... Nbd7 - c5 - e6 , intending to put this knight on d4 or, in a dream scenario, to follow up with ... Bf8 - c5 after White falls back with Be3 . Once we exchange the dark-squared bishops, we'll begin enjoying ourselves. In my experience, it's much more difficult for White to handle this position.} *

