1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. dxe5 {Taking the pawn is White's most popular choice and, in a way, the critical continuation. Other variations are covered separately.} dxe5 {After we recapture the pawn, White can choose between various setups, most involving some endings. We'll look at the most critical variations, including those that some great theoreticians, such as Anish Giri and Jan Gustafson, suggested for White in various opening courses.} 8. Nxe5 {Taking the e5 -pawn at once leads to a complicated ending. It's the move that famous theoreticians Giri and Gustafson suggested for White. Black has nothing to fear, but getting the move order right is important.} Nxe4 ({This is the correct move order. Taking on d1 first would have run into a most unfortunate problem:} 8... Qxd1 $2 9. Rxd1 Nxe4 10. Nxg6 Nxc3 11. Ne7+ {followed by bxc3 with a nearly winning endgame for White.}) 9. Nxe4 ({With the queen still on d8 , White doesn't have any tactical tricks.} 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 {transposes into another variation , and there are no other plausible lines.}) 9... Qxd1 {Now we can safely exchange the queens. White is slightly ahead in development, so we shouldn't be playing with fire keeping the queens on for too long.} 10. Bxd1 {This somewhat unnatural recapture is a suggestion of GM Gustafsson. The point is to use the rook on the e-file and later redeploy the bishop to c2 or b3 . It's a possible way to play, but it will not bring White any advantage. Black has many possible setups, and we'll look at one of them.} Bxe5 11. Re1 {White immediately activates the rook. The e5 -bishop is somewhat loose, and we have to be careful not to do something stupid.} Nd7 {As in many similar positions, d7 is a good square for the black knight. Defending the dark-squared bishop ensures that we are safe against possible tactical tricks. Covering the f6 -square further consolidates our position.} 12. c3 {We have seen this move very often by now. White makes the long diagonal much shorter and, as a bonus, gets a chance to activate the d1 -bishop. In life, though, everything comes at a cost, and the weakness of the d3 -square might come back to haunt White.} a5 {A good positional move, quite typical for this line. Black grabs some space on the queenside and, given the chance, will push the pawn further. This also gives the a8 -rook some breathing space and potentially the possibility to be activated via a6 .} 13. a4 {The black pawn appearing on a4 would start to look like bad news. White stops Black from advancing further but has to live with a rigid, inflexible queenside pawn structure.} Bg7 {I feel like we're analyzing an obscure ending in a sideline, so maybe the time has come to call it a day. The bishop retreats to g7 to free the e5 -square for the knight, reminding White of the weakness on d3 . Black has natural, easy play. White can't do anything very active as they don't have plausible pawn breaks.} *

