1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 {This natural developing move has been the preferred choice of professional players for many decades. There are some far-reaching implications of having the knight on f3 , mainly that the f2 -pawn is now blocked.  White won't be able to play the lines connected to f2 - f4 or f2 - f3 anymore, and the game will enter more positional waters. In this line, we'll have to focus more on plans than concrete variations.} Bg7 {After this standard developing move, we are ready to castle. It's one of the reasons why the Pirc is such a good opening – Black usually finds it very easy to complete the kingside development and bring the king into safety.  My first chess coach used to say that White should aim to castle by move five and Black by move seven, and the Pirc is one of the very few openings where Black often manages to castle even earlier.} 5. Be2 {This move leads to one of the main lines of this opening and, in fact, of the entire opening theory. Countless games have been played here over the last 100 years or so. Fortunately for us, some new ideas have been discovered for Black recently.} O-O {There is no reason for the king to stay in the center here. It's a quiet positional line, and we can afford to castle before deciding on our plan.} 6. O-O {White also calmly castles short, especially since the other, more aggressive setups don't work well with the development of the knight to f3 and the bishop to e2 . There are many very different variations Black can choose from in this position. Fortunately, there is a simple line that avoids most of the opening theory.} e5 {When preparing for this course, I discovered, to my great surprise, that this move has become one of Black's main lines. It has been around for a while but only recently started enjoying the popularity it deserves. Black challenges White's central pawns, forcing some reaction. Those of you who play the King's Indian Defense will recognize the similarity.} 7. dxe5 {Taking the pawn is White's most popular choice and, in a way, the critical continuation. Other variations are covered separately.} dxe5 {After we recapture the pawn, White can choose between various setups, most involving some endings. We'll look at the most critical variations, including those that some great theoreticians, such as Anish Giri and Jan Gustafson, suggested for White in various opening courses.} 8. Nxe5 {Taking the e5 -pawn at once leads to a complicated ending. It's the move that famous theoreticians Giri and Gustafson suggested for White. Black has nothing to fear, but getting the move order right is important.} Nxe4 ({This is the correct move order. Taking on d1 first would have run into a most unfortunate problem:} 8... Qxd1 $2 9. Rxd1 Nxe4 10. Nxg6 Nxc3 11. Ne7+ {followed by bxc3 with a nearly winning endgame for White.}) 9. Nxe4 ({With the queen still on d8 , White doesn't have any tactical tricks.} 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 {transposes into another variation , and there are no other plausible lines.}) 9... Qxd1 {Now we can safely exchange the queens. White is slightly ahead in development, so we shouldn't be playing with fire keeping the queens on for too long.} 10. Rxd1 ({This is the most natural move and also the move that Giri suggests in his course on 1.e4 .} 10. Rxd1 {and Bxd1 are equally popular over the board, but online, practically everyone takes back with a rook.}) 10... Bxe5 {After a short tactical skirmish, we get a quiet ending. White is still slightly ahead in development, which means we will have to exercise some caution over the next few moves. Around here in his course, GM Giri mentioned something to the effect that Pirc players are not known for their endgame technique. Respectfully, I disagree.} 11. c3 {A good positional move. White blocks the long diagonal, making the e5 -bishop less threatening. The c1 -bishop no longer has to defend the b2 -pawn pawn and can be deployed next move.} Nd7 {Of course, we have many different approaches, but this move has the advantage of being quite straightforward. Black intends to continue with ... Nf6 , achieving full equality. If White is still ambitious in this position, they should follow Giri's suggestion.} 12. Bg5 {A clever idea, preventing ... Nf6 + and provoking the king to g7 . Fortunately, we have a sufficient antidote.} Kg7 {Chess is a simple game sometimes. With this move, we regain control of the f6 -square. Furthermore, we create the possibility of playing ... h6 , which can be very useful after f4 , for instance.} 13. Be3 {We are still following Giri's repertoire. This unusual bishop retreat tries to profit from the fact that the e5 -bishop has been running out of squares. White threatens f4 , getting a pair of bishops. Fortunately, we come prepared.} Nf6 {This simple move is our improvement. We still follow the plan indicated by ... Nd7 . If we can trade the knights, Black will have nothing to fear.} 14. f4 {Has something gone wrong for Black? It looks like White will get everything they wanted and more. Fortunately, the appearances are deceptive here.} Bxf4 {This is our first trick. It doesn't look like it should be possible, but it is. :) We have to be aware of the idea behind it, of course.} 15. Bxf4 {Somewhat luckily, White can maintain material balance.} Nxe4 {The time has come to draw some conclusions. White will take on c7 , restoring the material balance and keeping the bishop pair in the ending. As compensation, Black has a strong knight in the center of the board. A plan for the next few moves includes fortifying this knight with ... h5 , ... Bf5 , ... Rfe8 , and possibly doubling the rooks on the e-file.  Although one doesn't feel it yet, the white king could become vulnerable in the future. Black's pawn majority on the kingside is more mobile than white pawns on the queenside. All in all, we have absolutely nothing to fear.} *

