1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. h3 {White covers the g4 -square to ensure that their bishop on e3 is undisturbed. The h3 -pawn, however, does very little to help White in the fight for the center of the board, and this move often turns out to be a loss of precious time.} O-O {It is always useful to take care of our king's safety before deciding on how to challenge White's center. Black keeps the structure flexible, ready to react in many different ways, depending on the setup White chooses. Black's reactions could include the setups with ... c6 , ... e5 , ... c5 , and sometimes even ... d5 .} 6. g4 {White takes some space on the kingside, trying to justify the previous move. They do, however, ignore the piece development for too long by doing so and also weaken the long diagonal somewhat, which allows Black to start their counterplay at once.} (6. Nf3 c6 {transposes to a different line, covered via the Nf3 move order.}) 6... d5 {Black uses the temporary weakness of the diagonal to hit White in the center. Taking the d5 -pawn would only allow Black to activate their pieces, so White has to push his e-pawn further, risking, at this early stage of the game, ending up overextended.} 7. e5 {This very double-edged move has the potential to restrict the g7 -bishop, something we have to pay close attention to. On the other hand, White used 5 of their first 7 moves to push their pawns, and this leaves potential weaknesses behind, as well as problems with completing development.} Ne4 {Of course, we centralize our knight, given this unique opportunity. Now, Black is ready to continue the active plan by playing ... c5 , undermining White's central superiority.} 8. Bg2 {White tries to tempt Black to take on c3 , but Black has no need to deviate from their plan. White's pawn on c3 would help strengthen the pawn chain that limits the g7 -bishop.} (8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Bg2 c5 {leads to the same position as in the main line.}) 8... c5 {As promised, Black starts the counterplay at once. It might look like this hangs a pawn, but this turns out to be an illusion.} 9. Nxe4 {Other moves don't pose many problems either.} dxe4 ({In fact,} 9... cxd4 {works as well, but we can only play one move at a time.}) 10. Bxe4 cxd4 {The simplest, amongst other possibilities. Now White has to be careful.} 11. Bxd4 {White tries to hang on to the material advantage, but this will prove to be a risky undertaking. The alternative was more prudent.} (11. Qxd4 Qa5+ {wins the pawn back, with equal play. Now, with both d4 and e5 attacked, White has to stay consistent.}) 11... Nc6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 {White won a pawn, but at too high a price. Black has a safe king, two bishops, and a strong initiative. White has none of those things and will likely regret their greedy strategy.} *

