1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. h3 {White covers the g4 -square to ensure that their bishop on e3 is undisturbed. The h3 -pawn, however, does very little to help White in the fight for the center of the board, and this move often turns out to be a loss of precious time.} O-O {It is always useful to take care of our king's safety before deciding on how to challenge White's center. Black keeps the structure flexible, ready to react in many different ways, depending on the setup White chooses. Black's reactions could include the setups with ... c6 , ... e5 , ... c5 , and sometimes even ... d5 .} 6. Qd2 {The natural way, but as we know, there was no need for the pawn to be on h3 to make this setup possible. The time White lost on this move enables Black to adopt the most central of all possible setups.} (6. Nf3 c6 {transposes to a different line, covered via the Nf3 move order.}) 6... e5 {Black exploits the vulnerability of White's central pawns, forcing White to respond. There are two major options – White can take on e5 , aiming for an ending, or close the center with d5 .} 7. dxe5 {This leads to endings, where, once again, it's unclear if the presence of the pawn on h3 was worth the time spent on it. In general, Black has no reason to fear endings in this opening.} dxe5 {Black gets a comfortable ending here and has a variety of setups they can choose from. In the long run, White can start suffering due to the misplaced c3 -knight and dark-squared weaknesses in the center. It's worth noting that once Black starts pushing the queenside pawns with ... c6 and ... b5 , White often finds it difficult to meet the threat of ... b4 .} *

