1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. h3 {White covers the g4 -square to ensure that their bishop on e3 is undisturbed. The h3 -pawn, however, does very little to help White in the fight for the center of the board, and this move often turns out to be a loss of precious time.} O-O {It is always useful to take care of our king's safety before deciding on how to challenge White's center. Black keeps the structure flexible, ready to react in many different ways, depending on the setup White chooses. Black's reactions could include the setups with ... c6 , ... e5 , ... c5 , and sometimes even ... d5 .} 6. Qd2 {The natural way, but as we know, there was no need for the pawn to be on h3 to make this setup possible. The time White lost on this move enables Black to adopt the most central of all possible setups.} (6. Nf3 c6 {transposes to a different line, covered via the Nf3 move order.}) 6... e5 {Black exploits the vulnerability of White's central pawns, forcing White to respond. There are two major options – White can take on e5 , aiming for an ending, or close the center with d5 .} 7. d5 {White closes the center and avoids the endgame for now. This entails some risks, however, since the white king will probably end up on the queenside. It just takes too long to develop the pieces on the kingside and castle short.  Furthermore, the move White spent to play h3 is once again a possible loss of time. White's setup would probably look more harmonious with the pawn on c4 instead of c2 , but it's a bit late for that.} c6 {Black starts immediate action to undermine White's central pawns, also getting ready for the white king castling long. The ensuing battle will be sharp but promising for Black, given that our king is much safer.  Depending on White's reaction, the black knight will either go to d4 via c6 or, more likely, to b6 via d7 . The c-file will open either way to make sure Black has a lot of play against the white king.} ({A sample line is dxc6} 7... Nc6 8. O-O-O Be6 {followed by ... Qa5 or ... Nb4 with good prospects. Qxd6 would only fuel Black's initiative. After Qc8} 9. Nf3 {Rd8 Qa3 Rxd1+ Kxd1} a6 {, White is up a pawn but with a worse position. The king can't be happy on d1 , the pawn on e4 needs babysitting, while ... b5 and ... Bf8 are immediate threats that White has to consider as well.}) *

