1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Bd3 {Not a great move, but many players tend to develop their bishop to d3 in almost any position, especially online.} Ng4 {It doesn't happen too often that ... Ng4 is a good move, but this one is quite nice. Black gets some play at once.} 6. Bg5 {Naturally, White doesn't want to part with this bishop yet, especially since the exchange on e3 would leave back some nasty weaknesses in White's structure. It's important to notice now that the d4 -pawn is taboo.} c5 {We can't take the pawn, but nothing can stop us from opening the long diagonal! White has no way to avoid structural concessions now.} 7. dxc5 {Probably the best try. White anticipates Black's idea and opens the position a bit for the pair of bishops. They won't be too scary, though.} (7. Bb5+ {is nothing to worry about, but the sequence is rather forced:} Nc6 8. d5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Rb1 a6 11. Be2 Nce5 12. f3 Nf6 {, when Black enjoys a good position after a subsequent ... b5 . The c3 -pawn can be taken sometimes, but playing less concrete variations and more natural moves seems better from a practical point of view.}) 7... Bxc3+ {The whole point of Black's setup. White's pawns will never be healthy after this.} 8. bxc3 Qa5 {Black wins back the pawn and gets easy play against White's numerous weaknesses. The pair of bishops is White's only compensation for the broken structure, but it's still a long way before White can consolidate enough to start dreaming about what their bishops will be able to achieve. Black's development is very natural, and the future is bright.} *

