1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Qd2 c6 6. f3 {People often play this move, but it just looks pretty without being very useful. For plans with Bh6 , f3 isn't necessary. The g1 -knight no longer has a good square, and g4 isn't a good threat.} b5 {The fact that we can play ... b5 without repercussions is a clear sign of something wrong with White's setup. White has no good plans now. It would be strange to castle long after ... b5 , castling into it, as they say. Bh6 works better without f3 . With the lack of good plans, White might choose a bad one.} 7. g4 {White is trying to insist that f3 was useful. It is often consistency, the trait that gets us in trouble.} h5 {A useful positional tool. Black forces the closure of the kingside and will have a free hand in the upcoming fight on the queenside and the center. I don't explore it in greater detail since White has much better tries in this line with Be3 . Gotta stay fair. :)} *

