1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6 {This move is quite direct and equally dangerous. It's not an invitation to panic but rather an appeal to pay close attention over the next few moves. :)} Bxh6 {This move is necessary. I don't want to castle and get mated after White plays h4 .} 7. Qxh6 e5 ({This is not the most popular move, as many prefer the elegant sortie with} 7... Qa5 {. Central strategies are usually stronger, though, and this position is no exception. Black establishes a strong presence in the middle of the board, and all we need to do is learn a few key lines.}) 8. O-O-O {This natural and popular move certainly deserves our attention. White maintains the pawn center and keeps the option of playing for the f4 break. There are also immediate threats along the d-file, so Black will need to proceed carefully over the next few moves.} Qe7 {Removing the queen from a dangerous file is a good, cautious move. The black queen has to stay close to keep the f6 -knight defended, as failing to do so could result in a devastating fork with Qg7 .} 9. f3 ({This move shares the same purpose of controlling the g4 -square as} 9. h3 {and has the bonus of firmly protecting the e4 -pawn. However, the downside is that the g1 -knight loses access to the f3 -square, which noticeably slows White's play down and opens up additional possibilities for Black.}) 9... exd4 ({Given White's slower approach, this is one of the new ways to play. The usual} 9... Nbd7 {remains a solid choice, as recently demonstrated by Anish Giri. Yours truly once played b5 , a move that Black's position is not yet ready for and should have led to a bad position. I'll leave it up to you to figure out why. :)}) 10. Rxd4 Be6 {In this position, Black can go for a solid strategy. Following up with ... Nbd7 and ... O-O-O , Black completes development without compromising the king's safety. The d6 -pawn is secure now and can always get out of trouble with ... d5 later.} *

