1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6 {This move is quite direct and equally dangerous. It's not an invitation to panic but rather an appeal to pay close attention over the next few moves. :)} Bxh6 {This move is necessary. I don't want to castle and get mated after White plays h4 .} 7. Qxh6 e5 ({This is not the most popular move, as many prefer the elegant sortie with} 7... Qa5 {. Central strategies are usually stronger, though, and this position is no exception. Black establishes a strong presence in the middle of the board, and all we need to do is learn a few key lines.}) 8. O-O-O {This natural and popular move certainly deserves our attention. White maintains the pawn center and keeps the option of playing for the f4 break. There are also immediate threats along the d-file, so Black will need to proceed carefully over the next few moves.} Qe7 {Removing the queen from a dangerous file is a good, cautious move. The black queen has to stay close to keep the f6 -knight defended, as failing to do so could result in a devastating fork with Qg7 .} 9. Be2 {This move controls the g4 -square, helping the white queen maintain its position on h6 . However, the e2 -bishop is not a particularly threatening piece, resulting in Black having time to develop their pieces.} Nbd7 {Black reinforces their central position. The e5 -pawn, which seemed vulnerable just two moves ago, has turned into an absolute fortress. Black plans to develop the bishop by playing ... b5 and ... Bb7 . White must act quickly.} 10. f4 ({It is logical for White to seize the opportunity to play this move, as some activity is required before Black completes development. On the downside,} 10. f4 {doesn't threaten anything, and Black can proceed as planned.}) 10... b5 {This move prepares to finish development with ... Bb7 and ... O-O-O , while also threatening the e4 -pawn. White can now take twice on e5 , though this would give Black a strong central outpost. Developing with Nf3 allows ... Ng4 , leading to a complex position.} *

