1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6 {This move is quite direct and equally dangerous. It's not an invitation to panic but rather an appeal to pay close attention over the next few moves. :)} Bxh6 {This move is necessary. I don't want to castle and get mated after White plays h4 .} 7. Qxh6 e5 ({This is not the most popular move, as many prefer the elegant sortie with} 7... Qa5 {. Central strategies are usually stronger, though, and this position is no exception. Black establishes a strong presence in the middle of the board, and all we need to do is learn a few key lines.}) 8. Nf3 {This is a good developing move. White attacks the e5 -pawn but without playing dxe5 first, which gives both sides some new opportunities.} Qe7 {Black responds patiently, as in the main line. The potential idea of ... exd4 is in the air, attacking the e4 -pawn. If White decides on dxe5 now or later, the game transposes to the main line, but here we'll explore what happens when White avoids this move.} 9. Bc4 {White uses the usual, well-known motives here as well. This bishop exerts strong pressure along the diagonal, given that the f7 -pawn is somewhat vulnerable.} Nbd7 {Black quietly reinforces the center and prepares to challenge the white bishop with ... b5 . The move ... Rf8 is always available to counter Ng5 , and dxe5 is neutralized by ... Nxe5 .} 10. O-O {In an ideal world, White would have preferred castling long, but here it would have allowed Black to play ... Ng4 , exploiting the f2 -pawn's weakness and dislodging the white queen. Castling short ensures the pawn remains protected and the white king stays very safe.} b5 {Why not claim some space on the queenside? While other moves are possible, we should avoid allowing a4 as it could cramp us down.} 11. Bb3 {I think it makes sense for the bishop to stay on this diagonal. Other moves remove the pressure from f7 and pose no problems.} exd4 {I like this new approach. Instead of always being ready to meet Ng5 , we distract the white knight to d4 , where it looks good but doesn't pose any significant threats. This respite allows us to finish our development in peace.} 12. Nxd4 Bb7 {Defending a pawn, developing a piece, and preparing to castle, what more could we ask for from a single move? Black secures an interesting middlegame with equal chances. In the long run, Black's mobile queenside pawn chain could become a serious problem for White.} *

