1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6 {This move is quite direct and equally dangerous. It's not an invitation to panic but rather an appeal to pay close attention over the next few moves. :)} Bxh6 {This move is necessary. I don't want to castle and get mated after White plays h4 .} 7. Qxh6 e5 ({This is not the most popular move, as many prefer the elegant sortie with} 7... Qa5 {. Central strategies are usually stronger, though, and this position is no exception. Black establishes a strong presence in the middle of the board, and all we need to do is learn a few key lines.}) 8. dxe5 {This is one of the more practical ways for White to play. By taking on e5 , White permanently removes ... exd4 from consideration. The pawn structure is now clarified, and White will target the black pawns on e5 and f7 .} dxe5 {From a strategic perspective, Black's position is quite promising. We have more pawns in the center and potentially a better bishop in distant endings. However, before these advantages can come into play, we should survive the next few moves.} 9. Nf3 ({White develops and starts the play against Black's weaknesses. Any delay would allow Black to consolidate easily.} 9. Bc4 {is equally possible but leads to the same position after Black plays} Qe7 {.}) 9... Qe7 ({We could also play} 9... Nbd7 {. Both sides aim for the same position, and there are many possible move orders.}) 10. Bc4 {White can't achieve anything by attacking the e5 -pawn alone since Black can easily defend it with ... Nbd7 . Playing against two weaknesses is more effective.} b5 {It is almost always nice to get some space on the queenside with the gain of time. After other moves, White could consider playing a4 . We should take our chances now cause they tend to disappear. :)} 11. Bb3 {The bishop should certainly stay on this diagonal. Black's pawns on e5 and f7 are still a problem for Black to solve.} Nbd7 {The black knight is finally able to join the fray. From d7 , it defends the e5 -pawn and can later get very active on c5 . Given enough time, Black will get a great position due to the space advantage on the queenside. White has to hurry.} 12. Ng5 Rf8 {There is nothing else. White will get the h7 -pawn, but this pawn-grabbing expedition will come at a serious cost.} 13. Nxh7 {It's not a very big pawn, but it is a pawn nonetheless. :) White hopes to be able to return the queen back from h7 and consolidate, but it is a long process.} Nxh7 {We should take the knight. Please note that ... Rh8 instead doesn't work since White can take the f6 -knight with a check.} 14. Qxh7 a5 {Having lots of space, Black continues to expand the queenside. Meanwhile, White struggles with their minor pieces, and the queen is stuck on h7 . Black's most immediate threat is ... a4 , while the more positional ones are ... Nc5 and ... Be6 , or ... Qg5 . For possible continuations, please refer to our selection of instructive games.} *

