1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Nf3 {This developing move is always a major option. White's moves Qd2 and Nf3 can be played in either order, so please keep an eye on potential transpositions.} c6 {Now we'll look at all the lines when White decides not to follow the main line with Qd2 . White can try several alternative setups, but they are all quite similar and not too difficult to learn.} {The move ... c6 is the part of our repertoire after Qd2 as well, so sticking to it here ensures consistency. Beyond that, ... c6 hardly needs an introduction. It prepares ... b5 , controls the center, and gives our queen some breathing room. You know the drill. :)} 6. Bd3 {It is a possible approach, although not a very dangerous one. The bishop isn't great on d3 , and I often feel that players tend toward this setup out of the unconscious desire for symmetry. The problem with perfect symmetry, at least in chess, is that it doesn't last. :)} Nbd7 {One of many possible moves and setups. In this case, my choice was made easier by the fact that this move was played by Magnus Carlsen, and he usually knows where to put his pieces. Black plays for ... e5 .} 7. O-O {White castles short. It's a bit late for all the plans that involve castling queenside. The game will now enter slow, quiet waters.} O-O {Both kings are extremely safe now. It's interesting to notice that the opposing sides haven't made contact yet.} 8. a4 {Sooner or later, White will have to take the possibility of ... b5 seriously. Other moves lead to the same kind of play.} Qc7 {Black keeps all the options. Depending on your mood, you can continue with ... b6 and ... Bb7 or return to the main plan with ... e5 . After ... e5 , White's options are more limited than usual because the d3 -bishop is blocking the d-file, and no one defends the g4 -square, forcing White to keep an eye on ... Bg4 and ... Ng4 . In short, it's an equal position in what is likely to become a long, positional game. :)} *

