1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Nf3 {This developing move is always a major option. White's moves Qd2 and Nf3 can be played in either order, so please keep an eye on potential transpositions.} c6 {Now we'll look at all the lines when White decides not to follow the main line with Qd2 . White can try several alternative setups, but they are all quite similar and not too difficult to learn.} {The move ... c6 is the part of our repertoire after Qd2 as well, so sticking to it here ensures consistency. Beyond that, ... c6 hardly needs an introduction. It prepares ... b5 , controls the center, and gives our queen some breathing room. You know the drill. :)} 6. Be2 {It's a nice, solid move. Its only drawback is that it allows Black a chance to go for an early ... b5 . Black profits from the fact that both b5 and g4 -squares are available, the latter being surprisingly relevant.} b5 {It's rare for us to go for ... b5 so early. In this particular position, we are threatening the e4 -pawn, which makes the difference with the Bd3 line.} 7. e5 {This rare move deserves more attention than it receives and could be White's critical try. The old saying about how you should play in the center in response to activity on the flanks still seems valid.} Ng4 {This move is necessary since anything else leaves us positionally compromised. It is also the reason why we are not playing ... b5 after h3 .} 8. Bf4 {White needs to address both threats, ... dxe5 , as well as ... Nxe3 .} dxe5 {With this move, we can force an ending. White can take back on e5 in different ways, but we can always use the vulnerability of the e5 -pawn to create counterplay.} *

