1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Nf3 {This developing move is always a major option. White's moves Qd2 and Nf3 can be played in either order, so please keep an eye on potential transpositions.} c6 {Now we'll look at all the lines when White decides not to follow the main line with Qd2 . White can try several alternative setups, but they are all quite similar and not too difficult to learn.} {The move ... c6 is the part of our repertoire after Qd2 as well, so sticking to it here ensures consistency. Beyond that, ... c6 hardly needs an introduction. It prepares ... b5 , controls the center, and gives our queen some breathing room. You know the drill. :)} 6. h3 {This move is very popular. White controls the g4 -square to prevent the potential moves ... Ng4 or ... Bg4 . Playing h3 is useful, but also an indication that White is not being particularly ambitious. For all the plans involving a kingside attack, h3 is not really necessary. From now on, the game will take on a more positional character.} O-O {As usual, we prioritize bringing our king to safety. It's a simple rule, yet thousands of games are lost because players forget to castle.} 7. a4 {This move is a usual continuation of the plan that started with h3 . White stopped Black's play on the kingside by controlling the g4 -square. Furthermore, by securing control of the b5 -square, White has made counterplay on the queenside more challenging. However, everything comes at a cost, and making two pawn moves on the side of the board allows Black to establish firm control of the center.} Nbd7 {This move is the most solid approach for Black. The knight is well-placed on d7 , controlling vulnerable squares like e5 and c5 . Most importantly, Black is ready to play ... e5 , striving for equality in the center.} 8. Be2 {This is one of many ways for White to deviate from the main line. As mentioned earlier, Black's reaction is similar and leads to the same type of position.} e5 {Following the plan that was indicated by the previous move, Black fights for central control and is unbothered by possible endings.} 9. dxe5 {In this line, it is usual for White to take the e5 -pawn immediately. Otherwise, Black might start creating counterplay with ... exd4 and ... Re8 .} Nxe5 {This reaction is typical as well. Black takes with the knight to prevent the white queen from occupying the d6 -square and exerting strong pressure on Black's position.} 10. O-O {It is natural to castle. The only alternative regularly played is taking on e5 and heading into the endgame. However, with the bishop already committed to e2 , a reasonably passive square, White can't fight for an advantage.} Nxf3+ {This is the simplest approach. Black takes on f3 before White gets a chance to reconsider and move the knight to d4 or d2 .} 11. Bxf3 Be6 ({Black completes development. The position is very similar to the main variation with} 11... a5 {. For further details, refer to the final position of that line.}) *

