1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Nf3 {This developing move is always a major option. White's moves Qd2 and Nf3 can be played in either order, so please keep an eye on potential transpositions.} c6 {Now we'll look at all the lines when White decides not to follow the main line with Qd2 . White can try several alternative setups, but they are all quite similar and not too difficult to learn.} {The move ... c6 is the part of our repertoire after Qd2 as well, so sticking to it here ensures consistency. Beyond that, ... c6 hardly needs an introduction. It prepares ... b5 , controls the center, and gives our queen some breathing room. You know the drill. :)} 6. h3 {This move is very popular. White controls the g4 -square to prevent the potential moves ... Ng4 or ... Bg4 . Playing h3 is useful, but also an indication that White is not being particularly ambitious. For all the plans involving a kingside attack, h3 is not really necessary. From now on, the game will take on a more positional character.} O-O {As usual, we prioritize bringing our king to safety. It's a simple rule, yet thousands of games are lost because players forget to castle.} 7. a4 {This move is a usual continuation of the plan that started with h3 . White stopped Black's play on the kingside by controlling the g4 -square. Furthermore, by securing control of the b5 -square, White has made counterplay on the queenside more challenging. However, everything comes at a cost, and making two pawn moves on the side of the board allows Black to establish firm control of the center.} Nbd7 {This move is the most solid approach for Black. The knight is well-placed on d7 , controlling vulnerable squares like e5 and c5 . Most importantly, Black is ready to play ... e5 , striving for equality in the center.} 8. a5 {White continues expanding on the queenside. The a5 -pawn restricts many of Black's options, like ... Qa5 , ... Qb6 , or ... b6 . Other moves are possible but lead to similar play.} Qc7 {It's a careful move, taking the endgames out of the picture for now. We are still planning to play ... e5 next but intend to keep the queens on the board.} 9. Be2 {Sooner or later, we all have to develop our pieces. The bishop is quite harmoniously placed on e2 , not blocking the d-file and keeping an eye on the h5 -square. Especially with a pawn on h3 , you should keep in mind a possible ... Nh5 - f4 maneuver.} e5 {The good old central plan. With the pawn on e5 , the Pirc stops being an unorthodox opening. We actually have more central pawns now! Alternatives do exist, mainly connected to playing ... b5 after some prep. You could consider ... Rb8 or ... Qb8 for this purpose.} 10. dxe5 {This reaction, immediately taking the pawn after Black plays ... e5 is a venerable tradition in this line. White tries to avoid ... exd4 and ... Re8 , when the e4 -pawn might begin feeling insecure.} Nxe5 {It is much better to take the pawn in this way. You don't want to be stuck with a d7 -knight that can't move. Our light-squared bishop and the a8 -rook are happy to see this knight gone. They might be playing for the same team, but they still have their own ambitions. :)} 11. O-O {It's a natural and ambitious way to continue. The alternative, taking on e5 , leads to a simple structure without many problems for Black.} Nxf3+ {This move is here mainly because it's simple. After other moves, we would have to start considering Nd4 or Nd2 , with the threat of playing f4 .} 12. Bxf3 Be6 {Finally, we can develop this bishop without taking any risks. The e6 -square is ideal, and slowly, we begin to realize that all our pieces are sitting quite happily. That's one of the advantages of learning openings – your pieces make it to decent squares.} 13. Bf4 {The only thing that could possibly be described as a weakness in Black's position is the d6 -pawn. Therefore, it is reasonable for White to try and attack it a few times. The truth is, the d6 -pawn is much stronger than it looks and White will understand it soon enough.} Rfd8 {Black is defending the d6 -pawn, of course, but also centralizing the rook. Later in the game, this can come in handy if Black plays for the ... d5 breakthrough or if the d-file opens, which can happen after the eventual ... Ne8 and ... Be5 . The other rook stays on a8 , fulfilling a modest but relevant task of keeping the a7 -pawn protected.} 14. Qd2 {It's as natural a move as they come. White connects the rooks and gets ready to increase the pressure on the d6 -pawn. The white queen also supports the dark-squared bishop, creating the possibilities of Bh6 or Bg5 , with a nasty pin in the latter case.} Ne8 {I must say I quite like this solid approach. Black defends the d6 -pawn in a way that makes it obvious White will not gain anything by attacking it. The two black bishops sit on some of the best squares on the board. The d8 -rook is happy to have freed the f8 -square (we don't have to worry about Bh6 anymore.)   Bg5 can always be answered by ... Rd7 . Our plans over the next few moves include ... b5 , with a slow, inexorable expansion on the queenside. White will not find this position easy to play.} *

