1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Nf3 {This developing move is always a major option. White's moves Qd2 and Nf3 can be played in either order, so please keep an eye on potential transpositions.} c6 {The move ... c6 is the part of our repertoire after Qd2 as well, so sticking to it here ensures consistency. Beyond that, ... c6 hardly needs an introduction. It prepares ... b5 , controls the center, and gives our queen some breathing room. You know the drill. :)} 6. Qd2 {Now we've arrived at one of the key positions of the entire line with Be3 . White prepares for an aggressive setup with Bh6 , h4 , and the like. Usually, we would keep the king in the center to avoid the immediate assault, but for once, I'll show you lines where we brace for the attack.} O-O {We're diving into unknown waters. Throughout this course, we've kept the king safe, but sometimes, playing complications is the way forward. Don't worry, I've got some new ideas lined up for you. :)} 7. Bh6 {This is by far the most dangerous attempt. The plan is simple: White wants to go h4 and h5 while preventing Black from playing ... h5 . The bishop on h6 acts as a blocker, which explains why White rarely takes on g7 (doing so would allow ... h5 ). Black also avoids taking on h6 , as inviting the white queen to such a dangerous position would be asking for trouble.} b5 {Our usual plan works perfectly here. Black gains some space on the queenside. We can only afford to do this in the face of an upcoming attack because White needs to stop for a move to defend the e4 -pawn from the threat of ... b4 .} 8. Bd3 {This move is, by far, the most natural and popular way to defend the pawn. White has other ways of preventing ... b4 , like a3 , but why wouldn't you want to protect the pawn and develop at the same time? This game will take a sharp turn shortly.} Bg4 {This is an unusual place for the bishop, but in this particular position, Black achieves counterplay by taking on f3 and leaving White with a potentially severely weakened pawn structure. We'll just have to avoid getting mated. :)} 9. Bxg7 {This comes too early. As a general rule in these positions, this exchange benefits Black by providing options to play ... h5 , ... h6 , ... Rh8 , among other things.} Kxg7 10. h4 {White attempts the same attack as in the main line but fails to pose any serious threats after exchanging the bishops.} Bxf3 {Black reacts similarly. Spoiling White's pawn structure is essential to ensure White has to take some risks.} 11. gxf3 e5 {This move is strategically vital. It attacks the d4 -pawn, locks White's pawns on f2 and f3 , and sets up additional pressure with ... Nh5 and ... Qf6 . In short, it's a strong move.} *

