1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 {Here we will examine various sidelines that White is likely to use at a club level, especially online. As you will see very soon, they are not very dangerous.} 5. Nf3 {This developing move is always a major option. White's moves Qd2 and Nf3 can be played in either order, so please keep an eye on potential transpositions.} c6 {The move ... c6 is the part of our repertoire after Qd2 as well, so sticking to it here ensures consistency. Beyond that, ... c6 hardly needs an introduction. It prepares ... b5 , controls the center, and gives our queen some breathing room. You know the drill. :)} 6. Qd2 {Now we've arrived at one of the key positions of the entire line with Be3 . White prepares for an aggressive setup with Bh6 , h4 , and the like. Usually, we would keep the king in the center to avoid the immediate assault, but for once, I'll show you lines where we brace for the attack.} O-O {We're diving into unknown waters. Throughout this course, we've kept the king safe, but sometimes, playing complications is the way forward. Don't worry, I've got some new ideas lined up for you. :)} 7. Bh6 {This is by far the most dangerous attempt. The plan is simple: White wants to go h4 and h5 while preventing Black from playing ... h5 . The bishop on h6 acts as a blocker, which explains why White rarely takes on g7 (doing so would allow ... h5 ). Black also avoids taking on h6 , as inviting the white queen to such a dangerous position would be asking for trouble.} b5 {Our usual plan works perfectly here. Black gains some space on the queenside. We can only afford to do this in the face of an upcoming attack because White needs to stop for a move to defend the e4 -pawn from the threat of ... b4 .} 8. Bd3 {This move is, by far, the most natural and popular way to defend the pawn. White has other ways of preventing ... b4 , like a3 , but why wouldn't you want to protect the pawn and develop at the same time? This game will take a sharp turn shortly.} Bg4 {This is an unusual place for the bishop, but in this particular position, Black achieves counterplay by taking on f3 and leaving White with a potentially severely weakened pawn structure. We'll just have to avoid getting mated. :)} 9. h4 {White have no time to waste if they want their attack to succeed. The threat of h5 is so powerful now that it could decide the game even without the a1 -rook joining the attack. Black must react with extreme precision.} Bxf3 {It's clear that Black is spoiling White's pawn structure to create targets for counterplay, but there is more to it than meets the eye. The f3 -knight also posed uncomfortable threats, such as Nh2 . The g-file opening shouldn't concern us – our kingside defenses are steady. Look at the well-protected g6 -pawn! I don't think White can hope to use the g-file to break through.} 10. gxf3 Nh5 {With the bishops still on the board (unlike the line with Bxg7 ) , h5 is the powerful threat. Blocking this pawn is the best way to stop White's attack before it gets too strong. As we already know, by controlling the f4 -square, the h5 -knight holds great positional value. From here on, the fight will revolve around f4 and the surrounding areas.} 11. Ne2 {This is one of White's sneakiest attempts. We know that Black's defense is centered around the h5 -knight, so White tries to dislodge the defender by playing Ng3 . This threat needs to be taken seriously.} Qb6 ({I like this entirely new approach. So far, Black has mainly relied on} 11... e5 {, barely surviving the ensuing complications. While preparing this course, I discovered a different idea – one that will take your opponent by surprise. By targeting the d4 -pawn, we prevent Ng3 . There are also other reasons behind our move, but all in due time. :)}) 12. O-O-O {With the e2 -knight currently immobile, it's only natural for White to castle and bring dormant forces into the attack. White's plan includes Rdg1 and Ng3 . The clouds are gathering...} Nd7 {We need all our pieces in play. From d7 , the knight supports the well-known ... e5 , but also... Oh, wait – no spoilers here.} 13. Rdg1 {As planned, White brings heavy artillery to the kingside. The threats are as numerous as they are strong; above all, Qg5 . It's time to unleash our surprise! :)} c5 {I am happy to suggest this move, which initiates the counterattack. Black threatens ... c4 above all, forcing White to shift focus to their safety. I analyzed this position in depth and concluded that Black is doing well.  The details of this analysis are somewhat misplaced in a 'simplified' course, but I've provided a separate, informative variation for further explanation. Feel free to check it out if you'd like to dive deeper.} *

