1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 {Here, we will consider White's various options on move 5, other than the main line with Nf3 .} 5. e5 {This thematic push comes a bit too early. White isn't quite ready to support their pawn in the center.} Nfd7 {By far the most ambitious, this move prepares to hit White's center with ... c5 . Now, the best White can do is to return to the main lines by playing Nf3 after all.} 6. Bc4 {Looks tempting, as the f7 -pawn and the e6 -square may appear weak at first glance. Black continues with their plan, however, and White's pressure along the a2 - g8 diagonal proves an illusion.} c5 {Ignoring White's 'threat', Black calmly proceeds with the original plan. White can't avoid losses in the center, also because the c4 -bishop does very little to support the pawns on dark squares. Black is already better here.} 7. e6 {Consistent, but just makes it worse.} fxe6 {There is no way for White to regain the pawn, and the f4 -pawn only makes it worse. White faces a losing battle here.} *

