{A most unpleasant surprise. White loses the pawn they did so much to get and will face an uphill battle from now on. As you'll easily find out yourself, White's only way to play on leads to a very sad ending ( Qxd8 Nxf3+ Kf2 Rxd8 Kxf3 Bg4+ Kf2 Bf5⩱ ) . Once again, that's what you get for playing a3 on move five and subsequent pawn-grabbing.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 {Here, we will consider White's various options on move 5, other than the main line with Nf3 .} 5. a3 {This little move doesn't deserve the popularity it enjoyed the last few years. White prevents the immediate ... c5 , by preparing to go b4 after the later ... Qa5 . The time lost by doing so can prove costly should the game sharpen up, and Black has a lot of ways to make it happen.} O-O {Nice to get the king into safety before starting the mess in the center of the board. Things will heat up very quickly now, and White is a long way from castling.} 6. Nf3 {Happy about having 'prevented' ... c5 , White returns to normal development. I find it quite surprising that many great players, including Anand, who played this a few times with White, could think that playing a3 so early in the opening can be a good idea.} c5 {The most principled way. Having moved a lot of pawns in the opening, now White is seriously behind in development. The whole idea of 5.a3 was to prevent ... c5 , but we have several tricks up our sleeves. :)} 7. dxc5 {White would be happy to exchange queens and play a lovely ending with the central pawns on e4 and f4 , but that's not going to happen.} Nbd7 {A novelty! Black continues to develop their pieces and forces White to open the e-file in the process. Things will get dangerous for White very quickly.} 8. cxd6 {What else? At least now White has some pawns to show for all the trouble ahead.} exd6 {Black has a lot of play here and means to keep the white king in the center, with ... Qb6 , for instance. Since normal moves don't guarantee an easy life, White will probably take a second pawn as well.} 9. Qxd6 {White is two pawns up now, but the queen is exposed on d6 , and the king is getting quite nervous on e1 . Black's next move comes quite naturally.} Re8 {Of course, Black uses this chance to start looking at the opponent's king, and not without menace. So early in the game – we just made 9 moves each – White finds it tough to come out of the opening alive.} 10. e5 {Tempting, natural and wrong. Yes, these things do happen. White's stability in the center is about to be shattered most brutally.} Nxe5 *

