1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 {Here, we will consider White's various options on move 5, other than the main line with Nf3 .} 5. Bd3 {Of all the sidelines, this one is probably the best. The bishop is really well placed on d3 and defending e4 -pawn prevents ... c5 in a natural way. Nonetheless, Black has quite a number of satisfactory replies.} e5 {A very central way to play and also quite logical in a way because White was not doing anything to control the dark squares in the center. This movie is also made possible by the fact that the d3 -bishop blocks the d-file.} 6. dxe5 {This is by far the most critical continuation. White doesn't have a good way to defend the d-pawn, so it's best to exchange it right away.} dxe5 {After Black recaptures the pawn in the center, we reach the first critical position of this variation. White has a choice between two very different continuations now. They can exchange the queens with a complicated ending, or they can play more ambitiously.} 7. Bb5+ {Well, to be fair, not a move that was necessary to cover. It has been played only a couple of times, but by pretty good players and it's also one of the top two engine suggestions. It's only here for completeness' sake. :)} c6 {The simplest move and also the most natural. Black has several ways to avoid the queens' trade, but there is no reason to do so. The endgame is not very dangerous for Black.} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Now, the only thing to take care of is making sure that the king remains sufficiently safe, but since the queens are off the board, it shouldn't be too difficult.} 9. Bc4 {Naturally, White uses this chance to attack the f7 -pawn. Black has some lines that are connected to the positional sacrifice of that pawn, but there is really no need for drastic measures so early in the game.} Be6 {The simplest move. Black develops the bishop and covers the f7 -pawn at the same time.} 10. Bxe6 {Of course, White uses this chance to spoil Black's structure somewhat. Although the black pawns are no longer perfect after this exchange, the king is near enough to make sure that the e6 - pawn is protected.} fxe6 {As has been the case for a few moves now, the e5 -pawn is not really hanging since Black would just move the knight to g4 or d7 and win the pawn back.} 11. Nf3 {Natural development. White is trying to force the black pawn to take on f4 and give White the tempo to develop the bishop and to castle long.} Nbd7 {Keeping the status quo. Black develops the knight and defends the e5 -pawn at the same time. Like most good moves, this move has more than one purpose.} 12. O-O {Since they didn't manage to force Black into taking on f4 at any point, White abandons the plans to castle long and settles for this less dangerous move.} Ke7 {Connecting the rooks and officially finishing development. Black's king on e7 is both safe and also fulfills a very important purpose of keeping the e6 -pawn protected. Black has all the reasons to be optimistic about the future.} *

