{Black continues the plan that was already in the air after c6 . Although the white pieces are perfectly developed, the bishops find little they can attack, and the c3 -knight is traditionally badly placed. I expect Black to fully equalize over the next few moves and maybe get chances to fight for more.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 {Here, we will consider White's various options on move 5, other than the main line with Nf3 .} 5. Bd3 {Of all the sidelines, this one is probably the best. The bishop is really well placed on d3 and defending e4 -pawn prevents ... c5 in a natural way. Nonetheless, Black has quite a number of satisfactory replies.} e5 {A very central way to play and also quite logical in a way because White was not doing anything to control the dark squares in the center. This movie is also made possible by the fact that the d3 -bishop blocks the d-file.} 6. dxe5 {This is by far the most critical continuation. White doesn't have a good way to defend the d-pawn, so it's best to exchange it right away.} dxe5 {After Black recaptures the pawn in the center, we reach the first critical position of this variation. White has a choice between two very different continuations now. They can exchange the queens with a complicated ending, or they can play more ambitiously.} 7. Nf3 {This is the more ambitious way. White keeps the queens on board, plans to castle long and uses their development advantage to get some initiative. Black has sufficient resources, however, to keep an approximate equality.} exf4 {Defending this pawn would have been difficult in the long run, so Black immediately clarifies the situation and establishes, for what it's worth, a certain structural advantage. From now on, the black pawns will be potentially safer.} 8. Bxf4 {White should, of course, recapture this pawn before it gets too late.} O-O {As always, we get our king into safety before deciding how to proceed with our development.} 9. Qd2 {Naturally, White uses this possibility to castle long! All the other plans wouldn't have been nearly as threatening.} Bg4 {A good developing move. From now on, Black will always be able to reduce the pressure somewhat by exchanging on f3 , if necessary.} 10. O-O-O {Naturally, White follows the plan that they started with the last move, castles long, and finishes the development of their pieces. We have reached a critical position now where Black has to choose between many available plans.} c6 {I like this move more than others because Black now has the potential to develop strong counterplay. The queen will be very active on a5 , and the white king will no longer be perfectly safe. The c6 -pawn is also extremely useful as it controls the squares b5 and d5 , rendering the c3 -knight somewhat useless.} 11. h3 {Sooner or later, White will have to clarify the position of this bishop since the pin along this diagonal is quite unpleasant to live with.} Bxf3 {Retreating this bishop would cost too much time, time that Black doesn't have in this position.} 12. gxf3 {White recaptures and strengthens the center, but some structural weaknesses remain. The very possible exchange of the dark-squared bishops could leave White with long-term positional problems in the future.} Qa5 *

