1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. e5 {This move is quite principled but comes way too early. White is not at all ready for the opening of the center and Black will easily get equal play and more.} Nfd7 {The knight moves to the safest square and exerts a lot of pressure on white pawns from here. From now on, White will struggle to keep the material equality.} 7. exd6 {This move is better than it looks. Initially, I was going to discard it by saying that 'opening the e-file is suicidal' or something like that, but in fact, White's position remains reasonably sturdy. As you probably know, White can afford many more liberties in the opening without being lost.} O-O {Black tucks away the king and starts eyeing the e-file with some intent. White has to be very careful now and has to make sure that they can also get the king into safety without any major damage.} 8. Be3 {This is the safest move at White's disposal. It blocks the e-file, defends the d-pawn, and helps White get ready to castle long. You really cannot expect much more from one move.} exd6 {With this move, Black restores the material balance, opens the e-file, and, in the meantime, also defends the pawn on c5 . From now on, it's White who has to be careful to retain equality.} 9. Qd2 {With this natural move, White prepares to castle long and also defends the e3 -bishop, which will be useful once the black rook appears on e8 . The queen on d2 will also be useful to support f5 with the idea of Bh6 , but we do hope White will not think of this. :)} Nc6 {A very natural square for the knight, especially since the d7 -square has already been taken. From here, Black exerts a lot of pressure on the d4 -pawn and hopes to be able to open the long diagonal at some point. Needless to say White will do their best to stop this from happening.} 10. O-O-O {At this moment, White is definitely relieved to get the king away from the open e-file, but whether the queenside will remain a safe place in the long term is a completely different question. Ideally, the white king would like to be on h1 , but that takes a few moves, and a few moves can be an eternity in chess.} Qa5 {It's always nice to be able to develop the queen into such an active position. From now on, Black will combine attacking ideas with more strategic plans to use White's weaknesses on the light squares in the center. These include f5 , e4 and also c2 , so White will have to really watch out for the arrival of the black bishop on f5 .} *

