1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. e5 {This move is quite principled but comes way too early. White is not at all ready for the opening of the center and Black will easily get equal play and more.} Nfd7 {The knight moves to the safest square and exerts a lot of pressure on white pawns from here. From now on, White will struggle to keep the material equality.} 7. dxc5 {Despite certain popularity, I don't see any reason for playing this variation. White abandons the pawn center and ignores the piece development for too long.} dxe5 {Clearly, the best way to recapture. The e5 -pawn is now gone and the c5 -pawn remains very vulnerable.} 8. fxe5 {Another white pawn appears on e5 , and this time, White is actually hoping for this pawn to be taken so that at least Black loses the right to castle in the process. But there is no reason for Black to rush at all since the e5 -pawn is doomed, and Black can take it at their leisure.} Nc6 {With this move, Black quietly reinforces the pressure on what remains from the white center and also defends the d8 -queen at the same time. From now on, White faces far from the trivial task of how not to lose two pawns without getting anything in return.} 9. e6 {It's a very sensible move. This pawn is doomed anyway, and White at least makes sure that Black has to ruin their structure by capturing it. Before we start applauding White's clever opening strategy, let me point out that out of their first 9 moves, seven were made by pawns. And now most of these pawns are gone. :)} fxe6 {Black naturally captures this pawn and regains the material balance. Since White has been ignoring the piece play for so long, it is also worth noting that Black has a slight lead in development. The c5 -pawn is going to be difficult to defend, and White will have to play very well to keep any compensation for that.} *

