1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. e5 {This move is quite principled but comes way too early. White is not at all ready for the opening of the center and Black will easily get equal play and more.} Nfd7 {The knight moves to the safest square and exerts a lot of pressure on white pawns from here. From now on, White will struggle to keep the material equality.} 7. e6 {This move has been played by some very good players, which makes me wonder what they were thinking. White doesn't get any advantage, nor is White's position very safe after this.} fxe6 {There is really no alternative to that. As a general rule, if the enemy pawn makes it this far, we take it. :)} 8. Ng5 {This is the only way to make any sense of what White has been doing. By attacking the pawn on e6 , White does force some concessions.} Nf6 {We certainly should not allow the white knight to arrive at e6 , given the possibility to defend the pawn with this nice natural move. White will get the sacrificed pawn back, but not really the one they wanted.} 9. dxc5 {White does restore the material balance, but there's no initiative left to speak of. There is no harmony in White's position, with knights developed all over the place. White will have to tread very carefully to retain some sort of equality.} O-O {It's always nice to get to safety before deciding what to do after that. White cannot do the same and still has to make sure that they can castle.} 10. cxd6 {White would probably risk losing the c5 -pawn if they waited any longer with this exchange.} exd6 {This is by far the more natural recapture. Given that the white king is in the center, it doesn't make sense for Black to exchange the queens, especially given that the black queen appearing on b6 will pose so many problems for the opponent.   Our center is very mobile and faces no opposition. As so often in the Austrian Attack, the f4 -pawn remains more of a liability than an asset, blocking the c1 -bishop. All in all, White is facing an uphill battle.} *

