1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. d5 {This is a very popular continuation, especially in those cases when White is not ready to challenge us in very topical theoretical variations. White hopes to keep their central pawns and castle, retaining some advantage. Black does get a few moves, however, to complicate matters.} O-O {As always, we castle first and think later. It is much easier to define the plans in the center of the board once the king has been tucked away safely.} 7. Be2 {This is a very possible way to develop the white pieces but doesn't pose any problems for Black. One of the drawbacks of having the bishop on e2 as opposed to d3 is that, in many lines, the e4 -pawn is not sufficiently protected. We have a wide choice of possible continuations here, and I'll show you what I think is the simplest.} e6 {Since White's last move did very little to control the center and to defend the e4 -pawn, it is very logical for Black to open up the e-file and get immediate counterplay. We could, of course, also go ... b5 and make it work, but the central strategy seems very easy for Black here.} 8. dxe6 {This capture looks logical, and White could be forgiven for thinking that the d6 -pawn could be weak later on. The truth is Black is very well developed and will easily achieve the central break with the timely ... d5 .} (8. O-O exd5 9. e5 Nfd7 {isn't dangerous for Black either.}) 8... Bxe6 ({Development first, of course. Recapturing} 8... fxe6 {would allow} 9. e5 {and lead to completely unnecessary suffering.}) 9. Ng5 {Given that the alternatives are somewhat bland, White at least decides to get the bishop pair. In this particular position, however, the bishop pair will not provide any advantage.} Nc6 {Natural and easy development. The black knight is very happy here, eyeing the dream square on d4 .} 10. Nxe6 {At least White is consistent. If they waited with this capture for too long, Black could reconsider and maybe move the bishop away at some later point.} fxe6 {We actually do not mind this structural change. The pawn appearing on e6 strengthens Black's center, and now the f8 -rook has something to do. In the longer term, the e6 -pawn will help us to break through in the center with ... d6 - d5 .} 11. O-O {Given that the d-file is open and the d6 -pawn is vulnerable, maybe in the ideal world, White would like to prepare to castle long. But in reality, they are just not developed enough for this, and this is a common problem with the Austrian Attack. Having made so many pawn moves in the opening often ends up losing precious time.} Qe7 {It's a very comfortable square for the black queen. Now, we can choose from many different plans, but mainly, they will be connected to the central breakthrough ... d6 - d5 . The black knight can end up on d4 , and the king will find a very comfortable spot on h8 .  I'm not trying to say that Black is better here since White has their fair share of chances with a pretty healthy position and two bishops, but given the choice, I would probably choose to play with the black pieces.} *

