1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. d5 {This is a very popular continuation, especially in those cases when White is not ready to challenge us in very topical theoretical variations. White hopes to keep their central pawns and castle, retaining some advantage. Black does get a few moves, however, to complicate matters.} O-O {As always, we castle first and think later. It is much easier to define the plans in the center of the board once the king has been tucked away safely.} 7. Bd3 {This is a very natural move, developing the bishop and defending the e4 -pawn at the same time. White looks ready to castle next and claim some advantage. We do have a surprise, however.} c4 {Despite this position having been played thousands of times, this move is almost entirely a novelty, at least in over-the-board practice. It is interesting to note that the online community has spotted this idea already and has been using it with some decent results.} 8. Bxc4 {White takes the pawn, of course. Now all White needs is just one move to be able to castle...} b5 {We have to keep generating threats! This is the second pawn sacrifice in 8 moves, and while not a record, it's still very impressive. By now it will be clear to our opponent that White's task is not going to be easy.} 9. Nxb5 {White has two possibilities to capture the pawn, and this is by far the better one. By transposition, and I was surprised to discover that this leads to a well-known position. I had to look twice to understand how that was possible – in fact, there is some theory where Black goes ... b5 first, followed by ... c4 .} Nxe4 {We don't have to be asked twice to take the central pawn, of course. Now Black has some serious strategic compensation for the pawn – the long diagonal is open, and the knight is very strong on e4 . Furthermore, there are also some tactical finesses that White has to watch out for.} 10. O-O {The simple move is also the best one. In my experience, bringing your king into safety is usually a good idea.} Qb6+ {This check is not immediately fatal but still forces White to find an only move. The resulting pin is quite awkward to live with.} 11. Nbd4 {Since everything else loses at once, White is forced to allow the nasty pin along the a7 - g1 diagonal. The d4 - knight is more stable than it looks, however, and Black doesn't have any immediate ways to increase the pressure.} Nf6 {This surprising retreat shows the true weakness of White's position, the d5 -pawn. Since trying to win d4 -knight by using all the pins didn't work out, Black now concentrates on simply attacking the d5 -pawn several times. In the long run, White will lose this pawn, and the central superiority should give Black the easier play. Furthermore, ... Nf6 is a novelty, and that's always nice.} ({If White tries hard to hold on to the d5 -pawn with Bb3 and c4 , this decision will be regretted soon. Following} 11... a5 {c4} 12. Ba6 {Be3 Ng4 Re1} a4 {Bxa4} 13. Bc4 {, White's pieces are very loose, and the pawns on d5 and b2 are hanging as well. White is better off to prevent ... a4 ideas with a4 , but after ... Nbd7 - c5 and ... Ba6 , White's pawn structure will start showing signs of sickness once again.}) *

