1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. d5 {This is a very popular continuation, especially in those cases when White is not ready to challenge us in very topical theoretical variations. White hopes to keep their central pawns and castle, retaining some advantage. Black does get a few moves, however, to complicate matters.} O-O {As always, we castle first and think later. It is much easier to define the plans in the center of the board once the king has been tucked away safely.} 7. Bd3 {This is a very natural move, developing the bishop and defending the e4 -pawn at the same time. White looks ready to castle next and claim some advantage. We do have a surprise, however.} c4 {Despite this position having been played thousands of times, this move is almost entirely a novelty, at least in over-the-board practice. It is interesting to note that the online community has spotted this idea already and has been using it with some decent results.} 8. Bxc4 {White takes the pawn, of course. Now all White needs is just one move to be able to castle...} b5 {We have to keep generating threats! This is the second pawn sacrifice in 8 moves, and while not a record, it's still very impressive. By now it will be clear to our opponent that White's task is not going to be easy.} 9. Nxb5 {White has two possibilities to capture the pawn, and this is by far the better one. By transposition, and I was surprised to discover that this leads to a well-known position. I had to look twice to understand how that was possible – in fact, there is some theory where Black goes ... b5 first, followed by ... c4 .} Nxe4 {We don't have to be asked twice to take the central pawn, of course. Now Black has some serious strategic compensation for the pawn – the long diagonal is open, and the knight is very strong on e4 . Furthermore, there are also some tactical finesses that White has to watch out for.} 10. Qe2 {This move is very natural, very popular, and also a serious mistake. Sometimes these things do happen. :) In the Pirc, these things happen so often that it makes you wonder if anybody seriously analyzed this before we came around to do this.} Qa5+ {Now this move is as natural as it is unpleasant for White to face, and it has been played a few times. What is most amazing, though, is that nobody discovered the follow-up.} 11. c3 {Since it is, unfortunately, illegal to castle when in check, White confidently blocks the e1 - a5 -diagonal and hopes to be able to castle on the next move. They are in for a most unpleasant surprise, though.} Nxc3 {In various databases, I discovered at least eight games where Black had a chance to execute this tactical blow and no one was able to find it. :( It is, of course, easier to find tactical nuances when assisted by a computer, and yet you would think that this shot would be within the range of most players, right?  Now, at the very least, Black wins the sacrificed pawn back and, in most cases, also retains quite a substantial positional advantage. White will have to fight very hard in order not to lose this position.} *

