1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. d5 {This is a very popular continuation, especially in those cases when White is not ready to challenge us in very topical theoretical variations. White hopes to keep their central pawns and castle, retaining some advantage. Black does get a few moves, however, to complicate matters.} O-O {As always, we castle first and think later. It is much easier to define the plans in the center of the board once the king has been tucked away safely.} 7. Bd3 {This is a very natural move, developing the bishop and defending the e4 -pawn at the same time. White looks ready to castle next and claim some advantage. We do have a surprise, however.} c4 {Despite this position having been played thousands of times, this move is almost entirely a novelty, at least in over-the-board practice. It is interesting to note that the online community has spotted this idea already and has been using it with some decent results.} 8. Bxc4 {White takes the pawn, of course. Now all White needs is just one move to be able to castle...} b5 {We have to keep generating threats! This is the second pawn sacrifice in 8 moves, and while not a record, it's still very impressive. By now it will be clear to our opponent that White's task is not going to be easy.} 9. Bxb5 {This is by far the worst response, leading to immediate problems for White. Sometimes, in chess being two pawns up doesn't guarantee anything.} Nxe4 {This typical trick works beautifully here. No matter what White will do, their position will sustain some serious damage. Black is already better.} *

