{The only thing Black should know in this position is why Bd4? doesn't work. Bxd4 Nxd4 Nxe4! Qxe4 f5∓ .} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. d5 {This is a very popular continuation, especially in those cases when White is not ready to challenge us in very topical theoretical variations. White hopes to keep their central pawns and castle, retaining some advantage. Black does get a few moves, however, to complicate matters.} O-O {As always, we castle first and think later. It is much easier to define the plans in the center of the board once the king has been tucked away safely.} 7. Bd3 {This is a very natural move, developing the bishop and defending the e4 -pawn at the same time. White looks ready to castle next and claim some advantage. We do have a surprise, however.} c4 {Despite this position having been played thousands of times, this move is almost entirely a novelty, at least in over-the-board practice. It is interesting to note that the online community has spotted this idea already and has been using it with some decent results.} 8. Bxc4 {White takes the pawn, of course. Now all White needs is just one move to be able to castle...} b5 {We have to keep generating threats! This is the second pawn sacrifice in 8 moves, and while not a record, it's still very impressive. By now it will be clear to our opponent that White's task is not going to be easy.} 9. Bd3 {This calm retreat attempts to keep everything under control. White is a pawn up and seems to have a nice and safe position. But the real problem is that the white king is stuck in the center, and that makes all the difference. For now, Black has the move and the initiative and can keep the white king in the center for a surprisingly long time.} b4 {An extremely important advance. Not only do we move the b-pawn from the square where it was hanging, but also we force the white knight to go to some unhappy places. You might know this from the Sicilian – it has always been my experience that once Black goes ... b4 , all the squares available to the c3 -knight are pretty terrible. And this is not different here.} 10. Ne2 {By far the most natural square for the white knight. All White wants to do now is to castle and we cannot allow this, which makes our reply pretty much forced.} Qb6 {Of course! Once again, in this line, the queen appears on b6 , and the white king starts feeling somewhat nervous after that. From now on, the entire play will develop along the lines of White trying to castle and Black trying to prevent it.} 11. Ng3 {Preparing Qe2 , which would control White's most vulnerable squares. The next few moves will be Qe2 , Be3 , and O-O , but this is a lengthy plan, and those are notoriously difficult to execute.} Na6 {We have all the time in the world. This knight goes to c5 , which is a really beautiful square. From there, Black will exert a lot of pressure on the d3 -bishop and the e4 -pawn.} 12. Qe2 {White follows the plan that is unfortunately doomed to fail.} Nc5 {The knight has reached its destination, and although it blocks the b6 - g1 -diagonal, White is still very far away from being able to castle. Amongst other things, Black threatens to open up the center by playing ... e6 .} 13. Be3 {This move was the plan all along, and it almost looks like White will be able to finally castle and enjoy the extra pawn. Unfortunately, White is just a move too late.} Ng4 {Black starts attacking White's pieces and pawns while the white king is still stuck in the center and tactics just do not work out well for White in this position. It seems that White's best move is retreating the bishop to c1 and trying to weather the storm, but nobody would think that this is a decent outcome of the opening for White.} *

