1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 {This is a very popular and very natural move. To some extent, this is also a default reaction from White when they're not ready for this line, so Black really has to know the plans here.} Qa5 {This move is very much the reason why we can play this line at all. Of course, our plan was never to take back on c5 and get a very bad ending. Having played ... Qa5 , we attack both the c5 -pawn and the e4 -pawn, and this typical idea allows us to restore the material balance. Now, White has a lot of possible moves, and we'll try to take a look at most of them.} 7. Bd3 {This natural move develops the bishop and defends the e4 -pawn. You are very likely to encounter this position at least a couple of times during your career of playing this opening. As I said earlier, White has a lot of alternatives, and we will cover them separately.} Qxc5 {We restored the material balance and also, at least temporarily, stopped White from castling short. The resulting structure is more reminiscent of some lines of the Sicilian than of the Pirc, so it will be useful to acquaint ourselves with general ideas.} 8. Qe2 {A necessary move, of course. White needs to be able to play Be3 in order to complete development.} O-O {Sometimes Black waits with this move and develops the pieces instead. I don't really understand the advantage of having the king on e8 , though. Bringing the king to safety can never be a mistake. :)} 9. Be3 {White follows the plan that was already indicated by their last move. Developing the piece with a gain of time is always a pleasant thing to do, and kicking the black queen away from c5 also enables White to castle short.} Qa5 10. h3 {Sometimes White plays this to stop the black pieces from accessing the g4 -square, but neither ... Bg4 nor ... Ng4 are very serious threats. The loss of time for yet another pawn move allows Black to seize the initiative immediately.} b5 {Using the fact that the white king is still stuck in the center, Black starts generating some threats immediately. Since this pawn is a taboo, White will have to take some defensive measures.} *

