1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 {This is a very popular and very natural move. To some extent, this is also a default reaction from White when they're not ready for this line, so Black really has to know the plans here.} Qa5 {This move is very much the reason why we can play this line at all. Of course, our plan was never to take back on c5 and get a very bad ending. Having played ... Qa5 , we attack both the c5 -pawn and the e4 -pawn, and this typical idea allows us to restore the material balance. Now, White has a lot of possible moves, and we'll try to take a look at most of them.} 7. Bd3 {This natural move develops the bishop and defends the e4 -pawn. You are very likely to encounter this position at least a couple of times during your career of playing this opening. As I said earlier, White has a lot of alternatives, and we will cover them separately.} Qxc5 {We restored the material balance and also, at least temporarily, stopped White from castling short. The resulting structure is more reminiscent of some lines of the Sicilian than of the Pirc, so it will be useful to acquaint ourselves with general ideas.} 8. Qe2 {A necessary move, of course. White needs to be able to play Be3 in order to complete development.} O-O {Sometimes Black waits with this move and develops the pieces instead. I don't really understand the advantage of having the king on e8 , though. Bringing the king to safety can never be a mistake. :)} 9. Be3 {White follows the plan that was already indicated by their last move. Developing the piece with a gain of time is always a pleasant thing to do, and kicking the black queen away from c5 also enables White to castle short.} Qa5 10. O-O {What we said earlier about the black king also applies to White. There is no reason to postpone this move, and castling long is far more dangerous.} Bg4 {It's best to make this move immediately. It is notoriously difficult to play with the c8 -bishop remaining passive, and that's exactly what could happen if we wait one more move and allow White to play h3 . Once again, this is the type of position where White's advantage of having the bishop pair will not be felt too much.} 11. Qe1 {This could be a more sophisticated move, but in reality it doesn't change very much. We still follow the same plan of exchanging the g4 -bishop for the knight.} Bxf3 {It might seem a bit strange to take on f3 without being forced to. But in fact, the g4 -bishop could remain dangerously misplaced if the f3 -knight were allowed to move away, and even risk getting trapped.} 12. Rxf3 ({The recapture is absolutely automatic, and in all the games I could find in this position, nobody ever took back with a pawn. I probably should have kept my mouth shut, but to me,} 12. gxf3 {seems to deserve some attention. And please don't worry about it, no one will ever do this. :)}) 12... Nc6 {Similarly to the main line, this knight is developed to c6 to leave the d7 -square free for the colleague.} 13. Kh1 {An important move in many similar positions, it is also very popular in this particular case. The white king gets out of a dangerous a7 - g1 diagonal, taking the sting out of any potential ... Ng4 ideas. Now, given time, White will slowly build up a dangerous attack on the kingside, profiting from the absence of the pawn from h3 . That is why Black needs to react a bit more urgently now.} d5 {Rather than sit and wait for the potential attack on the kingside, Black immediately strikes in the center. More broadly, this is a very useful strategy when facing an attack, and in this particular position, this move leads to mass exchanges and very playable endings.  As is the case in the Sicilian, for instance, endings generally tend to favor Black in this structure due to a greater long-term central control. We do have more pawns in the center of the board after all.} *

