1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 {This is a very popular and very natural move. To some extent, this is also a default reaction from White when they're not ready for this line, so Black really has to know the plans here.} Qa5 {This move is very much the reason why we can play this line at all. Of course, our plan was never to take back on c5 and get a very bad ending. Having played ... Qa5 , we attack both the c5 -pawn and the e4 -pawn, and this typical idea allows us to restore the material balance. Now, White has a lot of possible moves, and we'll try to take a look at most of them.} 7. Bd3 {This natural move develops the bishop and defends the e4 -pawn. You are very likely to encounter this position at least a couple of times during your career of playing this opening. As I said earlier, White has a lot of alternatives, and we will cover them separately.} Qxc5 {We restored the material balance and also, at least temporarily, stopped White from castling short. The resulting structure is more reminiscent of some lines of the Sicilian than of the Pirc, so it will be useful to acquaint ourselves with general ideas.} 8. Qe2 {A necessary move, of course. White needs to be able to play Be3 in order to complete development.} O-O {Sometimes Black waits with this move and develops the pieces instead. I don't really understand the advantage of having the king on e8 , though. Bringing the king to safety can never be a mistake. :)} 9. Be3 {White follows the plan that was already indicated by their last move. Developing the piece with a gain of time is always a pleasant thing to do, and kicking the black queen away from c5 also enables White to castle short.} Qa5 10. O-O {What we said earlier about the black king also applies to White. There is no reason to postpone this move, and castling long is far more dangerous.} Bg4 {It's best to make this move immediately. It is notoriously difficult to play with the c8 -bishop remaining passive, and that's exactly what could happen if we wait one more move and allow White to play h3 . Once again, this is the type of position where White's advantage of having the bishop pair will not be felt too much.} 11. h3 {White immediately clarifies the situation and practically forces Black to take on f3 . The pawn on h3 does have some drawbacks, however. Weakening the g3 -square is one, and occupying the h3 -square, which was potentially available for the white rook, is another.} Bxf3 {It is a bit late to change our mind here and, to be frank, we are quite happy to get rid of this bishop. We do have a plan for covering the light squares, but more on this later. Stay tuned. :)} 12. Qxf3 {By far the more natural recapture. Sometimes people take with a rook, but the rook does look a bit awkward on f3 .} Nc6 {You probably noticed it by now, but maybe it's a good idea to remind you. When possible, we develop the b8 -knight to c6 , and the d7 -square remains reserved for the one on f6 . This way, everyone is so happy that some people even call it harmony!} 13. a3 {This modest pawn move is by far the most popular and also an admission that White doesn't have any active and dangerous ideas. Since the bishop pair is about the only thing White can be proud of, they decide to keep the d3 -bishop safe.} Nd7 {A very natural move that allows the g7 -bishop to breathe freely. It is perhaps important to look at this position in greater detail. Our pieces cover almost all the dark squares in the center of the board, and we will use our pawns to cover the light ones.  Remember I told you a few moves ago that we had a plan for our light squares? This is exactly the plan. And it makes our play over the next few moves much easier, we will likely play ... e6 , ... a6 , ... b5 . In contrast, it is much more difficult for White to come up with a decent plan since White doesn't have many useful pawn breaks.} *

