1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qd4 {This unusual move has been enjoying certain popularity lately. White is trying to provoke taking on c5 in a way that would spoil Black's structure, but fortunately, we have many playable alternatives.} O-O {This move is by far the best. Not only do we get the king into safety, but also, by protecting the g7 -bishop, we renew the threat of ... Nxe4 . Furthermore, the d4 -queen will give us a lot of time to develop our pieces.} 8. cxd6 {It is a possible move and one that we should know well. White simply continues to take pawns and insists on being shown the compensation. Black has at least two very decent lines here, both of which we'll examine.} exd6 ({By simply recapturing the pawn Black keeps all the threats and opens the e-file at the same time. This move is less forcing and more strategically complex than the alternative,} 8... Nxe4 {.}) 9. Bd2 {As we have seen throughout this line, While needs to defend the c3 -knight in order to prevent all the deadly tactics with ... Nxe4 and the like.} Nc6 {We develop the knight with a gain of time and also force White to make a difficult decision as to where to move the queen.} 10. Qe3 {This seems like the best square for the white queen. This position has been tested a few times in correspondence chess, and Black didn't have many problems. In fact, the only real problem Black has is choosing between various very promising continuations.} Re8 {We politely remind our opponent that they have a number of weaknesses along the e-file. White is now forced to be very, very precise.} 11. Bd3 {What could be more natural than this move, defending the weaknesses on c2 and e4 , preparing to castle short at the same time? I was surprised to discover that this move was a mistake, and frankly shocked to find out why.} Qd8 {This is a truly spectacular moment. Black is pawn down, it's as early as move 11, and still Black somehow creates decisive threats that cannot be parried. I thought long and hard about some similar example in the opening theory and yet nothing came to mind. This could be one-of-a-kind.} *

