{In the only game I could find in this position, a very high-quality correspondence encounter in 2018, White found a way to make a quiet draw after Nb5 , and this is probably the best White can hope for.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qd4 {This unusual move has been enjoying certain popularity lately. White is trying to provoke taking on c5 in a way that would spoil Black's structure, but fortunately, we have many playable alternatives.} O-O {This move is by far the best. Not only do we get the king into safety, but also, by protecting the g7 -bishop, we renew the threat of ... Nxe4 . Furthermore, the d4 -queen will give us a lot of time to develop our pieces.} 8. cxd6 {It is a possible move and one that we should know well. White simply continues to take pawns and insists on being shown the compensation. Black has at least two very decent lines here, both of which we'll examine.} exd6 ({By simply recapturing the pawn Black keeps all the threats and opens the e-file at the same time. This move is less forcing and more strategically complex than the alternative,} 8... Nxe4 {.}) 9. Bd2 {As we have seen throughout this line, While needs to defend the c3 -knight in order to prevent all the deadly tactics with ... Nxe4 and the like.} Nc6 {We develop the knight with a gain of time and also force White to make a difficult decision as to where to move the queen.} 10. Qe3 {This seems like the best square for the white queen. This position has been tested a few times in correspondence chess, and Black didn't have many problems. In fact, the only real problem Black has is choosing between various very promising continuations.} Re8 {We politely remind our opponent that they have a number of weaknesses along the e-file. White is now forced to be very, very precise.} 11. Bc4 {White needs to play this to keep the approximate equality. The bishop is well placed on c4 , also reminding Black of the single weakness in their position, the f7 -pawn.} ({The alternatives are weaker – for instance,} 11. O-O-O {would run into a deadly attack after} Nb4 {, and placing the bishop on d3 , however natural, runs into a very unusual problem.}) 11... Nb4 {One of many ways to prove Black's compensation. By attacking the c2 -pawn, Black forces the c4 -bishop to assume a much more defensive role.} 12. Bb3 {There is nothing better. Once again, castling long would just bring the white king into mortal danger.} Be6 {It's quite a thematic move for this line. Black covers the f7 -pawn and exchanges the light-squared bishops to get to the c2 -square.} ({There is a very healthy alternative,} 12... Bf5 {, which leads to serious complications and equality at the end of the line. If you're interested, I'm sure you'll have a lot of fun checking the line yourself.}) 13. O-O {Just in time, White manages to get the king into safety. White is still up a pawn, so we have to wind down our usual optimism and show ways to clean equality. This position has been played in some correspondence games, and that's usually a good sign. Assuming some minimal knowledge of the ensuing lines, Black has very little to worry about.} Bxb3 {We take at exactly the right moment when White is limited in the ways to recapture. Because of the possible ... Nc2 fork, White has to take with the a-pawn, leaving the c2 -pawn a permanent weakness.} 14. axb3 {As mentioned above, this move is absolutely forced. White gains some time because the black queen will have to retreat, but the c2 -pawn will remain a problem for a long time.} Qc7 {The time has come to draw some conclusions. White is still up a pawn, but Black has excellent compensation due to more active pieces and potentially better endgames with the healthier pawn structure. White has chronic weaknesses on c2 and e4 , and the attempt to get stubborn to try and keep the extra pawn will result in Black attacking the e4 -pawn a few times to win it for free.} *

