1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qd4 {This unusual move has been enjoying certain popularity lately. White is trying to provoke taking on c5 in a way that would spoil Black's structure, but fortunately, we have many playable alternatives.} O-O {This move is by far the best. Not only do we get the king into safety, but also, by protecting the g7 -bishop, we renew the threat of ... Nxe4 . Furthermore, the d4 -queen will give us a lot of time to develop our pieces.} 8. cxd6 {It is a possible move and one that we should know well. White simply continues to take pawns and insists on being shown the compensation. Black has at least two very decent lines here, both of which we'll examine.} Nxe4 ({This move is very playable, and I, in fact, hesitated whether to offer this as the main line for this course. I only suggested} 8... exd6 {as the main move because it seemed that Black could have more of an upside there. I will give the next few moves without commentary because the line is essentially forced.}) 9. Qxe4 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Kf2 Qxa1 12. dxe7 Re8 13. Bc4 Qf6 {The end of the forcing sequence leads to the position where Black will still need to make some decent moves to neutralize White's initiative. At some point, Black will have to give back the exchange and aim for further simplification. The drawback of this approach is that it's basically a competition in memory rather than chess.} *

