1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qd4 {This unusual move has been enjoying certain popularity lately. White is trying to provoke taking on c5 in a way that would spoil Black's structure, but fortunately, we have many playable alternatives.} O-O {This move is by far the best. Not only do we get the king into safety, but also, by protecting the g7 -bishop, we renew the threat of ... Nxe4 . Furthermore, the d4 -queen will give us a lot of time to develop our pieces.} 8. Bd2 {This solid move has been chosen by many strong players. By defending the c3 -knight, White safeguards the e4 -pawn and also gets ready to castle long. On the other hand, the exposed nature of the d4 -queen will allow Black to develop their pieces for free.} Nc6 {In chess, time is everything, so we certainly use this opportunity to develop the knight for free. Once again, taking the c5 -pawn would lead to a structure that's favorable for White. Over the next few moves, White will have to tread very carefully.} 9. Qc4 {By far the most popular retreat. The white queen keeps in touch with the queenside, and White is still hoping to be able to exchange the queens.} Be6 {Just like on the last move, we use this opportunity to develop the piece for free. As so often in the Austrian Attack, Black is ahead in development here, having both deployed all the pieces and castled. White frequently falling behind in development is a sign of something being wrong with the opening strategy.} 10. Nd5 {It looks very natural to centralize the knight, but unfortunately for White, the knight is not very stable here. The e4 -pawn becomes more vulnerable, and the pin along the g8 - a2 diagonal doesn't help either.} Qd8 {This is the most ambitious approach. There was absolutely nothing wrong with taking the c5 -pawn and restoring the material balance, but Black will most likely gain more by keeping the queens on the board.} 11. O-O-O {Of course, White uses the chance to castle, especially given that the d1 -rook supports the wayward knight.} Rc8 {The rook is very well placed here, eyeing both the white king and the white queen from the distance. White's formation in the center is far less stable than it looks, and Black has some serious threats, too, like the unusual ... Nb8 , for instance, winning the c5 -pawn. For all practical purposes, Black is already much better.} *

