1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qd4 {This unusual move has been enjoying certain popularity lately. White is trying to provoke taking on c5 in a way that would spoil Black's structure, but fortunately, we have many playable alternatives.} O-O {This move is by far the best. Not only do we get the king into safety, but also, by protecting the g7 -bishop, we renew the threat of ... Nxe4 . Furthermore, the d4 -queen will give us a lot of time to develop our pieces.} 8. Bd2 {This solid move has been chosen by many strong players. By defending the c3 -knight, White safeguards the e4 -pawn and also gets ready to castle long. On the other hand, the exposed nature of the d4 -queen will allow Black to develop their pieces for free.} Nc6 {In chess, time is everything, so we certainly use this opportunity to develop the knight for free. Once again, taking the c5 -pawn would lead to a structure that's favorable for White. Over the next few moves, White will have to tread very carefully.} 9. Qc4 {By far the most popular retreat. The white queen keeps in touch with the queenside, and White is still hoping to be able to exchange the queens.} Be6 {Just like on the last move, we use this opportunity to develop the piece for free. As so often in the Austrian Attack, Black is ahead in development here, having both deployed all the pieces and castled. White frequently falling behind in development is a sign of something being wrong with the opening strategy.} 10. Qb5 {White insists, but by now, it's basically just wishful thinking. The white queen was vulnerable on d4 , and on c4 , and now it will be vulnerable on b5 , and White is still far away from finishing their development. One lonely pawn is not even close to enough to compensate for all these troubles.} Qc7 {Of course, we keep the queens on the board. Black is perfectly developed and has all the reasons to be ambitious.} 11. O-O-O {White, quite correctly, uses this chance to castle. Whether the queenside will be a safe space for White in the long term is a completely different story. It is perhaps important to add that White should refrain, now and later, from taking on d6 in order not to open the c-file.} Rac8 {From c8 , the black rook exerts a lot of pressure. The white queen, most unnaturally placed on b5 , continues to be a constant source of worry for White. Sooner or later, the files and diagonals leading to the white king will open, and White will face a long and difficult defense. The extra pawn provides very little consolation. In short, this is probably not the variation that White should ever employ.} *

