1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Bb5+ {A strangely popular move that doesn't have a point. Unless you're playing the game of three checks, of course, then it's really great. :)} Bd7 {Black is happy to exchange the light-squared bishops since the e4 -pawn remains vulnerable.} 8. Bxd7+ {This exchange only helps Black, but White doesn't have anything in the way of alternatives since both the b5 -bishop and the e4 -pawn are hanging.} Nbxd7 {Black managed to develop two pieces with one exchange, a most welcome outcome. Since White will be missing the light-squared bishop to give the e4 -pawn the solid protection it needs, Black has all the reasons to view the future with optimism.} *

