1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qe2 {We have to be aware of the existence of the slightly unusual-looking move. First of all, it's a cunning trap and, secondly, it leads to an endgame that is difficult to play unless you know what you're doing.} Qxc5 ({As always, we take the c5 -pawn with the queen. It is very important to note that the tempting tactical trick with} 7... Nxe4 {loses a piece to} 8. Qb5+ Qxb5 9. Bxb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nxe4 {. The same, of course, is true for the line where White plays Qd3 .}) 8. Be3 {The existence of this move is one of the reasons behind the line with Qe2 . It develops the bishop for free and enables castling long.} Qa5 {Black returns the queen to the most natural square and renews the threat of ... Nxe4 . White's somewhat awkward setup only makes sense because of what happens next.} 9. Qb5+ {This is the whole point. White aims to get a slightly more pleasant ending with better development of pieces and some initiative. The fact that this line has become the preferred weapon of many strong players shows how solid this opening is and how little White can actually fight for. Assuming we know some lines, this endgame is nothing to be afraid of.} Qxb5 {This move is forced. The attempt to develop the knight unfortunately runs into serious trouble.} 10. Nxb5 {This looks quite tempting but doesn't have its usual decisive effect. Black will easily parry the stronger of the two threats, and the e4 -pawn hanging in the center will tie White down quite a bit.} Na6 {Black prevents the more decisive of the two threats. White's central pawn hanging on e4 demands some attention and prevents White from being able to capitalize on the weakness of the a7 -pawn. Usually, a6 is not a very good square for the black knight, but in this particular position, it has some future, often jumping to b4 or sometimes c5 .} *

