1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Here we will take a look at the various alternatives White has to the main line. Most of these alternatives are not at all dangerous for Black, but some amount of knowledge is of course necessary.} 7. Qe2 {We have to be aware of the existence of the slightly unusual-looking move. First of all, it's a cunning trap and, secondly, it leads to an endgame that is difficult to play unless you know what you're doing.} Qxc5 ({As always, we take the c5 -pawn with the queen. It is very important to note that the tempting tactical trick with} 7... Nxe4 {loses a piece to} 8. Qb5+ Qxb5 9. Bxb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nxe4 {. The same, of course, is true for the line where White plays Qd3 .}) 8. Be3 {The existence of this move is one of the reasons behind the line with Qe2 . It develops the bishop for free and enables castling long.} Qa5 {Black returns the queen to the most natural square and renews the threat of ... Nxe4 . White's somewhat awkward setup only makes sense because of what happens next.} 9. Qb5+ {This is the whole point. White aims to get a slightly more pleasant ending with better development of pieces and some initiative. The fact that this line has become the preferred weapon of many strong players shows how solid this opening is and how little White can actually fight for. Assuming we know some lines, this endgame is nothing to be afraid of.} Qxb5 {This move is forced. The attempt to develop the knight unfortunately runs into serious trouble.} 10. Bxb5+ {This move seems to be the better one by far and also the choice of many strong players. White develops the last minor piece and is ready to castle either side depending on Black's reaction.} Nc6 {As in many different positions in this line, when possible, we develop this knight to c6 . Other moves are possible, but they look more passive to me.} 11. O-O-O {Very often in this line, White avoids castling long since the c1 -king can get into trouble in the long run. The queens having been exchanged, however, changes everything, and White quite correctly tries to put Black under immediate pressure.} (11. e5 dxe5 12. Nxe5 Ng4 $1 {A very important point that shows that White is not yet ready for immediate action in the center.}) 11... Bg4 {Pinning the f3 -knight is an effective way to fight against the immediate breakthrough in the center. We may have to exchange this bishop in the future, but often, White will either lose a lot of time or get the damaged pawn structure as a result of this trade.} 12. Nd5 {We should probably know this dangerous-looking move in order not to panic over the board. Black's position looks precarious, but in fact, we have several good ways to play.} Nxd5 {This move looks decidedly dangerous for Black, but it does have a very decent strategic and tactical foundation. We could also just castle long instead, although I prefer our main line because it clarifies the situation nicely.} 13. exd5 {White seems to be making a lot of progress, but things are actually quite far from simple here. Before we get too deep into the strategic aspects of it, however, the first priority is not to lose the piece.} a6 {This is clearly the only mechanism to save the piece, but interestingly, not the only move. Black could also take on f3 first, damaging White's pawn structure in the process.  Taking the knight without being forced to, however, costs Black some time, and White can use this time to develop some initiative. This is one of those eternal conflicts in chess – what is more important, initiative or the structure? In this particular position, it seems to be more or less a matter of taste.} 14. Be2 {A wise retreat. White cannot profit from any possible tactical skirmishes on the queenside and does well to keep the bishops alive and the structure healthy.} Nb8 {Black, too, needs to retreat and has to choose the square for the knight carefully. Amongst a lot of squares available, only the b8 -square has a decent future. Now and later, we'll have to keep an eye on this knight. With the pawn structure having closed down a lot, this is the piece that will win us the game.} 15. h3 {White clarifies the situation. Of course, other moves were possible as well, but sooner or later White would have to play h3 anyway.} Bxf3 {We abandon this bishop without any regret. Its destiny was already sealed after Bg4 , and changing your mind halfway through is a dangerous thing. Chess is a very simple game. It basically comes down to finding a plan and sticking to it. :)} 16. Bxf3 {Given the choice, White certainly keeps the pawn structure intact.} b5 {It's an important move and a good moment to take stock. The b5 -pawn seriously limits White's possibilities on the queenside and also prepares a plan of gradual expansion. This expansion will involve ... Nd7 , ... Rb8 , ... Nb6 , and so on, with various possible outcomes.  Whether it's the ending with opposite-colored bishops or the ending with the knight against the light-squared bishop, we'll have no reason to complain. I feel it's much more difficult for White to come up with a decent plan here.} *

