1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ ({Besides the main} 7. e5 {, which is covered separately in great detail, this is the second most popular move. As we have seen so often before, this exchange only helps Black to develop the queenside pieces, and this can't really be good news for White.}) 7... Nbxd7 {The most natural recapture and also the strongest one. Both other reasonable captures are playable for Black and, in fact, have been played many times. But if we can develop the knight, why shouldn't we?} 8. d5 {This move closes the position in an attempt to keep some degree of control. The truth is White's center is much more vulnerable than it looks. As often before, the e4 -pawn will be missing its natural defender after the exchange of the light-squared bishops.} O-O {Before starting any action against White's central pawns, it is important to get the king into safety. Now ... b5 is a real threat that White should take seriously.} 9. O-O {Nothing could be more natural than to castle in this position, but as mentioned before, Black had a serious threat that needed to be dealt with. Sometimes, a careless move early in the opening can put you firmly on the defensive, and this is also the case here.} b5 {Having castled and finished the piece development, Black is fully justified in beginning some action. This move threatens the e4 -pawn and forces White to take some defensive measures. White will not profit from opening the center with e5 since Black is much better developed and thus will have to stick to passive defense from now on.} ({A sample line is} 9... e5 {dxe5} 10. fxe5 Ng4 11. e6 fxe6 12. dxe6 Nde5 {Qxd8 Raxd8} 13. Nb5 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Ne5 {, when Black is a pawn down but the enormous activity easily compensates for the material deficit.}) *

