1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ ({Besides the main} 7. e5 {, which is covered separately in great detail, this is the second most popular move. As we have seen so often before, this exchange only helps Black to develop the queenside pieces, and this can't really be good news for White.}) 7... Nbxd7 {The most natural recapture and also the strongest one. Both other reasonable captures are playable for Black and, in fact, have been played many times. But if we can develop the knight, why shouldn't we?} 8. d5 {This move closes the position in an attempt to keep some degree of control. The truth is White's center is much more vulnerable than it looks. As often before, the e4 -pawn will be missing its natural defender after the exchange of the light-squared bishops.} O-O {Before starting any action against White's central pawns, it is important to get the king into safety. Now ... b5 is a real threat that White should take seriously.} 9. Qe2 {This move has been tried by some very good players. They seemed to have been aware of Black's threat to play ... b5 and took some measures. The queen is generally well-placed here, defending the e4 -pawn, controlling the b5 -square and also sometimes preparing the central break with e5 . There are also some drawbacks to this placement, and Black's next move points this out.} Re8 {A nice little move that takes advantage of the fact that White has a lot of vulnerabilities along the e-file. We know that the e4 -pawn can be weak in the long term, and having the queen and the king on the same file adds to the problem. Black's threat of ... e6 is not easy to parry without positional concessions.} *

