1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ ({Besides the main} 7. e5 {, which is covered separately in great detail, this is the second most popular move. As we have seen so often before, this exchange only helps Black to develop the queenside pieces, and this can't really be good news for White.}) 7... Nbxd7 {The most natural recapture and also the strongest one. Both other reasonable captures are playable for Black and, in fact, have been played many times. But if we can develop the knight, why shouldn't we?} 8. d5 {This move closes the position in an attempt to keep some degree of control. The truth is White's center is much more vulnerable than it looks. As often before, the e4 -pawn will be missing its natural defender after the exchange of the light-squared bishops.} O-O {Before starting any action against White's central pawns, it is important to get the king into safety. Now ... b5 is a real threat that White should take seriously.} 9. a4 {This move is probably White's most prudent choice. The threat of ... b5 is stopped for now, but Black's counterplay on the queenside will still happen, although in a slightly different form.} a6 {Simply renewing the threat. In chess, it is almost always good to follow the intended plan. Here it is especially important to do so before White gets to complete development.} 10. a5 {This is a very typical way to slow down Black's counterplay. The breakthrough with ... b5 will still happen, but at least the c3 -knight will not be disturbed, and the e4 -pawn will feel a bit better as a result.} b5 {Now that White can take en passant, this move does not have the earth-shattering effect we had hoped for, but we still get to open a file on the queenside for our rooks. We can't always get what we want, at least not all of it. :)} 11. axb6 {The pawn completes its glorious mission, and the c3 -knight gets to breathe a sigh of relief. Play will slow down a bit now, and White can take care of the piece development, and finally castle that king.} Nxb6 {It might not immediately look obvious, but this knight has many vital functions here. It controls the key squares a4 and c4 , but most importantly, by keeping an eye on the d5 -pawn, it prevents any white advances in the center.} 12. O-O {Finally, White finds the time to castle. In the long run, White's central control could become quite menacing, so Black shouldn't wait around too long and should start the active play as soon as possible.} a5 {With this move, Black quite clearly indicates the plan they are going to follow. With both sides having finished development, it is a good time for us to take stock. Black will play on the queenside, where White has some weaknesses. In various order, ... a4 , ... Qd7 , ... Rfb8 , ... Nc4 are all very easy moves to make. Again, White, despite a very solid position finds it harder to come up with a plan.} *

