{White keeps some amount of counterplay after Re1 , but as long as we do not take the g7 -knight, allowing two rooks on the 7th rank, Black is doing more than fine.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. e6 {This is one of the three important tries that White has in this position. Since this is such a central position, we will cover each of them separately.} fxe6 ({I think this is by far the cleaner solution. We do need to know a few lines, but they all end very well for Black. The alternative,} 8... Bxb5 {, is much more messy.}) 9. Ng5 {This is the point of White's setup. The e6 -pawn and the g4 -knight are both hanging, and Black needs something truly spectacular to get out of this predicament alive. What happens now is one of the most famous opening discoveries in the history of chess.} Bxb5 {The beginning of a most majestic trick. Even now it's not easy to see that Black's counterplay is directed against the white king.} 10. Nxb5 {White quietly recaptures the b5 -bishop and retains the threats of Nxe6 and Qxg4 . Because of the severity of these threats, our answer is forced.} Qa5+ {Luckily, we have this check. The b5 -knight is now lost, and despite all appearances, Black will come out of the complications unscathed.} 11. Bd2 {It is the more natural of two ways to block the check. Surprisingly for such a sharp position, the b2 -pawn hanging becomes an issue.} Qxb5 {With the fall of the b5 -knight, it would be natural to expect the same thing to happen to the g4 -knight. Amazingly, this piece often survives the ensuing mess.} 12. Nxe6 {With this move, White is creating new threats and renewing the old ones. Perilous as Black's position is right now, we should not forget that we are up a piece. This gives us many unexpected opportunities in the ensuing complications.} Qxb2 {This is clearly the most active way to defend against a threatened fork. Not only did Black get the pawn, but the black queen can also be really annoying on b2 . You might know from the poisoned pawn in the Sicilian Defense that this queen is often an unpleasant guest in your backyard.} 13. Rb1 {This move has been tried a few times by some good players and, in a way, is the point behind White's idea. White uses the fact that the d4 -pawn is protected and postpones taking the g7 -bishop for one more move.} Qxa2 {Black takes another pawn. The queen continues to tie White down and controls the number of important squares along the a2 - g8 diagonal. Black is already substantially ahead in material and this forces White to finally take on g7 .} 14. Nxg7+ {Finally, White gets some material back.} Kf7 {The best square for our king. The hanging b1 -rook is still preventing the white queen from entering the play. White's next move is both natural and forced.} 15. O-O {Finally, White gets to castle! Now that the white king is safe, Black has to consolidate to keep things under control.} Nf6 {We make this careful move that keeps our best defender close to the king. As I mentioned some time ago, this knight, despite hanging on g4 for a few moves, often survives. Black is still up material and has a safe, compact position.} *

