{Besides ... Kxg7 , Black also has a nasty threat of ... dxc3 , for instance after Nh5 . Once Black restores the material balance, the well-known positional factors will work in our favor. In endings, the f4 -pawn will be obstructing the white bishop and the light squares could be vulnerable for some time to come.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. e6 {This is one of the three important tries that White has in this position. Since this is such a central position, we will cover each of them separately.} fxe6 ({I think this is by far the cleaner solution. We do need to know a few lines, but they all end very well for Black. The alternative,} 8... Bxb5 {, is much more messy.}) 9. Ng5 {This is the point of White's setup. The e6 -pawn and the g4 -knight are both hanging, and Black needs something truly spectacular to get out of this predicament alive. What happens now is one of the most famous opening discoveries in the history of chess.} Bxb5 {The beginning of a most majestic trick. Even now it's not easy to see that Black's counterplay is directed against the white king.} 10. Nxb5 {White quietly recaptures the b5 -bishop and retains the threats of Nxe6 and Qxg4 . Because of the severity of these threats, our answer is forced.} Qa5+ {Luckily, we have this check. The b5 -knight is now lost, and despite all appearances, Black will come out of the complications unscathed.} 11. c3 {This is the solid approach, keeping the b2 -pawn protected. Black's hand is now forced.} Qxb5 {Although there are no plausible alternatives to this move, it is still scary to place a queen on b5 in view of the possible fork with Nc7 . To play this position without panicking, we should know the next few moves very well.} 12. Nxe6 {Typically for this variation, White is a full piece down but has managed to create many strong threats. Black has two pieces hanging, and Nc7 + is a winning threat. Black's next move is vital for this variation and not a move you usually find unless you know what you're doing.} (12. Qxg4 {invariably leads to the same position as our main line and doesn't have an independent meaning.}) 12... Qc4 {It is the key move for this line, magically holding everything together. We step out of the threatened fork and find a way to keep our queen maximally active. From c4 , it controls many important squares and still prevents White from castling short.} 13. Qxg4 {White finally captures the knight and obtains what looks like a truly dominant position. Fortunately for us, we still have a few tricks up our sleeve. White could also immediately take the g7 -bishop, but again, that would lead to the same position as the main line.} cxd4 {It's a nice feeling to calmly capture the central pawn while the rest of the board is in flames. The white king is stuck in the center, and this prevents White's attack from becoming too strong. White can capture the g7 -bishop, of course, but this time, the knight will not make it back alive.} 14. Nxg7+ {Since Black firmly covered the c7 -square, White shouldn't wait too long with this capture. After most other moves, ... Bf6 would consolidate Black's position nicely.} Kf7 {Things have calmed down somewhat, and the time has come for us to take stock. For a change, White is temporarily a piece up, but the g7 -knight is hopelessly trapped. The white king is still stuck in the center, without the immediate possibility of castling. This makes any attacking chances White could have difficult to realize.} *

