1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. e6 {This is one of the three important tries that White has in this position. Since this is such a central position, we will cover each of them separately.} fxe6 ({I think this is by far the cleaner solution. We do need to know a few lines, but they all end very well for Black. The alternative,} 8... Bxb5 {, is much more messy.}) 9. Ng5 {This is the point of White's setup. The e6 -pawn and the g4 -knight are both hanging, and Black needs something truly spectacular to get out of this predicament alive. What happens now is one of the most famous opening discoveries in the history of chess.} Bxb5 {The beginning of a most majestic trick. Even now it's not easy to see that Black's counterplay is directed against the white king.} 10. Qxg4 {This move is not threatening at all and has largely fallen out of fashion by now.} Bc4 {Black defends the e6 -pawn and gets a good game. I discuss this position and this line in greater detail in one of our model games, Nunn-Seirawan , so please check it out.} *

