1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. e6 {This is one of the three important tries that White has in this position. Since this is such a central position, we will cover each of them separately.} fxe6 ({I think this is by far the cleaner solution. We do need to know a few lines, but they all end very well for Black. The alternative,} 8... Bxb5 {, is much more messy.}) 9. Ng5 {This is the point of White's setup. The e6 -pawn and the g4 -knight are both hanging, and Black needs something truly spectacular to get out of this predicament alive. What happens now is one of the most famous opening discoveries in the history of chess.} Bxb5 {The beginning of a most majestic trick. Even now it's not easy to see that Black's counterplay is directed against the white king.} 10. Nxe6 {Do you know any opening positions where Black made nine moves and has three minor pieces and the queen hanging? I don't, and I wouldn't be surprised if this position is one-of-a-kind. Black's situation looks desperate, but it only takes one move to make everything right.} Bxd4 {Now this is most definitely a bolt from the blue. There is something undeniably beautiful in Black's minor pieces finding sudden harmony. With this move, we remind our opponent that there are things more valuable in chess than the queen. The only thing White can do now is choose between various ways to make a draw.} 11. Nxb5 {This move is the only way for White to prolong the game, only to make a draw a few moves later or run into danger in a slightly worse ending.} Qa5+ {The queen, miraculously still alive, joins the battle. White should now be careful not to walk into the a6 - f1 diagonal.} 12. Qd2 ({This move has been played by some good players, who probably didn't feel at ease taking an early draw. Objectively speaking, however, the endgame after} 12. Qd2 {isn't promising for White.}) 12... Qxd2+ {The simplest. We no longer need to search for complications.} 13. Bxd2 {This position still looks difficult for Black because there is no good way to save the a8 -rook. It is quite remarkable that the threat of Nc7 turns out to be an illusion.} Kd7 {Black bravely centralizes the king and forces the white knight to make some choices. Whether White takes the exchange or not, Black will have the upper hand in the ending.} 14. Nbxd4 {White quietly admits that the opening strategy didn't lead anywhere. The resulting ending is not without some risks.} cxd4 {Funnily, Black could postpone this recapture since the white knights cannot run away, but why?} 15. Nxd4 Nc6 {The most natural move, posing immediate problems for White. Whether they will now exchange the knights or not, the resulting ending is promising for Black. We have a lot of nice light squares in the center for our knights to occupy, and the f4 -pawn severely limits the scope of the white bishop.} *

