1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. e6 {This is one of the three important tries that White has in this position. Since this is such a central position, we will cover each of them separately.} fxe6 ({I think this is by far the cleaner solution. We do need to know a few lines, but they all end very well for Black. The alternative,} 8... Bxb5 {, is much more messy.}) 9. Ng5 {This is the point of White's setup. The e6 -pawn and the g4 -knight are both hanging, and Black needs something truly spectacular to get out of this predicament alive. What happens now is one of the most famous opening discoveries in the history of chess.} Bxb5 {The beginning of a most majestic trick. Even now it's not easy to see that Black's counterplay is directed against the white king.} 10. Nxe6 {Do you know any opening positions where Black made nine moves and has three minor pieces and the queen hanging? I don't, and I wouldn't be surprised if this position is one-of-a-kind. Black's situation looks desperate, but it only takes one move to make everything right.} Bxd4 {Now this is most definitely a bolt from the blue. There is something undeniably beautiful in Black's minor pieces finding sudden harmony. With this move, we remind our opponent that there are things more valuable in chess than the queen. The only thing White can do now is choose between various ways to make a draw.} 11. Nxb5 {This move is the only way for White to prolong the game, only to make a draw a few moves later or run into danger in a slightly worse ending.} Qa5+ {The queen, miraculously still alive, joins the battle. White should now be careful not to walk into the a6 - f1 diagonal.} 12. c3 {The safest choice, forcing Black to make a draw with perpetual check once again. If White feels more ambitious than this, maybe they should have played a different system.} Bf2+ {It's the same mechanism but with a slight twist. Even in the absence of the b5 -bishop, the white king is forced to avoid the light squares.} 13. Kd2 {It is the only square that doesn't blunder a knight.} Be3+ {White is well-advised to call it a day since being stubborn with Kc2 leads to Black's advantage.} ({A sample line is Kc2} 13... Qa4 14. b3 ({Kb1 Qxd1} 14. Nec7+ Kd7 {Rxd1 Nc6} 15. Nxa8 {Rxa8 a4 Bxc1 Rxc1} Rf8 {with a better endgame for Black despite the material deficit. White's pieces lack harmony, and their kingside pawns are under surveillance as well.}) 14... Qe4 {Kb2 Qxg2+ Ka3 Nf2} 15. Nxd6+ $1 Kd7 $1 16. Qe2 {Bxc1+ Raxc1} exd6 {and this is perhaps a good moment to end the line. Now ... Qe4 is a threat, and if White prevents that with} 17. f5 {, after} Nc6 18. Rf1 gxf5 {, the engines claim that Black is slightly better in the complications.}) *

