1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. h3 ({It is very natural for White to try to push the black knight back immediately. This line is quite similar to} 8. Bxd7+ {and it will be useful for you to compare the two.}) 8... cxd4 {Our reaction here is quite typical. Since h6 is not a great square for the black knight, we postpone moving there for as long as possible.} 9. Qxd4 ({It's the only capture that makes sense.} 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {transposes us to another line .}) 9... Bxb5 {Black has playable alternatives to this move, but it is quite nice to provoke the white knight to b5 , where it will be tactically vulnerable.} 10. Nxb5 {White certainly should take the bishop and not the knight. In a position about to open up, leaving Black with a bishop pair would be suicidal.} Nc6 {It's always pleasant to develop a piece with a gain of time. Please note that the g4 -knight deprives the white queen of some nice squares.} 11. Qa4 {This move defends the b5 -knight, thus eliminating some elements of Black's counterplay. The possible drawback is that the a4 -queen can sometimes be sidelined.} Nh6 {The knight returns to safety, and the situation calms down somewhat. White looks overextended, but Black could easily run into trouble with their h6 -knight. As in most of the lines we've seen, the activation of this knight can either make or break Black's position.} 12. Bd2 {Sometimes chess can be a very simple game. The white king wouldn't be too happy on g1 , and the bishop is vulnerable on e3 . Hence this move, preparing to castle long.} O-O {Bringing the king to safety is almost always a priority. This has now been taken care of, so we can look into other things, such as activating the h6 -knight.} 13. O-O-O {After this move, both sides have officially finished their development. The d1 -rook is very well placed, putting a lot of pressure on the d8 -queen. Black now needs to activate the h6 -knight and not get into any trouble doing so. It's not an easy task, but fortunately, you have this course.} dxe5 {Sooner or later, we'll have to take this pawn anyway. There is a hidden point behind this move as well. Believe it or not, we are fighting for the d4 -square.} 14. fxe5 {It is by far the most threatening recapture. White opens the c1 - h6 diagonal for the bishop, and the e5 -pawn will be very useful in controlling the d6 -square so that the black knight doesn't feel too comfortable on f5 either.} Nf5 {With this move, we achieve our strategic objective of activating all our pieces. The last question that remains to be answered is our plan for g4 .} 15. g4 {White attacks the f5 -knight and, for a brief moment, it looks like our strategy has failed. The knight has no good squares to go to, and no, the g3 -square doesn't count. Fortunately, as often before, the counterplay on the other side of the board saves us.} a6 {This move comes just in time. On move 9, we provoked the knight to b5 , expecting its vulnerable position to provide us with counterplay. Now, attacking it will allow us to gain access to the d4 -square.} ({White will likely avoid the opening of the a-file, and Nc3} 15... Nfd4 {becomes the likely continuation. This will threaten the a4 -queen, not to mention the forever vulnerable e5 -pawn. After this, it is White who has to make sure of equality.}) *

