1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. h3 ({It is very natural for White to try to push the black knight back immediately. This line is quite similar to} 8. Bxd7+ {and it will be useful for you to compare the two.}) 8... cxd4 {Our reaction here is quite typical. Since h6 is not a great square for the black knight, we postpone moving there for as long as possible.} 9. Qxd4 ({It's the only capture that makes sense.} 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {transposes us to another line .}) 9... Bxb5 {Black has playable alternatives to this move, but it is quite nice to provoke the white knight to b5 , where it will be tactically vulnerable.} 10. Nxb5 {White certainly should take the bishop and not the knight. In a position about to open up, leaving Black with a bishop pair would be suicidal.} Nc6 {It's always pleasant to develop a piece with a gain of time. Please note that the g4 -knight deprives the white queen of some nice squares.} 11. Qe4 {As in many similar positions, staying in the center is the most natural way for White to proceed. The queen stays active and helps protect the e5 -pawn. The slight drawback of this plan is that the b5 -knight is vulnerable, and Black can use this to create counterplay.} Qb6 {Black uses the temporary weakness of the b5 -knight and the f2 -square, forcing White to take some defensive measures. As in many other lines in this opening, we fight for the initiative early on.} 12. hxg4 {This move wins a pawn, but with the king stuck in the center and almost all the pieces undeveloped, White shouldn't be grabbing material.} Qxb5 {It is useful to note that the black queen still prevents White from castling.} 13. exd6 {Well, at least White is consistent. Some players do like taking pawns, but opening the long diagonal and the e-file for the black pieces is really playing with fire.} O-O {With this move, we bring our king to safety and finish the piece development. White is still very far removed from being able to do the same and will have to defend precisely over the next few moves to survive the opening.} *

