1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. h3 ({It is very natural for White to try to push the black knight back immediately. This line is quite similar to} 8. Bxd7+ {and it will be useful for you to compare the two.}) 8... cxd4 {Our reaction here is quite typical. Since h6 is not a great square for the black knight, we postpone moving there for as long as possible.} 9. Qxd4 ({It's the only capture that makes sense.} 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {transposes us to another line .}) 9... Bxb5 {Black has playable alternatives to this move, but it is quite nice to provoke the white knight to b5 , where it will be tactically vulnerable.} 10. Nxb5 {White certainly should take the bishop and not the knight. In a position about to open up, leaving Black with a bishop pair would be suicidal.} Nc6 {It's always pleasant to develop a piece with a gain of time. Please note that the g4 -knight deprives the white queen of some nice squares.} 11. Qe4 {As in many similar positions, staying in the center is the most natural way for White to proceed. The queen stays active and helps protect the e5 -pawn. The slight drawback of this plan is that the b5 -knight is vulnerable, and Black can use this to create counterplay.} Qb6 {Black uses the temporary weakness of the b5 -knight and the f2 -square, forcing White to take some defensive measures. As in many other lines in this opening, we fight for the initiative early on.} 12. Qe2 {It is probably best for White to keep control and not to indulge in pawn-grabbing expeditions. The greedy alternative might well end in tears.} a6 {It is a really useful trick, here and in some other positions. The knight remains on g4 as long as possible to prevent White from playing Be3 with tempo.} 13. Na3 {We are in correspondence chess territory, so it's best to have a bit of faith. This move intends to bring the knight to c4 to kick the black queen back again. Once again, all the lines that involve White taking the d6 -pawn risk opening the e-file with bad consequences.} Nh6 {Having thoroughly exhausted all the tricks in the position, Black finally retreats the knight back to h6 . Far from passive, this knight eyes the f5 -square. White's next move is very natural, given that it is the continuation of the plan indicated by 13.Na3 .} 14. Nc4 {White attacks the black queen and defends the vital e5 -pawn at the same time. Furthermore, it is becoming increasingly obvious that the black queen will not stay on the a7 - g1 diagonal forever, and White will finally be able to castle.} Qd8 {The black queen returns to its natural square and, in this position, the only square that is safe from being continuously harassed by the white pieces. With the tactical skirmish over, we can now take some stock of the position.  Black has a healthy pawn structure and pieces on good squares, especially if the knight makes it to f5 . The king will be very safe on g8 . Once again, opening the e-file is very dangerous for White.} *

