1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. Bxd7+ ({The second most popular move, with} 8. e6 {being the critical continuation. White prefers not to engage in a complicated opening preparation and instead chooses a line that often leads to a more positional game. A slight drawback of this approach is that it doesn't cause many problems.}) 8... Qxd7 {As often before, we should take with the queen to cover the tactically vulnerable squares, e6 and g4 . Now, White has a choice between two very different systems.} 9. h3 {This move is quite possible, although it doesn't pose serious problems. We only have to know one line to get a decent position.} cxd4 {By counterattacking in the center, we gain some time before the knight has to retreat to h6 .} 10. Qxd4 {This recapture is the best by far. Taking on d4 with the knight would have left the e5 -pawn extremely vulnerable.} Nc6 {It's always pleasant to develop the knight with the gain of time. Keeping the knight on b8 for the time being is not entirely pointless, but if we can get a piece out for free, why shouldn't we?} 11. Qe4 {It is the most popular and natural retreat for the white queen. White keeps an eye on the e5 -pawn, and the queen is well-placed in the middle of the board.} Nh6 {Black caused some damage to White's structure in the middle of the board over the last few moves and finally found time to retreat the attacked piece. The h6 -knight can be quite a mixed blessing – it could either end up pretty bad after White plays g4 or could occupy a great spot on f5 . That's why the tactical details of the next few moves are important.} 12. g4 {This move is very typical for these positions. White tries to prevent the knight from entering the game. If they succeed in playing Bd2 and castling long, Black's position could easily become untenable. That's why the next move is essential.} Rd8 {In anticipation of White's plans, the black rook occupies a vital file. Now, Bd2 would blunder away a central pawn, and other moves are not threatening either. Black has a fair share of chances in the upcoming battle.} ({After Bd2} 12... dxe5 {O-O-O} 13. f5 $1 {, Black brings the h6 -knight into the game:} gxf5 {Nxf5 , or} 14. Qc4 {Nf7 , when the knight can slide to d6 if needed. The position is rather unusual, but Black is better nonetheless.}) *

