{This move is the point behind the tactical sequence that started with dxe5 . White cannot move the e5 -knight because the queen behind it is essentially hanging due to ... Bxc3 +. There are various ways for White to play this position, but all of those lead to Black having excellent prospects.  The b7 -pawn White can take is of little consequence at the moment. You will also notice that the e5 -bishop and the f5 -knight will occupy powerful squares. We have all the reasons to be happy about the opening outcome here.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. Bxd7+ ({The second most popular move, with} 8. e6 {being the critical continuation. White prefers not to engage in a complicated opening preparation and instead chooses a line that often leads to a more positional game. A slight drawback of this approach is that it doesn't cause many problems.}) 8... Qxd7 {As often before, we should take with the queen to cover the tactically vulnerable squares, e6 and g4 . Now, White has a choice between two very different systems.} 9. h3 {This move is quite possible, although it doesn't pose serious problems. We only have to know one line to get a decent position.} cxd4 {By counterattacking in the center, we gain some time before the knight has to retreat to h6 .} 10. Qxd4 {This recapture is the best by far. Taking on d4 with the knight would have left the e5 -pawn extremely vulnerable.} Nc6 {It's always pleasant to develop the knight with the gain of time. Keeping the knight on b8 for the time being is not entirely pointless, but if we can get a piece out for free, why shouldn't we?} 11. Qe4 {It is the most popular and natural retreat for the white queen. White keeps an eye on the e5 -pawn, and the queen is well-placed in the middle of the board.} Nh6 {Black caused some damage to White's structure in the middle of the board over the last few moves and finally found time to retreat the attacked piece. The h6 -knight can be quite a mixed blessing – it could either end up pretty bad after White plays g4 or could occupy a great spot on f5 . That's why the tactical details of the next few moves are important.} 12. Be3 {This move is White's most popular try. In anticipation of ... Nf5 , the white bishop is ready to fall back to f2 to cover the weak g3 -square. At the same time, White is getting ready to castle long.} Nf5 {The knight enters the game. We'll have to remember, of course, that it can be vulnerable to attacks with g4 . Fortunately, our plan has a tactical justification. Black has several safe alternatives to this move, but I like that it leads to a sharp, unbalanced position that gives us chances to win the game.} 13. Bf2 {It is the only move that makes any sense. Black was threatening ... Ng3 with decisive effect.} dxe5 {The beginning of a tactical sequence with a surprising twist. After ... dxe5 , it is important to pay attention to the fact that it is no longer legal for White to castle long. Throughout my life, the rules about castling have always been tricky for me. :)} 14. fxe5 {White recaptures the central pawn and renews the threat of g4 , pushing Black back to the 6th rank. The following tactical trick came as a surprise to me.} Nxe5 {Capturing the central pawn turns out to be possible, much to our delight. Not only does Black get the central pawn and open the long diagonal for the bishop, but the f5 -knight is also very happy about new squares, such as d6 , being available. Now we no longer have to worry about g4 .} 15. Nxe5 {White, of course, takes back, although by now Black's resource will no longer come as a surprise.} Qe6 *

