[GameId "2166551626555830"]

{It is not very often that this knight ends up on a6 in this line. As I mentioned before, the structure changed drastically after White played d5 , with the c6 -square no longer available. White has a lot of weaknesses in this position, the pawns d5 and g4 being the most prominent. Black will castle long and enjoy good prospects in the middlegame.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. Bxd7+ ({The second most popular move, with} 8. e6 {being the critical continuation. White prefers not to engage in a complicated opening preparation and instead chooses a line that often leads to a more positional game. A slight drawback of this approach is that it doesn't cause many problems.}) 8... Qxd7 {As often before, we should take with the queen to cover the tactically vulnerable squares, e6 and g4 . Now, White has a choice between two very different systems.} 9. d5 {This is the main line. White changes the nature of the position by moving the pawn away from d4 and controlling the c6 -square. We will talk more about the nuances of the position once the situation is clarified somewhat.} dxe5 {Our play here and over the next couple of moves is quite forced. We cannot let White have such a powerful pawn center and should address this immediately.} 10. h3 {This move is the point behind the pawn sacrifice. By attacking the g4 -knight, White tries to restore two pawns on the 5th rank, and it would be a most unwelcome outcome for Black. Fortunately, we have a nice strategic resource.} e4 {An elegant positional solution to our problems. Now, instead of two powerful pawns on the 5th rank, White will get long-term weaknesses in the center.} 11. hxg4 {I understand the visual appeal of opening the h-file, but we do need to acknowledge that there is no way that the black king is going to end up on the kingside. In the long term, White may very well regret having so many pawn weaknesses.} exf3 12. Qxf3 {This finishes the forced sequence. Black's next move is very important.} Na6 *

