1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 ({Moving on to the main line with} 5. Nf3 {.}) 5... c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 {This position is the very heart of the Austrian Attack and, in many ways, of the entire opening. It's also one of those lines that you have to know by heart since some of the complications are impossible to figure out over the board. But then again, no worries, it's nothing you cannot learn in half an hour. :)} Ng4 {This move is forced. The knight doesn't have other good squares and we're definitely not going back.} 8. Bxd7+ ({The second most popular move, with} 8. e6 {being the critical continuation. White prefers not to engage in a complicated opening preparation and instead chooses a line that often leads to a more positional game. A slight drawback of this approach is that it doesn't cause many problems.}) 8... Qxd7 {As often before, we should take with the queen to cover the tactically vulnerable squares, e6 and g4 . Now, White has a choice between two very different systems.} 9. d5 {This is the main line. White changes the nature of the position by moving the pawn away from d4 and controlling the c6 -square. We will talk more about the nuances of the position once the situation is clarified somewhat.} dxe5 {Our play here and over the next couple of moves is quite forced. We cannot let White have such a powerful pawn center and should address this immediately.} 10. h3 {This move is the point behind the pawn sacrifice. By attacking the g4 -knight, White tries to restore two pawns on the 5th rank, and it would be a most unwelcome outcome for Black. Fortunately, we have a nice strategic resource.} e4 {An elegant positional solution to our problems. Now, instead of two powerful pawns on the 5th rank, White will get long-term weaknesses in the center.} 11. Nxe4 {This simple capture is probably White's best bet. The alternative is sometimes played but leads to too many weaknesses for my taste.} Nf6 {The knight proudly returns to f6 , having caused some havoc in White's position. The double attack on e4 and d5 forces White to react.} 12. Nxf6+ ({The simplest, and also the best. White is not sufficiently developed to go for any pawn-grabbing expeditions.} 12. Ne5 Qd8 13. Nxf6+ exf6 $1 {This line shows that placing the knight on e5 can have its drawbacks.}) 12... Bxf6 {This bishop is very well-placed on the open diagonal, and there is no reason for us to consider the alternative capture.} 13. O-O {With nothing left to clarify in the center of the board, White finds the time to castle. Despite the broken-looking structure on the kingside, the white king is actually quite safe.} O-O {The black king also finds a haven on the kingside. With play having calmed down a lot, maybe we could talk a bit about the strategic aspects of this position. Both sides have a solid position without major weaknesses and will have no problems finishing the development.  White has a bit more space, but the space also comes with the responsibility to defend it, especially the d5 -pawn that requires constant attention. We are already used to the f4 -pawn blocking the white bishop. White has tried many directions here in tournament practice, and I will mention a few.} 14. Ne5 {A very natural move, but as we have seen a couple of times already, this knight can also become a target.} Qd6 {The queen keeps an eye on both the e5 -knight and the d5 -pawn. Black is quite happy having freed the d7 -square for the knight.} *

