{This is a blitz game by Magnus Carlsen. We don't often try to learn from blitz games, but again, it's Magnus Carlsen. :)} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 d6 3. Nc3 c6 4. Be3 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 ({It's not our main move, just a reminder.} 5... Bg7 {is one of our main positions .}) 6. Bd3 ({The bishop is rarely great on d3 . Other lines would have been more challenging.} 6. e5 $5 Ng4 7. Bd2 dxe5 8. h3 e4 9. hxg4 exf3 10. Qxf3 {and White should be better here.}) 6... Bg7 7. h3 e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qd2 Qe7 {Getting the knight to c5 is vital in Black's fight for the strategic initiative.} 10. O-O-O {White castles into trouble. The king would have been safer on g1 .} Nc5 11. Bh6 {Trading these bishops doesn't help White. In general, Bh6 only works if White is attacking. Otherwise, the dark-squared bishop is sorely missed in the fight for central squares, such as c5 , d4 , and f4 .} O-O 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. h4 {There is no attack. The pawn had the task of controlling the g4 -square.} Bg4 {Black immediately uses the new situation. The bishop exerts a lot of pressure from here.} 14. Qe3 b5 {We have seen this motive, expanding on the queenside, many times throughout this course.} 15. Kb1 a5 16. Ne2 a4 17. Nh2 {White's position was already beyond repair.} Bxe2 {There will be no need for this bishop in the attack to come.} 18. Bxe2 (18. Qxe2 {keeps the pawn but doesn't change the evaluation:} a3 19. b3 Rfd8 {.}) 18... a3 19. b3 Ncxe4 20. Bf3 Nd5 {It's the game. The rest is agony.} 21. Rxd5 cxd5 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. h5 f5 24. Ng4 fxg4 25. hxg6 h5 26. Rxh5 Rh8 27. Rh7+ Rxh7 28. gxh7 Rd8 29. Kc1 Kh8 30. c3 Qd6 31. Qxe4 Qd1# *

