1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 Nf6 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6 Bxh6 7. Qxh6 e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nf3 Qe7 10. Bc4 b5 11. Bb3 Na6 {A decent alternative to the move we considered in this course. These two moves usually lead to the same position around move 15.} (11... Nbd7 {is our main move.} 12. Ng5 Rf8 13. Nxh7 Nxh7 14. Qxh7 a5 {is where we left things in the theoretical part of this course. Let's look at some possible lines.} 15. a3 (15. a4 b4 {( Qg5!? could be very confusing fo White.} 16. h4 {Qxg2 O-O-O b4 Nb1} Ba6 {looks very messy. )} 17. Nb1 {Ba6 Nd2} O-O-O {O-O-O Nc5 and Black has a very strong position for a tiny material deficit.}) 15... Nc5 16. Qh6 {, we transpose into our model game here. The lines with ... Nbd7 and ... Na5 finally become one. :) And if O-O} Qg5 {, the white queen should start getting nervous around here.}) 12. Ng5 Rf8 13. Nxh7 Nxh7 14. Qxh7 Nc5 15. Qh6 a5 16. a3 Be6 {It's a very positional way of playing a pawn-down position. Black keeps a strong knight and prepares to castle queenside.} 17. Bxe6 Nxe6 18. Qe3 (18. O-O-O b4 {could get tricky for White. , and if O-O Nd4 , this knight is a monster.}) 18... O-O-O (18... Nd4 19. Rc1 O-O-O 20. Ne2) 19. Qb6 {White is in time to cause enough trouble to force an exchange of queens. White's position would get dangerous if Black could comfortably play ... Nf4 .} Qc7 {Black's position is so strong that there is enough compensation even with the queens off.} 20. Qxc7+ Kxc7 21. Rd1 b4 22. axb4 axb4 23. Ne2 Nc5 (23... c5 $5) 24. f3 b3 {After the immaculate play by both sides – it's a correspondence game, after all – everything ends with a well-deserved draw.} 25. Rd2 bxc2 26. Nc1 Ne6 27. Rxc2 Rd4 28. Ne2 Rb4 29. Kf2 Rfb8 30. Rhc1 c5 31. Rb1 Kd6 32. Nc3 Nd4 33. Rd2 Ke6 {In a real tournament game, Black might still have an easier task here. I hope you were not too impressed by White's extra pawn – it didn't have much effect on the game.} *

