1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 c6 5. Qd2 b5 6. Bd3 Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. h3 Nbd7 9. O-O {We jump in here. It's a rapid game, and I guess I'm one of the few people who still remember it. It is far from flawless, yet very instructive as an example of how wrong things can go for White in the Pirc.} e5 ({Black doesn't have to play this thematic move at once and could develop some more pieces first:} 9... Qc7 $5 {or Bb7!? .}) 10. dxe5 {A good moment for this exchange, with the black queenside somewhat vulnerable.} dxe5 ({Surprisingly, it's a mistake. The c8 -bishop would appreciate some air, and that's why Black is better off exchanging the knights:} 10... Nxe5 $1 11. Nxe5 dxe5 {.}) 11. Ne2 (11. a4 {is the most thematic approach. Black can't avoid some weakening now:} b4 12. Ne2 a5 13. c3 c5 14. Rfd1 {.}) 11... a6 12. a4 Bb7 13. Ng3 Qe7 {So far, Peter has handled the opening extremely well. The next move loses the thread, though.} 14. Bh6 {The positional mistake we've also seen in Bilguun-Carlsen. White only profits from trading the bishops if there is a prospect of an attack. Here, there are none.} (14. c4 $1 {is the way to exert pressure on Black's queenside. Maybe Peter missed the tactical detail that follows.} bxa4 15. c5 $1 {This trick is well-known from similar positions. Black is in big trouble now. ( Rxa4 c5∞ )} Nxc5 $2 16. Qb4 {.}) 14... Rfe8 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Black is fine now.} 16. b4 Rad8 17. Rfe1 Nb6 18. Qg5 Kh8 19. axb5 cxb5 {White didn't do anything wrong after playing Bh6 , yet Black's position seems a tad stronger. White has to take care of the queenside.} 20. Nd2 (20. Reb1 $5) 20... Rd4 21. Qe3 Na4 22. Nf3 ({This move already looks like panic. The correct defense was really difficult. After} 22. Bf1 $1 Rxb4 23. c4 {, White probably generates enough play here to save the game.}) 22... Rxb4 23. Qg5 Nc5 24. Nd2 Nd5 {Black is winning now. The rest is agony.} 25. Qh6 Nf4 26. Bf1 f6 27. c4 Rb2 28. Nf3 b4 29. Rad1 a5 30. Ne2 Nfd3 {Ivanchuk's positional feeling is one of the great gifts to the chess world. Believe me, it is far from easy to convert this convincingly. And if this can happen to Peter Leko with the white pieces, then it can definitely happen to your opponent.} *

