1. e4 d6 {Not sure if many players remember this game. Bobby Fischer played the Pirc in a World Championship match in 1972, a testimony to the faith he had in the opening.} 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. Bd3 Qxc5 8. Qe2 O-O 9. Be3 Qa5 10. O-O Bg4 11. Rad1 Nc6 {The moves were quite standard until this point. White has to decide on a plan.} 12. Bc4 {White tries to go for activity and sets a nasty trap as well.} Nh5 (12... Qb4 $2 {It is really not easy to see that the b2 -pawn is poisonous.} 13. a3 $1 Qxb2 14. Na4 Qxa3 15. Ra1 Qb4 16. Bd2 Nd4 17. Qd3 {and Black runs out of tricks. The queen is trapped and lost.}) 13. Bb3 (13. Rd5 {, I think this move was suggested as an improvement by some commentators back in the day. It doesn't endanger Black either.} Qc7 14. Bb3 {( Rg5} Nd4 $1 {) Na5 and White loses most of their attacking potential after a series of exchanges.}) 13... Bxc3 {A most daring approach. Black has faith in pawns and healthy structures.} 14. bxc3 Qxc3 15. f5 Nf6 16. h3 (16. Bh6 Ne5 $1 {What a great positional sacrifice. White's attack runs out of steam:} 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 {.}) 16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Na5 {The light-squared bishop is potentially dangerous.} (17... Qe5 $5 {is interesting, but Ne5 is very natural and yet wrong. These things happen. :)} 18. Qf4 $1 {and White's attack can quickly become deadly here.}) 18. Rd3 Qc7 19. Bh6 Nxb3 20. cxb3 (20. Bxf8 Nc5) 20... Qc5+ 21. Kh1 Qe5 {I like this moment. There was nothing wrong with moving the f8 -rook, but White would still keep some attacking chances. Fischer sacrifices the exchange and builds a rock of a position. Spassky doesn't make his rooks count in the remainder of this game.} (21... Rfc8 22. Bg5 Qe5) 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Re3 Rc8 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. Qf4 Qxf4 26. Rxf4 Nd7 (26... d5 27. e5 Ne4) 27. Rf2 Ne5 28. Kh2 Rc1 {The rest of the game is Fischer enjoying the solidity of his position. Making a confident draw with Black might not seem like much, but everything feels different in the final stages of the World Championship.} 29. Ree2 Nc6 30. Rc2 Re1 31. Rfe2 Ra1 32. Kg3 Kg7 33. Rcd2 Rf1 34. Rf2 Re1 35. Rfe2 Rf1 36. Re3 a6 37. Rc3 Re1 38. Rc4 Rf1 39. Rdc2 Ra1 40. Rf2 Re1 41. Rfc2 g5 42. Rc1 Re2 43. R1c2 Re1 44. Rc1 Re2 45. R1c2 *

