1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. e5 Ng4 8. e6 fxe6 9. Ng5 Bxb5 10. Qxg4 {It's not the most critical continuation, but to be fair, these were very early days for this line. This game was one of those to show the long-term potential of Black's setup.} Bc4 11. b3 Bxd4 12. Bd2 Bd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 {After a short tactical sequence, we can discern the outlines of the upcoming battle. White hopes to use the fact that the black king is stuck in the center. Black has an impressive mass of central pawns. In this particular case, the pawns rule. :)} 14. O-O-O ({Maybe} 14. Ne6 {was a better try.} Qc8 15. c3 Bf6 16. O-O Nc6 17. Rae1 d4 {with a tough fight.}) 14... Nc6 15. Qe6 {It's a tempting sortie, but White's threats aren't as strong as they seem.} Qc8 16. Qf7+ Kd7 17. Qxd5 Qg8 {Perfect timing. For the second time in this game, Black controls vital squares along the a2 - g8 diagonal.} 18. Qxg8 {White is winning back the pawn, although the white and black pawns are of different quality here.} (18. Qf3 h6 19. Qh3+ Kc7 20. Ne6+ Kb8) 18... Rhxg8 19. Nxh7 b5 20. Ng5 b4 (20... a5 $5) 21. Rhe1 a5 22. Ne6 {The last few moves were all natural and logical. Now, Black has to decide whether to keep the d4 -bishop or not.} a4 ({Maybe} 22... Bf6 $1 {would be easier for Black. White has no tactics on the d-file, and Black proceeds with ... a4 , crushing through. The move that Yasser played in the game is also good but much more complex.}) 23. Nxd4 Nxd4 {Underestimating Black's potential.} (23... cxd4 $1 {The central pawns are very powerful. The following line is a demonstration of what's possible when analyzing with a computer.} 24. Kb1 Ra5 $1 25. Bc1 Rh5 26. h3 a3 $1 27. Rd3 e5 28. Bd2 Re8 29. fxe5 dxe5 {and Black has a winning advantage here.}) 24. Bxb4 {Now it looks like a draw. The rest was pretty clean and of no particular interest to us. :)} axb3 25. axb3 Nxb3+ 26. cxb3 cxb4 27. Kb2 g5 28. f5 Ra5 29. Ra1 Rxf5 30. Ra7+ Kc6 31. Raxe7 Rf2+ 32. R1e2 Rgf8 33. Kc2 Rxe2+ 34. Rxe2 d5 35. Kd3 Kd6 36. Ra2 Ke5 37. Re2+ Kd6 38. Ra2 Rf1 39. Ra6+ Ke5 40. Rg6 Kf5 41. Rd6 Ke5 42. Rg6 Kf5 *

[Event "?"]
