1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. Nf3 c6 6. Qd2 O-O 7. Bh6 b5 8. Bd3 Bg4 9. h4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nh5 {In the theoretical part dealing with Be3 lines, I promised to show you some of the analysis behind the moves. To show you that some work indeed has been done. :)} 11. Ne2 (11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. f4 {( O-O-O} e5 $1 {) Nd7} 13. O-O-O (13. Be2 b4 $1 14. Nd1 {Ndf6 e5 Nd5 Bxh5 gxh5 Ne3 dxe5 fxe5} Kh8 {O-O-O a5 , this line is a mess. The black king is much safer than it looks.}) 13... Qa5 14. Kb1 {e5! Black fights for the center, even at the cost of a pawn. dxe5} (14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Be2 b4 16. Nb5 $5 cxb5 17. Bxh5 {Rad8 Be2 Nf6∞}) ({dxe5 Bxb5 Nb6! Bxc6 Nc4 Qd5 Qd3 Nxb2 Kxb2 Rab8+} 14. Nxb5 Rc8 {begins to look very risky for White.}) 14... Qb4 15. b3 Qxc3 {Qxc4 Qxc4 bxc4 Rab8+} 16. Kc1 Nxf4 {and White's pawns are so weak that Black should easily have enough play here. My computer agrees. :)}) 11... Qb6 12. O-O-O Nd7 13. Rdg1 c5 {I was very proud to discover this. It's not only new, it also works!} 14. Bxg7 (14. Ng3 Nxg3 15. Rxg3 c4 16. Bxg7 {leads to the same position as our main line.}) (14. Nc3 {is a slightly strange move. Black has many playable replies.} Qa5 $5 (14... cxd4 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qg5 Kh8 18. Qxe7 Qxe7 19. Nxe7 Ne5 {, or} 20. c4 {.}) 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Bxb5 Rab8 18. Bc4 Rfc8 {.}) 14... Kxg7 15. Ng3 Nxg3 16. Rxg3 c4 17. Be2 (17. Bf1 {, I don't see the point behind this move:} e5 {.}) 17... e5 18. h5 Qxd4 19. Qg5 {White seems to have a strong attack, but we have a solution.} h6 20. Qe7 (20. Qf5 g5 $1 {Same idea here.}) 20... g5 21. Rd1 (21. Qxd7 $2 Qxf2 {, and if} 22. Rhg1 {Qxf2 Rxg5+} Kh8 $1 {R5g2 Qe3+} 23. Kb1 Rg8 {.}) 21... Qxf2 22. Rxg5+ Kh8 (22... hxg5 23. Qxg5+ Kh8 24. Rxd6) 23. Rf5 (23. Rgg1 Rad8 24. Qxd6 Kh7 {, this mess can get very difficult for White to navigate:} 25. Rg6 $5 Qe3+ $1 26. Kb1 Nc5 27. Qxe5 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 Ne6 {.}) 23... Qe3+ 24. Kb1 Qxe2 25. Qxd6 f6 26. Qxd7 Rad8 27. Qxd8 Rxd8 28. Rxd8+ Kg7 {This ending looks complicated, but in fact, it's probably White who is lucky not to be losing here. With the f5 -rook offside, Black's attack could also be decisive, right?} 29. a3 Qe1+ 30. Ka2 c3 31. Rd7+ Kg8 32. Rxf6 Qc1 {This is one of many lines with a draw at the end.} *

